This little bumpkin is only 9 pounds.  His owner passed away, and he found himself with CHR in the hopes of finding a new home.

Leo is charming and will seek out attention from his pet parents.  His past parents were worried that a hawk might swoop down and take Ling while out on a potty break outside, so they chose only to use pee pads for elimination breaks. Leo's current foster sits outside with the dogs to make sure they potty outside because they will often run inside the house and pee even after being let outside for a potty break. To avoid accidents, Leo's foster mom keeps a belly band on him.   

Because the two pups were littermates, we are hoping to adopt them together for the reduced adoption fee of $700.
Having a fenced yard is ideal for these sweeties for their new potty training regimen.  
Also, they don’t like doing stairs, so keep this in mind if you have long stairways leading out of your home because that would be a problem for them.      

Leo can be barky and snappy at dogs he does not know so we would like them to go to a home without other pets. 
 
Leo did fine at the grooming shop and behaved nicely on car rides.  He’s a very gentle baby boy.

animal.description:
You will never meet a dog quite like Rusty.
He is soft and cuddly, but don't ever let him hear you say that because when you first meet him he will pretend not to like you and act as tough as he can. In reality he is a very insecure dog who puts on a front to keep people away. It takes time, but once you gain his trust he becomes sweet and full of personality. 
He will always have a strong personality and think he is king of the castle so he would need someone with very good dog skills and who can understand him. It is a long process, but so worth the journey.
He can live with other dogs, but is very selective who he shares his home with and would likely have to live in a managed home of some kind. Don't let all this fool you because beneath his tough guy exterior lies a sweet, silly little guy who, once he let's his guard down, would make a great companion. He does require relationship building and multiple visits so he would need a patient and understanding person.

animal.description:
This sweet girl is Nala. She is sweet, beautiful, and deaf. Nala understands commands via hand signals. She is spayed, vaccinated, microchipped, and potty trained. Easy to walk on leash and full of affection! Nala is 4 years old. We believe she was born deaf but we don't know for sure. She became available because her original owner left the state and his job did not allow enough time for her (12 plus hour wok days). Nala knows the following commands by hand signal: Shake, Sit, Down and Stay. She is fully potty trained and barks at the door to let you know she needs to potty. She has never lived with children so an adult only home is best for her. Her ideal setting would be a house with no other pets.  She is easy to walk on leash and has a low to medium energy level.  If interested, please send an email with details about your experience owing pets, your household and where you currently reside (just to know how close you are to our foster home).  Nala plays well with other dogs, however she is food aggressive (not with humans just with dogs) so that is why we are suggesting her as an only pet.  She would be a great human companion.

Thank you!
lovehabitatrescue@live.com

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Please contact Tracey (traceysl@tarasdream.org) for more information about this pet.

Email T.A.R.A. | T.A.R.A.'s Web Site | On-Line Application

Hello! My name is Callie Sue, and I'm looking for my forever home! I thought I'd give you an update on myself since I've been with my foster family for a bit, and have learned so much. I may not have had the best start to my short life, but I'm learning people and other dogs are nice to have in my life. After living with a family, in a house, and with other dogs, I'm learning to trust. I am still easily startled with loud sounds or quick movements, but I recover much faster and instead of continuing to run and hide, I will now come back and investigate. I am now fully housetrained, and have gone several weeks without an accident! I'm a pretty smart girl. My foster family has 2 other dogs that I live with, and let me tell you- they have taught me so much about what being a dog is all about! I now play with them, and with toys, and act silly and even get the zoomies! I still like to eat in a quieter place, away from any possible interruptions, but it's okay my foster family doesn't mind that I prefer to eat in the living room while everyone else is in the kitchen. I am still a little cautious of new people, but if you just go slow, and give me a minute to figure it out, I promise I will give you all the love. My foster family has been so great in giving me time to get comfortable with everyone. I still tend to trust females faster than males, but if I do come around if you just keep showing me it's okay. My foster mom says the best forever home for me would be a family with older children for now. Because I still startle so easily, it's probably still best that my forever family not have quick moving young children. I won't hurt them, I'll just always be running away from them. It would also be best for my home to have another dog that I can look to for guidance. I do like running and playing with other dogs and I really look to them to show me how to be a dog. I am still working on my basic commands, my foster family had to start at the beginning- just realizing that I could take a treat from their hand. I'm getting it, we're just making baby steps. My foster family has noticed that with my increased confidence that I have quite a prey drive. This means I LOVE chasing the bunnies and squirrels, I will hunt for them even when they get out of the yard. This may mean, I may not be the best dog to live with a kitty friend, but I haven't met one yet, so I don't know for sure. I am also rather athletic and have some serious hops. I tend to jump fences (especially those short ones) when I get nervous. The more comfortable I've become in my own yard, the less I've made an attempt to jump. Finally, once I've learned to trust my humans, I get a little worried when they aren't around. I would love a family that would be around most of the time. If I do need to stay at home without you- it helps if you can leave me with something to keep my mind off of things. My favorite treat is a kong stuffed full of yummy things that my foster mom freezes. Man I can that will keep me busy for a good long while. If you think you're family would love to give a shy, sweet girl like myself a forever home- please reach out to these amazing people at T.A.R.A and ask more about me, Callie Sue! I'm learning so much everyday and I've come so far in such a short time. I may be the perfect fit for your family and you'll never know if you don't ask about me.

Approximate Birthdate: April 2018

Adoption Fee: $150.00

TARA's adoption fee includes: spay/neuter, age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, heartworm test (if age appropriate), heartworm and flea prevention, and deworming. TARA's pets are all eligible for a

two week trial

.

animal.description: Jessie is one of those dogs who will be your BFF no matter what. She bonds with her family and is very loving and loyal with her foster mom and her young daughter. She can be a little reserved with strangers but once she knows you, you have a loyal, steadfast companion for life. Still a young girl at about 2 years of age, this Shepherd, Lab and a mix of possibly a couple other breeds is a very well mannered girl. Jessie spent time with our trainer and quickly learned her basic obedience skills and will respond to her commands quickly. She aims to please but is not up in your face about it. She sleeps through the night and is house trained in her foster home with access to the yard. Jessie is just easy going and will go with the flow observing from afar. She can be your at home work partner because you will hardly know she is in the room while you work away or jump on your Zoom calls. Jessie is wonderful on walks and needs just a walk or two a day to be happy. She is non reactive on her leash when you see people or other dogs which makes your walks relaxing. Jessie loves her 9 year old human foster sister; they play soccer with the neighborhood kids and Jessie is the star! While most of her time is spent lounging, when her playful side comes out, she loves to play with anything - catch, chase and tug of war. She would do best in a home with kids over the age of 6, just due to her size. While she has made a few dog friends through patient intros with her foster family, Jessie can be a little reserved and choosy with other dogs and will need to be the only dog in her forever home. She also thinks kitties should be chased and will need a home without cats. She is a wonderful girl and will do great in a home with a kind and easy going family. If you're interested in meeting Jessie, your first step is completing an adoption application on our website. If you've adopted from us before or are already approved to adopt, reach out to your adoption coach for next steps. This information is as up to date and accurate as possible for the dog in its current environment. All dogs and puppies will need time and training to adjust to their new surroundings and to learn the rules of their new home. If you are interested in meeting one of our dogs, the first step is to complete the Adoption Form on our website at www.labsandmore.org and take some time to review our adoption process. Your adoption includes the spay or neuter, current vaccinations, microchip, and other services provided while in our care. The safety and health of our puppies is priority one, so we only allow approved applicants to meet and handle puppies. Please understand everything we do is for the dogs and conducted by our kind and generous volunteers. We rely solely on donations, and we do not profit from a dog's adoption. Labs and More is a 501(c)3 non-profit organization that operates on donations and time dedicated to this cause by volunteers. Your adoption will save the life of future dogs in need. Labs and More makes no guarantees regarding the behavior, breed, or age of the dogs in our care. Although we strive to provide necessary medical care to dogs in our care, we cannot predict future or current medical needs whether they were symptomatic or not at the time of adoption.Thank you for looking to Adopt a Labrador Retriever or other Mixed Breed Dog from California Labradors Retrievers and More Rescue. Please take a moment and go to www.labsandmore.org and click on Adopt to complete our online dog adoption application. If you have any questions email us at doginfo@labsandmore.org or call us at 858-273-5386. Thank you for looking to a rescue group to fulfill your dream of adding a new dog to your life! Dogs + Love = Family

animal.description:
This beautiful lady is Ebony!  She's a 4 year old Cane Corso and weighs in at 106 pounds. Ebony is super lovable, fun-loving, playful, and she has this adorable sassy attitude (in a fun way).  Ebony has so many wonderful qualities, but she is also incredibly strong, so she requires an owner with large breed experience.  She'd also prefer to have a large fenced-in yard to play in. 

Due to Ebony's strength and the fact that she can startle easily at times, we are requesting she go to a home with no kids under the age of 16 years old.  She doesn't appear to be a fan of other dogs, though they don't phase her on walks.  Not sure how she'd do with kitty cats.  

Ebony has a history of a previously fractured leg which is now completely healed.   Ebony LOVES walks, and she does  well on the leash - though occasionally she thinks it's a toy.  Her friend also tells us that she's excellent riding in the car. 

If you are interested in this beautiful gal, apply today!  Her minimum adoption fee is $275 plus a $12 fee, if 4 months or older, for rabies registration for McLean County residents.

She has been spayed, microchipped, vaccinated, heartworm checked, dewormed, and is on flea and heartworm preventatives.

For information about this dog's breed(s), visit: http://www.dogbreedinfo.com/abc.htm 

To fill out our adoption application, go to: http://fs16.formsite.com/WishBoneCanineRescue/adoptionapplication/index.html

Lily is a strong gal with a large personality. Not only is Lily a goofball with an active spirit, she is also a gentle sweetie who loves to snuggle, be prepared to have a 80 pound lap dog!
Lily's smile can light up a room and even though she can't hear, she leaves an impression on everyone who meets her. 
Lily is Deaf.
She is looking for a dog experienced household that is able to continue her sign language and basic obedience training. Lily has learned so much while at CHS which only proves what a determined and smart this gal is.
Lily would do best in a home without young children or other pets. 
She is a big girl who loves to play, which can be too much for some children and pets. Lily is dog social and would really enjoy going for walks with other pups, but her off leash play style can come across as too much for other dogs. Please feel free to call CHS Staff for more information.

animal.description:
Meet Maddie! She’s a little over a year old and around 50lbs. Maddie had a rough start to life, found emaciated and too weak to move on the side of the road. Luckily she received the care she needed at the shelter. Unfortunately with such a traumatic start to life, Maddie is very fearful of new people. Maddie has been fully vetted and has been living in a foster home for around 6 months. 

Maddie is looking for a very specific type of home due to her fear. She’s made progress with socializing and will continue to in the right home, but will need a very patient, quiet, routine place. Her adopter should have plenty of previous dog/training/behavior experience. Maddie seems to bond more easily with women, men are more “scary” and she will bark/growl when unsure. She is working on potty training, is crate trained and knows commands like sit, down, place & stay. Once she trusts you she loves you completely! Maddie walks well on a leash, although with her fearfulness she enjoys walking in more remote, quiet areas at this time. Maddie enjoys running and playing in her fenced yard as well and a fenced yard is a requirement for her new home due to her fear. She would not be a good fit for apartment life or a busy neighborhood. She has a medium energy level and would benefit from continued training with her family. Maddie does well with most other dogs but would do best in a home without cats or kids. She is fully vetted, her adoption fee is $200.

Are you Maddie’s unicorn adopter? Visit www.fetchmihome.com/adopt to fill out an application or email fetchmihome@gmail.com to ask questions!

animal.description:
Meet Madison
Madison is one of the friendliest dogs we’ve met in a long time. We rescued Madison from a high-kill shelter and since arriving on April 10, 2020 she’s quickly become a shelter favorite. She has a joy for living and she’d love nothing better than belonging to a family who loves her. 
Madison is about 1 1/2 years old and currently weighs 51 pounds. She’s thought to be a retriever mix. She’s a bigger pup, tall and lanky with a beautiful, angora-soft golden brown coat. We’re not sure what this young pup has gone through in life, but she seems afraid of other dogs and will give chase to cats. She's also terrified of children and will shut down, but she LOVES people. She welcomes attention for adults and will happily sit with her person. She is an active girl and an active lifestyle would suit her best. She’s learning to walk on a leash and she knows how to sit already. Madison is being showered with affection and kindness and every day she grows a little more confident in the scary and noisy shelter. If you’re looking for a terrific young dog to welcome as your best companion and make part of your activities, Madison may be the girl for you.
Call 706-865-4135 for information on additional health services provided as part of the adoption fee.  If interested in one of our puppies or dogs, please submit an application online or at the shelter. Applications can be submitted online at: https://www.charlessmithgallhumanesociety.org/page/dog-adoption-application 
Once an application is submitted online, you will receive an email saying your application has been successfully submitted.  If you don’t receive this email within 24 hours, please check to make sure all application fields were completed or please call our shelter at 706-865-4135. All adopters must complete an approval process which involves a reference check with current/recent vet and a brief home visit if located in the immediate area. We do permit out of state adoptions. Adopters MUST come to the shelter to transport their new family member home. We do not ship nor do we transport them to their new homes. Adoption policies and application procedures are detailed at the shelter website: http://smithgallhumanesociety.org/ under tab All Adoptable Animals.
Charles Smithgall Humane Society (CSHS) is a No kill shelter. Animals in our care remain safe with us until adopted. Resident animals are primarily owner relinquished and also accepted from local Animal Control. The facility usually is operating at capacity with a list of animals waiting for space to open.
Adoptions and meet and greets are being scheduled by appointment only. Please call our office, email us or complete an application and someone will be in touch just as soon as they can. 
Location: 4823 Helen Hwy. 75N, Sautee, GA 30571, Phone: 706-865-4135
Email: smithgallhumanesociety@windstream.net
Our shelter in Sautee GA is located about 3 miles south of the alpine town of Helen in northeast GA.

animal.description: Grayson is an incredibly handsome dog with some of the softest bunny fur you've ever felt, but this active pup prefers you not dwell on his good looks or how adorable he is - he's way too busy for all that. But if you're looking for a running sidekick or someone to help you stay active, Grayson's got you covered. This energetic pup can run fast and far, and he'd love to be your trail buddy! This lovable lad is a survivor of Hurricane Harvey, and he came to Austin with some medical issues - distemper, some seizures and skin problems. He will need medications for life, but he has not let it get him down. In fact, Grayson has found a new leash on life, and he wants to share his endless joy with his humans! He has boundless energy, and he's not picky how he gets it out. He loves any activity you can throw his way - running, hiking - whatever he can do to keep moving, because this boy's got energy to burn. If you're looking for a fun playmate, Grayson is more than up for that, too. Grayson is really stoked that toys exist; he knows where the toy chest is and he can barely wait for you to pull out a trinket. If he had to pick a favorite, he'd probably say anything he can fetch. He will sit and wait for you to throw the ball, or if you're the one sitting, he'll drop a toy in your lap until you get the picture that he's waiting patiently for you to throw something. He also likes to play tug of war, but if playing with his human isn't an option, he'll pick out a toy to chew on and keep himself entertained. Grayson would love an active home with a yard and a family with older children who can handle his rambunctious nature. He's giddy when he sees kids, and seems to know they'd make great playmates. If you think you can handle an adorable bundle of energy, come meet Grayson!

animal.description:
OBI WAN is a 3 yr old hound mix.  Obi has a laid back personality.    He likes to chase squirrels and be outside during the day. He sometimes plays with other dogs but mostly he’s a great napper!  Yep, look up the definition of “porch dog” and there’s probably a photo of Obi!    Obi gets a bit territorial around his food bowl & he’s not a big fan of  unfamiliar dogs or humans, but when properly introduced, he is an amazing companion!      ObieWan is somewhat of a dog with a cat soul.  He’s not gonna crawl up for a snuggle but when HE wants some lovin’ & cuddles, ITs on!     He’s a bit afraid of thunderstorms and still thinks he’s about a 10 pound puppy when he climbs up into your lap.     Obie Wan will make some lucky family a precious pet!    

All our adoption fees include spay/neuter, micro-chip, up-to-date vaccinations, including rabies thru date of adoption. This pup tested heartworm negative, and is on regular monthly heartworm prevention & on flea/tick prevention. 

In order to be considered for one of our beautiful pups, please go to our website and complete and application: https://www.mustluvdogs.org/adoptable-pets.
Please note that we are a DUE DILIGENCE adoption organization. Part of our approval process requires, among other things:
* Experienced pet home with verifiable vet references/history preferred, but we realize that everyone has to start somewhere, so all applications will be considered.
*The majority, but not all, of our pets require a fenced yard or secure enclosure.  In the case of apartments, we require Landlord approval and designated dog area in complex.
*Verifiable good veterinary history INCLUDING regular vaccination/visits and good Heartworm Prevention history is a MUST!
*Adopter must be able to have time to spend with the pup and be able to provide the pup a safe environment to live.
*ALL our dogs are expected to be primarily INSIDE dogs.  They MUST sleep inside the home.  We truly understand that some folks have working dogs (i.e. farmers, ranchers,etc); however, the majority of our dogs have had a rough life prior to coming to us & we want to make sure that they are showered with LUV & maybe even a bit spoiled for the rest of their lives. 

Other facts are also considered, including whether children or other pets are a good fit with the dog. 

Must Luv Dogs reserves the right to deny any applications that we don't think are a good fit with the pup. Our first & foremost concern is the dog's best interest. It is our MISSION to place them in a home that is a great fit for their needs for a lifetime of luv & being part of a family.
*We will consider adoptions in any area; however, will do not ship or transport puppies under the age of 12 mos. We will ONLY transport an adult dog on a transport approved by MLD, at adopter's expense.
* In order to be affordable and afford every family an opportunity to have a pup of their own, we keep our Adoption Fees low; however, please keep in mind that the fees we charge do not cover all costs for the pup.  Any additional donations are greatly appreciated!

Please note that all of our pets are in private foster homes. In order to reduce any stress or confusion for our pups, we require a completed, approved application BEFORE setting up a meet & greet for any of our pups.  Alternatively, you are always welcome to come meet any of our pups at one of our regular Adoption Events.   Our events are always posted on PetFinder OR on our Facebook page: https://www.facebook.com/mustLUVdogs.org.

Finally, THANK YOU for considering Must Luv Dogs for your next pet. 

*Most dogs require a fenced area in yard. 
*Apartments okay IF nearby dog park or walking trails (with landlord appoval).
*ALL dogs must be INSIDE dogs and treated a part of family. 
*We are a DUE DILIGENCE Adoption Rescue.  
*Must have good Vet history & Heartworm prevention is a MUST!
*ALL dogs are fully vetted, spay/neutered and microchipped prior to adoption.

FYI:   Even though this pup tested heartworm negative, we provide the following procedural information for your information:  Any of our pups who test HW+ are treated with the *slow kill method of treatment.   The *slow-kill method, simply stated, is a 30 day regiment of  doxycycline followed by a monthly dose of Advantage Multi for 12 months, then retesting.   Most dogs test negative after one year of following this treatment; however, we always recommend that potential adopters consult & follow the advice of their family veterinarian upon adopting any of our hw+ pups.   Although the fast-kill method is still considered the "gold-standard" by the AVA, and may be preferred by some vets; the slow-kill method has proven to be effective in our rescue. The main reason we utilize this method is due to our limited financial constraints and the high number of our rescue pups that are infected.   In the cases of severe infection and if the pup is highly symptomatic, we sometimes use the fast-kill approach instead.   Again, we recommend for you to consult with your veterinarian after the adoption is complete and follow their recommendations.

animal.description:
ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS
Fenced yard
Canine sibling

Imagine being tied to a piece of rebar with only a few inches to move and being left there in the rain. Pretty sad, right? Well that's what happened to me. I am very lucky that someone saw me and came for me. I was there all day by myself wondering how I was going to get out of that mess. I was then taken to animal control where I spent several days waiting to see if someone would come for me a 2nd time. That didn't happen.
My name is Floyd and I am look for a new family. I love to play with the other dogs in my foster home and I am a lovable lap dog in spite of what I have been thru. My foster mom says I am a big ole teddy bear. I have 4 kids in my foster home and I love playing with them but I also love being a couch potato so don't let my size scare you off. I love my new toys and my bed. I am crate trained and housebroken. I know a few commands and would like to learn more. My only vice is I am not a fan of cats. I probably wouldn't hurt them but they seem like play toys to me and that's just not good my foster mom says. I am about 2 years old and weigh appx 70lbs. If you would like to meet me send an email to theloveofk9s@yahoo.com. Please allow 24 hours for a reply.

Adoption donation pays for all vettng...my neuter, a heart worm test, all vaccinations, deworming, flea prevention and a wellness exam.

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Porter joined Last Hope after his owner abandoned him, leaving him behind when they moved away. This wonderfully loving boy deserves the very best in a forever home, and we're excited to introduce you to him! Porter has lived with other dogs and children, he is not interested in a home with small animals but instead prefers the company of mellow dogs his size. He has done doggie daycare and is submissive and playful with dogs his size in a small group setting

In his younger years, Porter was known for his ability to jump a fence...he has proven young at heart and can still do this when tempted! He is mellowed out now at around 6 years old, and with a responsible owner who would never leave him unattended this really should not be an issue. Porter rides in the car like a champ, and he will make a wonderful companion for someone seeking a friendly dog that is moderately active. Porter is strong on a leash, but he is respectful and listens very well!

Porter's adoption fee is $250 and includes his neuter, microchip, current vaccinations and preventatives PLUS a free obedience course at Cedar Run Pet Boarding & Daycare in Hiawatha. Last Hope requires that all animals be kept as indoor pets only, be altered and current on vaccinations and preventatives. Our adoption process includes reference and background checks, a vet check and a home visit. Please submit an adoption application on our website for consideration, www.Adopthope.org

animal.description:
*Due to COVID-19, we are currently only processing adoption applications from  Kentucky and adjoining states. To all of our potential adopters, please consider adopting or fostering animals close to home! To those potential adopters in other states, please remember us and revisit our available pet listing once the it is safe to travel more freely! Thank you!* 

Rosie, called Jo by her foster family, is a fun and sociable puppy and is especially cute with one ear up and one ear down most all the time. She was born in March 2020 and weighed about 30 pounds in November 2020. Her sister's adoptive family had a canine DNA test done and shared the results with us. You can see the results as one of her photos. 

Rosie LOVES to run and do the zoomies! She loves people and toys! She gets so excited that she would be better in a home without children under 12 years old. She needs a fenced yard where she can run and play. Rosie loves her cat foster brother! She loves other dogs who are nice to her. She can be a little scared of big, over-assertive dogs. She is leash-trained, house-trained AND crate-trained!  She sleeps in her kennel and will go in on command. 

Rosie is ready and willing to learn! She needs a family with the time and interest to continue training her and  who will work with her high energy. She know "sit", "lay down", "kennel", "spin" and "roll over" and she's ready to learn more. She has so much love to give! She just needs to right family to find her.

She will be a wonderful addition to a family who will give her lots of love and care. Like all dogs, Rosie will be happiest when she is involved with her family and their activities his whole life.

All of our puppies are up-to-date on vaccinations, intestinal worm treatment, heart worm, flea and tick prevention and will be micro-chipped prior to adoption. Our foster families do their best to begin their house-training but please be patient with any puppy you adopt. It's a learning process!

If you are ready for the work, time, patience, expense and commitment required to raise a puppy, we welcome your adoption application. Sending us a completed application is the very first step so be sure to do that first thing! The adoption donation is $200. All of our animals must be spayed or neutered when reaching the appropriate age. A reimbursement of $50 will be sent to the adopter once we receive the receipt from the procedure. The adoption donation also includes a discount for S.T.A.R. Puppy Kindergarten or Canine Good Citizen Class. 

When applying for any adoption, please be aware that The Humane Society office is open Mon - Thurs from 10 - 3. We will respond to any inquiries or adoption submissions sent during non-office hours on the next day we are in the office. Thank you for your understanding!

Dog Adoption Guidelines:

You must fill out an application to be considered for adoption. You can find the application at www.ForThePets.org/adoption.htm or email humanesociety@murray-ky.net for an application.

It is not a first come process; we try to match the dog with the family for a FOREVER home. We process all applications at once and take the dog off the site, place on adoption pending status until a decision is made. If a suitable home match is not found, the dog returns to active status.

The dog adoption process can take up to two weeks; we are a small group of volunteers who mostly have full time jobs.

All of our dogs are indoor dogs with outdoor privileges, unless otherwise specified.

We do not fly or ship our dogs due to heat/cold concerns and safety issues. If you are willing to fly out AND fly the dog back in the cabin (size restrictions) with you, that would be considered.

If you apply to adopt a dog and are chosen, you must come to Murray, KY to pick up the dog and fill out the paperwork in person.

We can't provide individual meet and greet sessions for each applicant. If chosen to adopt, you will have plenty of time for your family and pets to visit with the potential new family member before signing any paperwork and will not be committed to adopt if you choose not to at that time.

She is just looking for a low-key, low energy home to live out her Golden Years. Despite her age, Bella still likes to go for walks, a few times a week, but nothing too long or strenuous. She loves being outside in a nice fenced back yard, or can find a few toys tooccupy her time when inside, at home. Bella is house trained, crate trained, comes when she is called, and walks on leash (or harness) w/out issues. Most of all-Bella LOVES her people around her. Whether she wants to rest her head in your lap, is enjoying some one-on-one cuddle time, or is just in the same room with you-she is content. If there might be other dogs around the hone-an introduction with Bella is a MUST.... She is still working on her socializing skills. The ideal home for this gorgeous gal is with minimal noise, older or no kids, a strong, semi-active owner, a secure yard, and nothing but an abundance of love to give. If Bella sounds like your dream come true-pls reach out to DPA for more info! She can't wait to meet you! This pet is available for pre-adoption and may not be officially ready for adoption, as it is still undergoing medical treatment. Depending on the medical status, a Meet and Greet may be put on hold until they can safely participate in a meeting with potential adopters. In some cases, this pet may be able to move to its forever home while it is still under the medical care of Dallas Pets Alive. If you are interested in learning more, apply now and one of our Adoption Counselors will discuss the options available so you can bring home your new furry family member! Applications are processed in the order in which they are received; please be aware that this pet may have interested applicants ahead of you. All Dallas Pets Alive adoptable pets are spayed or neutered, microchipped, and up to date on vaccines upon adoption. The standard minimum donation for dogs over six months to seven years is $200, puppies under six months is $250, dogs eight years and over are $100 unless specified otherwise. You can view all the adoptable pets and fill out an adoption application online on our website at http://dallaspetsalive.org/adopt/adoptable-dogs/ . For more information, you can email adopt@dallaspetsalive.org.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Meet Marley! This calm, beautiful girl was born around December 2014. This brief video shows how loving and affectionate she is. https://youtu.be/xnfSsO7wKwE

When we got her from the shelter, Marley was terrified of everything. She cowered away from people and tried to hide under furniture. After several months of tender loving care from her foster family, she has transformed into her true loving, affectionate, confident self.

Once fearful of riding in a car, watch how she now lays calmly watching things go by. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LqMHiyreBpU

Marley loves people. She adores having her face and booty scratched. She warms up to visitors who come to the house; first she goes to her crate for safety, and eventually comes out. She has not been kid tested, but for now, children in the home should be old enough to know that they cannot startle her or pull her tail.

Marley will learn your schedule very well. At bedtime, she sleeps on her bed in your room along with the rest of the dog pack. She sweetly wakes you up with kisses and demands for attention.

She gets super excited and jumps all over the place when she knows she's about to go on a walk in the neighborhood! Once you get going, she steps politely into place right alongside you.

Her forever human needs to be a benevolent alpha leader, otherwise her past street survival skills will take over and she will rule the house. She would likely be okay as an only dog if she can spend lots of time with her people. If she has a doggie friend in her forever home, the dog should be easy-tempered and docile, otherwise they will likely clash.

Marley does not tolerate the slightest hint of bad manners or disrespect from other dogs. She even takes offense if a dog accidentally wags their tail in her face or growls during introductions. Any new dogs should be introduced properly to avoid her possible overreaction.

Marley likes having an open-door crate that she can use as needed. She does not sleep in it at night, but takes turns with the other dogs resting in it throughout the day.

Along with being leash trained, she is house trained and doggie-door trained. She is scared of thunderstorms, so she could use extra love and hugs during stormy days.

She loves to roam the neighborhood, so she needs a tall wooden fence to prevent her from going on her own walkabout. And she's a door-dasher! You'll have to be careful when opening the front door, otherwise, she'll dash out to go exploring by herself!

Marley loves being outside in the backyard. She takes her toys out with her while she enjoys the sunlight and fresh air.

If you want to spoil her a bit, she loves having yummy vegetables, eggs, and rice in her kibble!

Marley is very sweet and loving to humans who make her feel safe. She will be a wonderful addition to the right family.

animal.description:
CANDIE IS NOT AVAILABLE FOR ADOPTION
CANDIE IS A SPECIAL NEEDS PUP WHO NEEDS SPONSORSHIP

Hi there. I'm Candie, a 12-year old bichon mix. I am a BROC Senior Sunsetter and I've been living with my foster family here for nearly three years. Being a Senior Sunsetter means I'm kinda special. My mom says I'm the sweetest, most loving girl you can find. She must surely love me because even though I have ongoing health challenges, she said she will take care of me for the rest of my life. It has not been easy for her - or me! You see, I have something called 'auto-immune deficiency' so I got this bad thing on my back and tummy. Mom called it MRSA. Not sure what that means but sometimes I sure itch a lot. My mom and the doctors treated me for a over a year with all sorts of medication. Now, my mom gives me special baths every other day to keep me as comfortable as possible. Last year, I had to have surgery in my tummy. They said I had a hernia and they needed to take it out. I don't know what they did because luckily I was sound asleep. I never did see my hernia! I'm so glad that all my family at BROC take such good care of me. I wonder who is taking care of them.

At Bichon Rescue of Orange County, our commitment to our pups does not waiver when they have special needs. These special needs pups are less likely to be adopted for reasons of age, health or behavior. We have amazing volunteers committed to fostering these pups until the end but we need sponsors to help with funding all of their needs.

Won't you consider supporting Candie by setting up a monthly sponsorship? Even the smallest amount will help. As a Senior Sponsor we will send you photos and updates on Candie.

If you can find it in your heart to help Candie or one of our other seniors, please copy and paste this link in your browser: https://bichonrescueoc.org/sponsorship

animal.description:
You MUST fill out an application on the Carolina Hearts website (link below) to be considered for adoption. Due to a large volume of calls and emails, we can ONLY ensure responses to those who fill out an application on the Carolina Hearts website (link below).

AVAILABLE: Andes

Through absolutely no fault of her own, our adorable little Andes is back and ready for a new family! She is still a sassy and lovable girl who needsjust the right home to give her the structure and environment that she needs to thrive. Andes is a double merle Mini American Shepherd and at 5 years old and 15 pounds, she's the best companion for both hikes, walks in the park, a game of fetch or just cuddling up on the couch. Due to her start in a puppy mill and improper breeding, she has been deaf all her life. It's easy to forget she can't hear, though, as she is so attentive to her people and has such a zest for life.

Since being back with her original foster family, Andes has grown and matured. She still knows all her original obedience commands through sign language and has learned new ones such as "leave it" and "calm". "Place" is her next one to conquer! She is amazing on a leash and responds very well to learning new behaviors. Andes is full of energy and needs an outlet for that energy to maintain her good behavior. She needs a strong, assertive and very committed family who will keep up the training and structure that she does so well with.

Andes gets along well with people and other dogs once she is introduced properly on a leash. She could stand to learn some better manners when meeting canine friends, but once she is comfortable she loves playing and running around with her foster brother and their pack of friends. She is NOT suited for a home with small children (under 12) or cats.

This amazing girl will adjust so well once with the right family. She deserves the stability and love of some really great humans.

Anders is UTD on vaccines, microchipped, and spayed. She is fostered in Greer, SC and her adoption fee is $300. If you are an approved applicant and are interested in Andes please contact the adoption committee. If you are interested and not yet approved please visit our website for adoption procedures and application.

http://carolinaheartsrescue.org/adoption-information/

Hey there!  I'm Jesse.

 I'm a 5 year old Terrier mix and I love to play!

When the awesome officers of Hallettsville PD took me in, they tried really hard to find my owner.  You see, my owner more than likely dumped me and left me to fend for myself.  It was a really sad and scary time for me.  I was scheduled to be put to sleep and sent over the Rainbow Bridge when the awesome peeps from Lucies decided to bring me in.

I am soooo much better now and have felt love like I have never known.  I have learned to run and play and have fun!  Being a grown man now, I tend to like the lady dogs better than the males.  ;)

Oh yeah, I'm leash and crate trained as well.

I make great eye contact and would give my owner my whole heart and desire to be with them as much as possible.  Won't you please give me a chance???

animal.description:
Hi... my name is a Scarlett and I am a 6 year old pit terrier mix. I've been living with my foster family about 6 months now; ever since this crazy 'virus' has been around.
They tell me I am basically a quiet dog that loves people. I am not a good 'watchdog'; I just let anyone walk right in.
I am an only pet as my foster parents have no other pets and they tend to spoil me. I can not tolerate cats and I have been told that I am allergic to them. I also have a few food allergies that my new owner will need to be aware of.
I do walk well on a leash until I spy a cat or other small animals that I would like to chase.
I need a strong 'male' presence in my life that will correct me on walks when I try to go after small prey. I love car rides and prefer the front seat. Because of my super strength, children over the age of 10 would be best.
I might do well with another dog my size, which is 60 pounds, but wound definitely need a meet and greet to see if we would be compatible.
I'd like to find my forever family soon... applications are available at petsearchpa.org

IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN STELLA, PLEASE GO TO OUR WEBSITE TO READ ABOUT THE PROCESS AND FILL OUT AN ADOPTION APPLICATION. www.furkidrescue.org 

Stella is a 1 year old great Dane . She was born with two front legs that are deformed. Currently, she hobbles around fairly well on her front right deformed leg. Her left leg is of no use. As she gets older and larger, she is most likely going to have issues with holding up her weight, and will need a wheelchair, or prosthetics. Because of this, she will likely do well in a home that she does not have to do any kind of stairs on a daily basis. She can do a small set of stairs now, but if she has to do stairs every day, it will not be a good home for her. 

Stella is spunky, and playful. She loves playing with other dogs. She loves her toys, and her bones, and her favorite part of the day is breakfast. This girl lives for food! She sleeps in her dog bed every night next to her foster mom’s bed. She sleeps through the night and will not get you up to go potty. She loves laying outside in the sun. She has a favorite place on the couch, and props herself up on the end. She is cuddly and playful. She does not go for walks. A fenced in yard is required.

animal.description:
Henna #A1929706

Henna is polite greeting new people. She does not jump up, just greets and smells them.
She is Medium energy. She likes to be a couch potato, but a few times a day she enjoys getting in a good sprint or chase the ball. She needs a decently long walk each day at the very least, or she gets fussy at night.
Henna needs to be the only pet in the home. She is reactive to other dogs and critters when out on walks.
She is affectionate and likes to be close by. She will sleep in her dog bed at night. She doesn't like spending time in her crate.
Henna is house trained and makes it clear that she needs to go outside. Great on a leash, unless she sees another animal. She is getting used to traffic and busy streets.
She knows some basic commands and is good in the bath.

Henna is spayed, microchipped, up to date with vaccinations and will come with 6 weeks of FREE training through our prison program when adopted.

animal.description:
Description of pet
Destine was brought to the NYCACC- the NYC Municipal shelter due to her owners moving and couldn't take her.  So they dumped her at the kill shelter at only 2 years old.  This was last year in Feb 2019.

She then landed on the Euthanasia list due to her fearfulness and anxiousness. at the shelter.  She was saved by an amazing foster that saved her life.


DESTINE'S STATS:

AGE: 3 YEARS OLD

WEIGHT: 50 lbs

SPAYED: YES

GOOD WITH KIDS: YES OLDER

STRANGERS: NO

OTHER DOGS: YES

ON LEASH: YES

HOUSE BROKEN: YES

CRATE TRAINED:  YES

Luna needs a person with strong experience working with dogs that have trust issues.  She will need time to decompress and someone who is patient and able to gain her trust.  

Luna is very afraid of strangers and is aggressive until she gets comfortable with someone.  She will chase cars and try to snap at them as they drive by. 

Luna has had a tough go at life as indicated by her initial reaction to people. She can be aggressive and lunges until she is feeling safe and comfortable (it took me about two hours of sitting outside her crate and feeding her treats before I felt ok letting her out), but once she is, she has more than enough love to give. She can be very lovable and sweet, but it is only once you have established a safe and comfortable environment for her. She loves walks but will chase cars and pull towards and bark at passerbyers.  She is good with other dogs and loves to play but gets super excited and can agitate other dogs with her energy. She is a super sweet dog but will need an owner that is patient and willing to work with her issues.

animal.description:
Duncan, or Mr. Monkey as the kids love to call him, is as sweet, loving and energetic as can be! He loves his people and always wants to be right in the middle of the family! He enjoys cuddling and loves to sleep under the blankets! He loves everyone he meets including other dogs and cats. 

He enjoys playing tug of war, football and catch! He likes to go for walks and still pulls but settles down once he’s walked a little. He knows basic commands like sit, shake, high five, stay and come (to a fist pointed at him). He is very food motivated and learns quickly! He definitely wants to please you and get rewarded! He tends to resource guard so will do best in a home with no other pets or children. He has shown some increase in fear/anxiety in unknown situations like a neighbor snow blowing so will definitely need training in this area as well. 

Duncan would do best in a home that has no other pets, a fenced back yard and a person who is willing to do more training. He would do best with positive reinforcement and clear boundaries as he’s very sensitive. He is a sweet boy who needs a structured environment with training and lots of love and attention to give. He is estimated to be 10 months old and 55 lbs. Since we don't know at all what doggy genes are in the dogs make up (we don't know who mom and dad are!), we are just guessing on breed and size when grown.

Please note that because we require a home visit at the time of adoption we can only place animals in homes within a 60 mile radius of Minneapolis. If you are interested in meeting this dog please fill out the pre-adoption application on our website at http://www.safehandsrescue.org under Adopt and we will get back to you to arrange a meeting in the foster home.

animal.description:
Meet Tootsie!

Tootsie was rescued from an animal control facility in Fannin County, where she was scheduled to be euthanized due to limited space. 

It's hard to believe that this beautiful girl would be willing to forgive humans for keeping her chained in a small patch of grass for FOUR LONG YEARS while they used her for breeding - but she did.  In fact, she is extremely loving and affectionate, and grateful to be alive.  Her owner passed away, and the family discarded her to a high kill shelter, like yesterday's garbage.

We're thinking that Tootsie needs to be a one woman dog, as she aligns herself to the female in the home.  She could live in harmony with a couple, as long as one person doesn't mind not receiving as much of her affection.  We believe that she must have been abused by the (male) owner who was using her for breeding.  She is NOT aggressive toward men, only somewhat timid and fearful.

The following was written from Tootsie's perspective while she was in a shelter in GA -

"Distance. It’s something that I hear you humans are learning a lot about lately. As for me, it was how I lived most of my life. My name is Tootsie, and I spent most of my life at the end of a chain, outside and exposed, never knowing what it was like to be close to a human being. Then suddenly, the person who used to feed me was gone and I found myself here at this shelter. I was so scared, but I soon learned to trust the nice people here who took me for walks. That was an amazing experience for me. I’d never known much outside a small patch of dirt, so walks were magical. I lived so long in solitude that I’m not much of a fan of rambunctious pups, because I like things quiet and calm. As long as they’re low-key like me, I’m happy to hang out with other dogs, though. But people are just about my favorite thing in the world. I love having my head in someone’s lap. I hear you have these things called sofas, and I really want to see what those are all about. Things that are soft and warm sound like a dream to me. I’ve longed for comfort for so long, and I’ve longed for love, too. Maybe that’s why I’m a velcro dog whenever someone comes to walk me. I can never be close enough to my human friends. They’re my world, but lately they haven’t been here to see me. I guess it’s all part of the distance thing I’m hearing about, but I’m still worried that maybe I’ve been abandoned again. I'm not getting any younger, but they think I'm just about four or five years old. I have been here at this shelter for seven whole months as of today. That’s a long time, and this place is just supposed to be temporary. What will become of me if my friends never return? What will I do without people? Maybe you can help me find someone to love me, a lap where I can always put my head. Tell my shelter friends that I miss them, and I hope they’re thinking of me. And maybe, somewhere, someone is looking for a peaceful 49-pound pup like me. I hope they can find me from a distance. I’ll be here wishing and hoping."

Tootsie is now in NH and looking for her forever family. She's been here for 8 months, living in a family environment.  We kept her this long so that she could decompress and learn what love feels like, and now we feel that she's ready to find her forever home.  

She's confident, and absolutely wonderful with women, but initially fearful of men.  Most of the rescuers in the Georgia shelter were female, so Tootsie developed an affinity for women.

Tootsie is about 5 years old, and weighs 60 lbs. She is spayed, has all her required vaccines, and is microchipped.

If you'd like to open your heart and home to this lovely lady, please complete an adoption application at https://www.heartsandtails.org/adoption-application/

PLEASE NOTE that due to the overwhelming number of inquiries we receive daily, we can only respond to those who have completed an online application, and appear to be a good match. PLEASE check all of the fields in this profile to ensure your question hasn't already been answered as most of the information is in this profile.

animal.description:
Looking Glass Animal Rescue is a 501c3 virtual rescue, using a network of dedicated fosters throughout the Northeast to care for our animals until adoption. You may be required to travel if approved for adoption.

Sport is a goofy, energetic love with the right person,. Sport is very male selective and will need his space on his time. He takes some time to warm up and adjust, all intros need to be slow, but once he does he really shows you his playful side in the appropriate environment. A good game of fetch, long walks is all he wants. He loves being next to his human while chewing on a bone or hanging outside taking in all the different smells. Sport is 4 years young and still requires an energetic household. He has done amazing with crate training and will now go in with just a simple point and mention of "bed". He is a bit fearful of the unfamiliar so patience and slow introductions to all new things are a must but I promise you, you will not be disappointed. Sport does great with well behaved mini humans although due to his energy and size little ones over 7 is recommended. Sport will not do well in a close living situation and will need a fenced yard of his own. His hound instincts are strong so No kitties for this guy please, Sport has a very high prey drive. Dogs ok with proper intros.

Sport is available for adoption through Looking Glass Animal Rescue, a 501c3 non-profit animal welfare organization. All adoptions are subject to review and approval. Please complete an application at https://lgarinc.org/adoption-application/

Please note that you must be 25 years of age to adopt and we reserve the right to refuse adoption to anyone. Please be advised that we will not approve adoptions to persons who mislead or fail to provide accurate information on this application. Incomplete applications will not be processed.

animal.description:
My name is Holly Mae! 

I'm a little over a year old and have been through a lot in my short time. I was completely shut down when I arrived in MN due to my past experiences. My foster family has been really patient with helping me to build my trust of people. I am still pretty shy and timid, but my foster mom thinks I will thrive with a loving and patient family. I do like my crate to be openly accessible if I get scared.

I am currently in a foster that has two other dogs and they are showing me that humans are not as scary as I think. I am warming up to them and do enjoy playing with them occasionally in my fenced in yard. I definitely need a fenced in yard in my forever home as I get spooked easily which makes me want to run and hide.

My crate is my safest place. I go there to seek comfort if a loud noise is made or if a new person I don't know comes into my space. I also sleep in my crate at night and hang out in there during the day when my family is at work. I love my crate and do great in there. 

My perfect family would be one that can be really patient with letting me adjust and lets me work through my fears on my own time. A family that doesn't have a ton of activity in the house would be best as a lot of activity and noise can be terrifying to me. I need a home with a fenced in yard so that I can stay safe and one with another dog so that I'm motivated to keep building trust with humans. I am a really sweet girl once you get me out of my shell and am super lovable!


--------------------------------------------


All our Warrior Dogs will have all age appropriate medical care and vaccines, a microchip, and spay/neuter before adoption unless age is a factor with a puppy younger than 6-12 months at the time of adoption. If that is the case, the spay/neuter will be covered in the adoption fee and the owner will be responsible to have the procedure completed at a Warrior Dog Rescue Veterinarian at the appropriate time.

Please note that the majority of our dogs in rescue are from shelters where they have been found as strays or abandoned. Their breed description is based on our very best educated guess based on physical characteristics and their dispositions. If they came to our rescue as an owner surrender, the breed description will be listed as provided by the previous owner.

Adoption Fee - $450

To apply for this pup, please submit an Adoption Application at http://warriordogrescue.com/adopt/adoption-application/

animal.description: Meet Marlo! He is about 5 years old and we think he is a Pointer mix. Marlo came to Labs and More in rough shape with some broken teeth, very underweight and an old leg injury. He still has some lingering medical issues with his lungs that are being managed with medications and he will need routine checks and medication the rest of his life. While he tires a little faster than most dogs, he enjoys his short walks and can get around just fine. Marlo is house trained and crate trained in his current foster home. He has been around other dogs and done well. He is shy with new people and takes time to build trust, but he has opened up in his foster home and gently asks his foster mom for pets and affection. If you are interested in meeting Marlo, please submit an adoption application on our website. This information is as up to date and accurate as possible for the dog in its current environment. All dogs and puppies will need time and training to adjust to their new surroundings and to learn the rules of their new home. If you are interested in meeting one of our dogs, the first step is to complete the Adoption Form on our website at www.labsandmore.org and take some time to review our adoption process. Your adoption includes the spay or neuter, current vaccinations, microchip, and other services provided while in our care. The safety and health of our puppies is priority one, so we only allow approved applicants to meet and handle puppies. Please understand everything we do is for the dogs and conducted by our kind and generous volunteers. We rely solely on donations, and we do not profit from a dog's adoption. Labs and More is a 501(c)3 non-profit organization that operates on donations and time dedicated to this cause by volunteers. Your adoption will save the life of future dogs in need. Labs and More makes no guarantees regarding the behavior, breed, or age of the dogs in our care. Although we strive to provide necessary medical care to dogs in our care, we cannot predict future or current medical needs whether they were symptomatic or not at the time of adoption.Thank you for looking to Adopt a Labrador Retriever or other Mixed Breed Dog from California Labradors Retrievers and More Rescue. Please take a moment and go to www.labsandmore.org and click on Adopt to complete our online dog adoption application. If you have any questions email us at doginfo@labsandmore.org or call us at 858-273-5386. Thank you for looking to a rescue group to fulfill your dream of adding a new dog to your life! Dogs + Love = Family

animal.description:
Brynn
Female
Terrier mix
About 6-3/4 years old
House trained
Crate trained
Walks well on a leash
Knows basic commands
Good with other dogs
Unknown with cats
Good with respectful children 10 years old or older

Brynn came to us from another rescue when they asked if we could help with her. They had rescued her from a large hoarding situation and she had done well in foster care in their rescue, but had little interest. They thought she would get more exposure with us, and we were happy to help.

Brynn is a sweet, loving, playful girl who is slightly timid when meeting new people but warms up quickly.

She does well with other dogs and we would like to see her in a home with at least one other dog.

She would like a fairly quiet home - a lot of commotion may make her nervous.

She will make a fabulous family member!

To adopt please fill out the form at our website - https://www.furryfriendsct.org/adoption-application

ADOPTION POLICIES AND PROCEDURES:

Our goal is to help you find a wonderful new family member! We work closely with you to ensure that the dog you adopt will be a wonderful match for your family's make-up and lifestyle. Our adoption and foster placement processes includes an application, personal and vet reference checks, a home visit, and a meet and greet with the dog and all family members and other pets.

Placement is considered on the basis of the best interests of the dog and the best fit with the family - we do not adopt on a "first come, first served" basis.

We do not transport our dogs outside of the state of CT. If you live outside of CT and are able to travel to us after an application is approved, with your family and other pets, for a meet and greet and to complete the adoption in CT if that goes well, you're welcome to apply to adopt one of our dogs, as long as you live in one of the New England states. We do not adopt our dogs long-distance, or outside of the New England area.

PLEASE NOTE: All of our dogs live in foster homes within the state of CT. We do not have a facility. For that reason we ask that you go through the application/approval process prior to a meet and greet, which is always part of our placement protocol. We do this because we try to keep our foster families' day to day lives s uninterrupted as possible. You can fill out an adoption application at our website, at https://www.furryfriendsct.org/adoption-application

animal.description:
*Home with attached yard needed
*NO apartments, duplex, townhouse rented rooms
*Dogs okay
*NO cats
*NO children
* Prefers women 

SCOUT is a sweet shy boy, who we rescued from the shelter where he was about to be euthanized  because he was so frightened of people! It took him a few weeks at his foster home to get comfortable and he attached himself to the kids quickly as he felt less threatened by kids. He loved playing ball with them!
He was adopted out and recently returned to us because his adopter's had a baby and as the baby started walking and playing with loud toys and screaming, it became too much for our shy and fearful boy so they felt it was best for SCOUT to find a home he would be more comfortable. He was adopted again to another family who told us they were a quiet home but turns out they had lots of activity with their teenage daughter and friends, neighbors and family gatherings. It was just too much for Scout to handle and he was stressed and acting out. So he is back with us and we are now looking for a better fitting home for our sweet boy...one that is not full of loud and scary noises....with no children, and preferably with a single woman who is either retired or works from home. 
SCOUT is a good boy! He is housetrained and crate trained. He is good with other dogs and will do best in a home with another calm doggie friend to help him with his confidence and to show him the ropes!
SCOUT is doing good on his leash walks. He has gotten more confident but still gets frightened of loud noises or ‘scary objects’.... he likes walking/running on trails in the hills or off the beaten path. He is very happy just playing in the backyard and hanging out on the couch. When things get too stressful or overwhelming for him, he likes to go in his crate. It’s his safe place. 
SCOUT's breed is still a mystery to us! Maybe part lab? maybe part pit? maybe part Aus Shep?? Who knows!??   BUT, He's cute as a button and just the right size at about 45 lbs. SCOUT needs a quiet home with no children as loud noises and commotion scare him. He would do best with a single woman who is retired or works from home, who will make him feel safe, yet encourage him to be brave, but not force him to handle more than he can take, and who will never give up on him, even on his most insecure days, who will accept him as he is and not expect him to be what he is not....and of course, commit to loving him forever. 

SCOUT's adoption fee is $250 which includes health examination, current vaccinations, neuter, microchip, flea and de worming treatment, along with any other medical/dental deemed necessary by our veterinarian.

NO LONG DISTANCE (South California) OR OUT OF STATE ADOPTIONS

You can request applications by emailing Rhodiesrescue@gmail.com or contacting us through Petfinder. 
When submitting an application please allow time for your application to be reviewed. We will contact you if we have questions or need further information or to schedule meet and greets. If you do not hear from us within 3 days, it does not mean you are not a good home for a dog, but you may not be the right match for this particular dog.

Bugsy is about 5# and 9 years old...he qualifies for our seniors adopting seniors program. *** If interested please submit an application at www.becauseofyourescue.org ***

animal.description:
4/22/2020 update - our adoption area is limited to UT, NV, ID, OR, WA and MT with a home visit.  If you are outside of this area please do a search for your local GSP/GWP/Pointer rescue group.

--------

I'm MAYHEM!  My rescue lady just loves me and loves having me at home with her when she doesn't have a bunch of newbie young 'uns that take up all her time.  I love being with her, the other dogs and even the cats.  I'm a little suspicious of people I don't know so I need to get out more for socializing.  I'm very playful with my pack and will tone down my enthusiasm so I don't hurt the little ones.  After all, I'm a Great Big Boy!

My approx. DOB is 02/12/2017 so I'm finished growing and I'm the perfect weight for my size.  I need an active home to keep me trim and healthy.  I'll be the best hiking/camping buddy.  No one's going to break into your home while I'm there!

I'm not a first-time-owner kind of guy.  My new home needs to know my breed, give me a job and help me become all I can be.

I don't do well in areas where there's lots of pollution or long-lived pollen.  It bothers my sinuses.  Benadryl helps, but a less-polluted environment is better for me. 

Oh, and as you can tell from the pictures, I like sleeping under the covers. <3 

---------

GENERAL APPLICATION NOTES:

We strongly urge adopters to consider a male canine companion if they already have a female GSP/GWP. We get asked several times a year to take in one member of a 2-female GSP family because there are control issues between their girls that result in pretty ferocious fights. Interestingly that never happens among males. Go figure.

Dogs under 2 years of age need to go to a home with another well-socialized canine companion of a similar size (when grown) and within a few years of the pup’s age. This is how they maintain and continue their learning/socialization process. Socialization outside the home is important but doesn’t replace the in-home learning that is so important as the pup ages. https://www.facebook.com/ UtahsPerfectPointers/posts/ 1460968517254816

Most older dogs aren’t interested in having a puppy incessantly chewing on it and demanding attention. If you live outside of the Salt Lake area and are sure that your older dog just loves puppies, please arrange a visit at your home with a 2-4 month old pup for a couple of hours and make sure that your older dog feels the same way about this that you do. Please video the interactions and send it to us.

Just a word of caution........ most pointer types need jobs. Otherwise they're not good pets. They need to be able to utilize their brains and no amount of exercise without a "work" or "thinking" component is adequate. The job doesn't need to be hunting. But it does need to be something that satisfies their genetic predispositions - nose work, agility, tracking, dock diving, etc. The job cannot just be obedience. If they can't use their innate senses they're just never going to be the dog you want for the next 15 years.

A physical fence is required for most of our dogs.

As far as other breeds go, the pointers are generally good with most other breeds with the exception of the Arctic breeds and bulldogs. I'm not sure why, but if there's ever an altercation in daycare between a UPP dog and another dog, it's generally one of those two breeds. It may be the difference in energy levels. It may be some ancient behavior we know nothing about...... Not sure.

Utah's Perfect Pointers is a very small rescue group and doesn't have the resources to adopt to states except for the ones noted above.. If you are interested in adopting a GSP please contact the closest groups below. Keep in mind that not all of their dogs may be listed on their sites.

animal.description:
4/22/2020 update - our adoption area is limited to UT, NV, ID, OR, WA and MT with a home visit.  If you are outside of this area please do a search for your local GSP/GWP/Pointer rescue group.

--------

I'm BROOKLYN!  I'm a very busy girl and totally loving.  As you can see, I'm missing a leg from a car accident two years ago.  It doesn't slow me down at all.  I race around the yard with the other dogs with absolutely no problems.  I'm great with other dogs and I'm even OK with cats (with appropriate supervision).

I've had two litters of puppies - both after being hit by a car and losing my leg.  Unfortunately my owners thought it would be nice to breed me "because I'm from such good lines". (**%#!)  Those days are over.  It's time I had someone to take care of me as their bff - not to use me for their selfish purposes.

I'm very snuggly.  I love crawling into my people's laps and lying with them while they pet me. <3

Don't let my missing leg fool you.  I'm "everything GSP" - cuddly inside and totally "out of control" outside.  I bark incessantly because I'm so excited.  I'm terrible on a leash.  I want to run with abandon totally ignoring my people who want me to coooooooommme baaaaccck!  I need a very breed-experienced home that's very active and knows how to get the very best out of me outside as well as inside!


---------

GENERAL APPLICATION NOTES:

We strongly urge adopters to consider a male canine companion if they already have a female GSP/GWP. We get asked several times a year to take in one member of a 2-female GSP family because there are control issues between their girls that result in pretty ferocious fights. Interestingly that never happens among males. Go figure.

Dogs under 2 years of age need to go to a home with another well-socialized canine companion of a similar size (when grown) and within a few years of the pup’s age. This is how they maintain and continue their learning/socialization process. Socialization outside the home is important but doesn’t replace the in-home learning that is so important as the pup ages. https://www.facebook.com/ UtahsPerfectPointers/posts/ 1460968517254816

Most older dogs aren’t interested in having a puppy incessantly chewing on it and demanding attention. If you live outside of the Salt Lake area and are sure that your older dog just loves puppies, please arrange a visit at your home with a 2-4 month old pup for a couple of hours and make sure that your older dog feels the same way about this that you do. Please video the interactions and send it to us.

Just a word of caution........ most pointer types need jobs. Otherwise they're not good pets. They need to be able to utilize their brains and no amount of exercise without a "work" or "thinking" component is adequate. The job doesn't need to be hunting. But it does need to be something that satisfies their genetic predispositions - nose work, agility, tracking, dock diving, etc. The job cannot just be obedience. If they can't use their innate senses they're just never going to be the dog you want for the next 15 years.

A physical fence is required for most of our dogs.

As far as other breeds go, the pointers are generally good with most other breeds with the exception of the Arctic breeds and bulldogs. I'm not sure why, but if there's ever an altercation in daycare between a UPP dog and another dog, it's generally one of those two breeds. It may be the difference in energy levels. It may be some ancient behavior we know nothing about...... Not sure.

Utah's Perfect Pointers is a very small rescue group and doesn't have the resources to adopt to states except for the ones noted above. If you are interested in adopting a GSP please contact the closest groups below. Keep in mind that not all of their dogs may be listed on their sites.

animal.description:
Shirley is a beagle mix, 5 years old and 30 lbs. She was one of a large group we got of similar dogs who were very unsocialized. All but Shirley and Felix have been adopted. She is one of the shyest. She has progressed a bit; but being in a foster would help, where she would have one on one attention and there would be less going on. She would do well to have a k-9 companion who is confident for her to model.
She will need time to settle in, and new owners will have to make sure she can't escape the yard or run out the front door, until she is used to the home. She is not used to leashes.
Please find our applications and valuable information under 'Adopt a dog'* on our website: *www.beaglesandbuddies.com* and email your application to beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Let us know your preference of appointment day/time and which dogs you are interested in and we will do our best to accommodate and email you the closest appointment available. Please allow us up to a week to get back to you. Most appointments will be Friday-Sunday, 10 am - 2 pm, for an hour.
*Note bring any other dog/s and the entire family to your meet and greet at B&B.* A complimentary training manual is included with each adoption, authored by terristeuben.com. Check out her website - she is fabulous!
B&B is glad to be open during the pandemic. We know the value and comfort of a loving pet companion and are doing our best to help the dogs and folks who need them. We update our website daily and are always rescuing, vetting, rehabilitating, socializing.
* We are accepting applications for volunteers to spend time with our dogs, hang out, sing/read to the shy ones, walk/toss ball with those who go to the playgrounds; cleaning, office work, gardening, and building/repair projects! *

Are you my furrever family?

For further info on the adoption process, please visit our home page and check out the "Adopt a Dog" section, which has thorough instructions. All our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and

fully vaccinated before adoption; they have been wormed, bathed, socialized, walked daily and much loved; each adoptee leaves with a leash, collar, and all medical records.

Our prices are higher than the shelters' because we nurse the dogs through their illnesses and get them needed surgeries and dentals. We also spend time socializing. Furthermore, unlike shelters, rescues do not get financial aid from the government and must rely on donations, grants, and adoption fees. Our fees for adults start at $150 and go up to $750. The higher end is for our most in demand dogs, such as young beagles and other purebred dogs. The lower end is for dogs who have been here a while. For puppies, we may go beyond this and charge $1000. The good news is that, because rescues fall under the "charity" category, the fees for our dogs are officially donations and are therefore tax deductible. You can think of it as donating to a worthy cause and getting a dog in return!

Sponsor Me

Beagles & Buddies must find ways to raise money so we can continue saving dogs. Your tax-deductible donation keeps our rescue kennel operating!

Hours

Friday: 10 am to 3 pm

Saturday: 10 am to 3 pm

Sunday: 10 am to 3 pm

Monday: CLOSED

Tuesday: CLOSED

Wednesday: CLOSED

Thursday: CLOSED



Weekday appointments may be available. We are a small staff and do our best to accommodate your needs. **Note that during COVID, we are not holding open houses on any day. Please email us for an appointment and include your application (found on our website, beaglesandbuddies.com, under "Forms"). Most appointments will be Friday through Sunday, though other days may also be available. We usually schedule one appointment per hour. Allow 1-2 hours for your appointment. Please look at our website and make a list of one or more dogs that you would like to see.

Contacting Us

If you have a question about adopting, giving up a dog, boarding, or volunteering, please visit the appropriate tabs on our
home page.

For more specific questions, call 626-444-9664 (please leave a voicemail if no answer) or email at beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Note that
Emailing
is always preferred!

Thanks!

Please note: If you are viewing this profile anywhere other than Beagles & Buddies own website, you are not receiving full info. Visit info on pet here.

animal.description:
Jipsey is a 4 year old spayed female Pit Bull mix.  She came into rescue from a southern shelter after just having puppies.  The pups have all been adopted and now it is Jipsey's turn.  Jipsey is sweet, friendly and affectionate.  She is ok with most dogs although would not mind (and might prefer) living as a solo dog.  Jipsey is not safe to live with cats.  Jipsey is crate trained, seems to be house trained and has nice manners.  She is good off leash and loves to hike and run in the woods.  Jipsey is looking for an experienced dog home who can understand her hesitance toward being grabbed by the collar.  She needs hands off training (treat training works well) especially if it is cold out and she doesn't want to go outside!  She is a nice dog who is still learning the ropes of being a "pet."  With positive training and self confidence building Jipsey will be a great addition to someone's home!

Adoption Fee: $100
Birthdate: 4/2016
Weight: 50 lbs.

Jipsey tested positive for heartworm. HHR will provide 6 months of meds to treat her.

She is housetrained and sleeps in a crate.
She will need an active home that will keep her mentally and physically busy. She will chase cats that run. She needs proper intro to new dogs.
