animal.description:
WHOA, hey Dude! Dude is a 1.5 year old, brindle mastiff mix who was dumped and roamed for a few months before someone was able to catch him. Thankfully they got him safe temporarily and have reached out to us to help Dude continue on his journey to find a home that will love and care for him always. He is working on his house and crate training and coming along nicely. He hasn't had much exposure to a leash, and it currently scares him for reasons only he knows, but his foster family will of course be working on this with him and helping him understand it means good things for him from here on out! He isn't quite trustworthy with free yet and will need to be crated for the time being. He temp foster had other dogs, livestock and kids and he did fantastic with everything and everyone, making him a super easy addition to just about any home.  He needs a home that will help him gain confidence and let him know that he is loved, he is very food motivated so will learn quickly. A very friendly guy who can't wait to be a part of a family and loved as such.

To see the most up to date adoption status of this dog, please visit www.bigdogshugepaws.com
This is just one of hundreds of gentle giants available for adoption at BDHPI! It is best not to get your heart set on any one particular dog upfront because there is no guarantee they will still be available once you are approved or that they are even the right match for your family. Purebred puppies are only eligible for adoption to giant breed experienced homes.

animal.description:
Shasta is a 5-year-old pittie mix with a shiny black/brown coat and the kindest honey-brown eyes! She came into Chicago Animal Care and Control from Safe Humane Chicago where she was rescued from a terrible situation. She had been found living in deplorable filth after firefighters responded to a fire in the home. The floors were covered in feces and urine. There was no food or water anywhere, but there were multiple other dogs and cats. 

Coming into the shelter, Shasta wasn’t very sure of her surroundings, but she managed to relax a bit and now’s she’s really living the life in her foster home! Shasta loves to be around her humans and especially loves to snuggle with them! She hasn’t met any cats since being with PFP, but she definitely doesn’t enjoy the company of other dogs, so she’d need to be the only puppy princess in her castle. 

Shasta does great in the car and doesn’t mind going on rides. She is crate-trained and is an angel in her crate. She can sometimes be shy when meeting new people, especially men. She is potty-trained, and knows some basic commands (sit, stay, lay down, come, leave it, up). She is intelligent and eager to please and has been learning and transitioning well. 

Additionally, she is a great running companion! She loves sprinting, but also does great on well-paced long-range running routes. She is still youthful and playful, and looooves power chewer toys, especially ball-shaped toys! 

Her only downfall? She doesn’t like noisy things like the vacuum or coffee bean grinder! The good news is, she’s fine with the blender, so if you need someone to share your smoothie with, she’s your gal! Interested in Shasta? Fill out a survey today at www.playersforpits.com/adoptionsurvey!

I'm looking for my own little family with no other animals and a nice man, that isn't too alpha but is kind and would have patience and love for me. I would love a couple of kids to play with too. I am pretty reactive to dogs, and don't like them, so it's best that you have a house with a 6 foot fence. I am a big strong boy, that loves life. Are you my family?? If you are can you please call Stephanie at 602-695-6232 or DDee at 602-448-6836 don't forget my name is Zeus, I'm in Phoenix and would love to meet you! Please call rather than email, as those take time sometimes, and I want to meet you asap!

animal.description:
Hunter is sweet loving 6yr old WOLF DOG malamute mix looking for his forever home. Hunter gets along with most dogs but it is unknown how he would do with small breeds. He would have to be adopted to a home with another canine companion to keep him company. Hunter is known to be an escape artist so he would need a 7-8ft fenced in area/ yard. He would also need some house training to spend any time in the house. Hunter is currently learning not to jump up on people to greet them as he does not know his own strength and gets very excited at times. Hunter is a very high energy dog so he would need daily exercise, he walks best on an EZ walk harness. He is a quick learner and very treat motivated. Hunter has no food aggression but could use better skills/ manners when being fed as he gets very excited with food in sight! Hunter has been around children and from what we observed he is good with them so far, it is unknown how he would do with them for long periods of time. He loves to run given the energy he has and would enjoy potential hikes/ long walks with his new owners! Hunter over all has a great temperament and would make a wonderful loving companion animal for the right person!

Do not inquire about or apply for Hunter if you live in any the following States: Delaware, Maryland, Pennsylvania, New York, Connecticut

animal.description: Agent S - A44138365Intake Type: 4/9 Stray - Public drop offVideos:Agent S Outside -- https://photos.app.goo.gl/1FDC2uE3N6Uvo1Fo8Agent S with Staff 1 -- https://youtu.be/5Xk6coqCpy4Agent S with Staff 2 -- https://youtu.be/ejBuz6OUa5sAgent S Plays Fetch -- https://youtu.be/DwUEWIE7kEoMedical Observation: (4/14) During check-in Agent S was able to be removed from kennel and brought into dog intake to be vaccinated. During the procedure Agent S was nervous but allowed his PE to be done. I was able to touch him with slow precise movements which allowed him to begin to relax slowly during the exam. Agent S showed signs of fear and stress(tucked tail with tense skin) but after check in has been much more relaxed - still tense but I can now go over to his cage and pet him through the gate.(4/10) Unable to check in. Dog is hard barking, snarling, and lunging at kennel door.Behavior Observation: (4/29) Easily leashed and removed from kennel. Pulls moderately through shelter and parking lot. Once he hits grass, immediately urinates and defecates. In yard, explores by sniffing perimeter for a few minutes before returning to handler's call and accepting pets all over with loose body. Loves chasing a tennis ball and returns and drops ball to handler. Pulls slightly back through parking lot and into shelter. Easily returned to kennel and leash is easily removed.(4/21) Per Staff -- Easily leashed and removed from kennel today. Pulls through shelter and out to yard. In yard, initially fairly aloof as he runs laps around perimeter. Does return to handler after urinating and defecating and accepts pets from back of neck to flank with loose body. Easily distracted by passing vehicles does not pay much attention to handler but continues to accept pets with loose body language when handler approaches. Easily returned to kennel and leash easily removed.(4/19) Dog Meet --Attempted dog meet with Sheila through fence. Agent S was very aroused, vocalizing, muzzle punching the fence. When met Sheila on leash, attempted to snap before able to introduce. Took in separate yard and continued to fixate on Sheila from across the parking lot. Still allowed handling and did not tense up. No interest in toys or treats. Pulled heavily through parking lot and into shelter. Placed back in kennel and leash removed without issue.(4/19) Per Staff -- Agent S was easily leashed and removed from kennel today. Still bows when leash is presented but easily looped. Once on leash, pulls through shelter and outside until in yard. In yard, runs laps for 5 or so minutes before returning to handler. Allows handling all over with loose body. Chases a rope toy but does not play with it once he gets to it. When handler stops petting, uses nose to nudge for more pets to flank. Pulls back to kennel but easily returned to kennel and easily unleashed.(4/18) Per Staff -- Moderately difficult to remove from kennel due to dog retreating and then coming forward again. Friendly, but conflicted. Once looped, exited easily and only pulled slightly while walking to evaluation room. Allowed handling all over although did show some signs of stress - heavy panting and some displacement sniffing. No issues returning to kennel or removing lead.(4/15) Was able to remove from kennel again on 4/15. When assessor approaches kennel, Agent S comes to front of kennel, takes treats nicely and pushes against kennel door to solicit pets, allows pets with loose body language. Leashing is easier than last time but Agent S still bows and then retreats before coming forward again and bowing. Is able to be leashed with no snapping at leash and readily leaves kennel. He pulled strongly through shelter and parking lot into yard. In yard, Agent S is initially tense but loosens after a few minutes and allows pets over entire body with relatively loose body language. Did not show interest in toys. One member of the public did walk by the fence which caused Agent S to tense and bark. Handler was able to pick leash up with no issue. Agent S pulls through the parking lot and shelter when returning. He is easily returned to kennel and leash is easily removed.(4/14) Per Staff -- Agent S approached for treats and took them gently but would bow and then retreat to back of kennel once presented with leash. After a few attempts, Agent S became overstimulated and started nipping at leash. A very loud barking dog in the kennel next to Agent S seemed to be escalating the situation. The handlers ended the interaction and moved to the other side of the kennel, which was quieter. Agent S remained at the kennel door as the handlers attempted to leash and accepted pets and treats. The handler was able to leash Agent S and the dog immediately exited the kennel, pulling strongly through the shelter and to the outside. Agent S continue to pull through parking lot, zig zagging in front of handler until we got into a yard. Agent S' body language in yard was tense and handlers attempted some pets to flank which were accepted. Agent S was very aloof in yard, tracing perimeter repeatedly but would accept treats from handler when he passed by. Showed no real interest in toys beyond chasing a tennis ball once. When members of the public would walk by the fence, Agent S would tense and hard bark. Agent S tensed up when handler picked up leash to go back inside and pulled strongly on walk back to kennel. Agent S dodged going back into the kennel but was lured in with treats and easily unleashed.(4/12) Per Staff -- Unable to remove from kennel. Took treats with a soft mouth, ears back, tail neutral. As soon as the leash was in sight he moved to the back of the kennel and would not approach.(4/12) Per Staff -- Still unable to be removed from kennel. Dog is hard barking at front of kennel, retreats and then charges towards front of kennel, snapping at bars. Spent 8-10 minutes attempting to coax with treats and Fresh Pet but behavior continued. When attempted to leash, dog snapped repeatedly and tore leash.(4/10) Behavior -- Initially dog lunging and hard barking at approach of assessor. Ceased barking when treat was presented, but still showing teeth. Assessor dropped treat and stepped away. Approached dog for a second time, dog this time was not snapping/lunging, but was low growling and extremely stiff. Able to drop treat in kennel and stepped away for another few moments. Came back, dog was on other side of kennel, but was able to call him over and again give treat. Dog continued tense posture with low tail, but ceased offensive behavior and growling.(4/10) Upon intake, one individual surrendering the dog had to place the dog in the kennel; ACA commented that the woman who was also present at the surrender said she was "terrified" of the dog. animal.description:
Meet Tank Man! He’s a 12 years young. If we didn't have records showing he was this old... we would NOT believe it. He is in great shape for a senior dog.
50ish lbs American Bully mix.
Tank is great with young kids, and other dogs- he’s not fond of cats, opossums, or raccoons. No trash bandits to worry about at your house!
He is very relaxed and likes to just hang out. 
He is a little hard at hearing, with his age, but not totally deaf. He knows basic signs though such as “come” “sit” “shake”. 
He is house trained and doesn’t need a kennel. He was with one owner his whole life and a well behaved gentleman.
He likes his walkies and does well on a leash. When something catches his eye though, he embodies his name and sits like a tank. So he’d like a little time to see what he sees before moving on.
He’s just a big love bug! 


*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our dogs are healthy, spayed/neutered, vaccinated and on heartworm preventative. They live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. Many have basic obedience skills and all have been temperament tested. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, please visit our website to complete an application: http://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt

If you have any questions, please see our website: http://www.takepawsrescue.org/FAQ

animal.description:
Puma is a 3-year-old stud muffin!  After being adopted a few months ago, Puma was, sadly, returned to us.  Since being adopted and then returned to us, his confidence has taken a pretty major hit, making him very nervous and untrusting of strangers.  We don’t know much about what happened during his 2 month-long adoption, but we do know that he endured several significant and stressful changes in a very short time and learned that to deal with scary situations, he can be scary himself to back people off.  

Puma is NOT aggressive and he doesn’t want to hurt anyone; he just needs to re-learn how to cope and relax in uncomfortable situations.  His current foster is doing an AMAZING job helping Puma and we’re confident that with continued training and the right family, Puma will be back to his happy-go-lucky self in no time!  We just have to find a patient, loving family willing to put in the effort that Puma deserves to get him there.  

Puma LOVES balls!  He’ll fetch and even drop the ball for you.  He also tears toys apart, but won’t eat the stuffing.  He goes into his crate with no issues, especially when you tell him to “hit the hay” and once he warms up to you, he LOVES to cuddle and give kisses!  One of his favorite things is to have his belly rubbed.

Please help us get sweet Puma into a safe, loving forever home!  If you're unable to help by adopting, sharing this post or donating is always appreciated.  Don't forget, Passion for Pitties is a 501(c)(3), so all donations are tax-deductible!…every little bit helps!

If you’d like to adopt our loving Puma, please fill out an application at www.passionforpitties.com under the “Adorable Adoptables” heading.

animal.description:
Hi there!  My name's Rhyann, what's yours??  I'm 9 years young, and I'm looking for a new best friend.  I was brought to the shelter because my owner was no longer able to care for me.  So I'm waiting for that special someone to come along who will love me forever!

In my last home someone was with me all the time.  There was never a time when I was left alone.  While that was really great that I was with them so much, it caused me to have separation anxiety.  Which makes finding a new family more difficult.  

So I need a family where I can be with someone all the time.  I would make an excellent office dog!  I spend my days in the office here at the shelter, and 'help' with alllll kinds of things!!

I would do well in a home with kids, but would prefer a home where I can be the only pet.  That way I can have all the attention for myself!  

I'm up to date on vaccinations, spayed, and I also have a microchip.  All I need now is YOU to adopt me!!

animal.description:
King was found along side the road guarding the body of his deceased canine friend.  He's a happy boy here at the shelter and loves getting belly rubs. We recommend no small children due to his strength. 

WE ARE CURRENTLY OPERATING BY APPOINTMENT ONLY DUE TO COVID-19
Unless otherwise stated, the adoption fees for dogs over 5 months range from $50-$175. Puppies under 5 months are $175.00. Cats over 1 year are $35.00, kittens under 1 year old are $60.00. Dog adoption fees include a microchip. Cats can be microchipped by request for an additional $5.00.
The adoption fee includes the animal's surgery, vaccinations, flea preventative, deworming medication, sample bag of food/treat samples and a free first exam with participating veterinarians. Shelter policy and 2018 Indiana state law decrees all animals must be spayed or neutered prior to leaving the shelter.

animal.description:
VIOLET is a sweet-natured, 2-year-old, 50-pound Chocolate/Black Labrador Retriever mix.

From Violet's Foster Guardian:

"Violet is a sweet, shy, well-behaved Lab mix with beautiful amber eyes.  She is comfortable in a crate, easily housetrained (She only had a few accidents the first few weeks at our house), walks well on her leash, and doesn’t jump up.  She rarely barks or chews(flip flops are the only thing she’s chewed).  She has learned commands such as sit, come & paw very quickly, so she is easily trained and wants to please.   She will follow commands to sit and stay when putting down her food bowl until we tell her to eat.  Since she’s not a chewer, she doesn’t chew on many toys, but she does enjoy a Kong toy stuffed with things like pumpkin, peanut butter, wet food.  I froze them & gave them to her to keep her from boredom during heartworm treatment. 
 
She is very food motivated, but not food aggressive and she doesn’t counter surf or anything like that.    She is very gentle with taking food and is comfortable with us being close by or petting her while she eats.  She doesn’t usually beg for food when we eat.  If she does, we just tell her no and to go lay down on her bed and she does.  She responds very well to a stern ‘NO’ which we’ve used very infrequently.  Raising your voice or yelling hasn’t been necessary.  She will stay on her blanket, towel or bed if you tell her to and she will keep her kong/treats on it as well.  We’ve trained her to Stop at curbs while walking.  She is sometimes afraid of very loud noises when out walking.  She also isn’t a big fan of going out in the rain, but she is surprisingly calm while inside during a storm or fireworks.  She happily goes in her crate at night & sleeps through the night.    She now loves a car ride & tries to hop in the car whenever we open the door.

We have an inside rabbit. When Violet is in the room, we keep the rabbit in her cage.  Violet may look at the rabbit, but just walks by the cage and doesn’t bother it.  

She enjoys sitting next to us on the floor for belly rubs or while we watch TV.   She lets us touch all parts of her…head, belly, back legs, backside, paws, etc. 
   
I would recommend a metal trashcan with a heavy lid or one inside your cabinets.  She shows a lot of interest in our trashcan when we open it.
The only concern a new owner would have with Violet is our inability to acclimate her to many people during the COVID crisis.  She does not like being touched by people other than our family. (She does prefer some family members over others)   I have been working with friends to try to get her more comfortable.  I’ve had them offer her treats or food and she takes it gently but does not want anyone to pet her.  I’ve had people visit on the porch and she will lay down calmly while we talk.  She does the same thing if I meet a neighbor while out for a walk.  She will also go up and sniff people, but no petting. 
 
As we’ve had more people come in our house, she has recently started barking at people when they come in our house, especially men.  It’s not a very vicious bark.  I am able to get her to stop by petting her and telling her it’s ok and I usually ask the person to offer her treats.  She will bark again, but I continue to tell her it’s ok & soothe her.
   
When we first brought Violet home she was awaiting being spayed, so we were unable to let her near other dogs.  Since being spayed, she is awaiting completion of her heartworm treatment.  We need to keep her calm, so we still haven’t been able to introduce her to other dogs. I like to call her a silent observer.  When we are out and she sees people or dogs walking calmly, she watches them closely until she feels they are at a comfortable distance before she will turn her back on them.  If the other dogs are barking at her, she’s significantly more cautious & may give a low growl or bark back."

WHAT'S NEXT?

If you would like to meet, foster or adopt this pet, please fill out our online FOSTER/ADOPTION APPLICATION which can be found in the main menu of our website or at the bottom of this page - simply copy and paste the link into your browser. EASY PEASY!

Once we've reviewed your application, arrangements can be made for you guys to meet! It'll be kind of like a blind date!

***

This pet is spayed or neutered in accordance with our strict policy wherein all animals are altered prior to adoption. This pet is dewormed, current on vaccines, and started on monthly flea/tick and preventatives.

Animal Alliance's policy is that we will adopt dogs younger than 1 year old to families with children under 9 years old. We do not adopt dogs 1 year or older to families with children under 9 years old due to the unknown history of adult dogs. 

BY APPOINTMENT ONLY:  Meetings at our Adoption Center are by appointment only (no walk-ins).  An online adoption application is required and must be approved prior to meeting any animals.  Adoption appointments are set up by email by our Adoption Coordinator (no phone calls, please).  This process ensures our dedicated time to the animals in our care, as well as full attention to adopters at scheduled times.  

Prior to submitting an application, please see the Animal Alliance Adoption Process for adoption details.

To fill out an adoption application, go to:
https://www.animalalliancenj.org/fosteradoption-application/

animal.description:
Yes he is available to adopt - you must apply in order for us to set up a meet and greet if he would potentially suit your home

PLEASE READ BELOW IN FULL:

WHY IS HE LOOKING FOR A HOME?
Duke has been at the kennel for a year.

This boy's owner moved from Manitoba in 2019 and put the dogs in boarding in the Fall.

Sadly she passed away Feb 26th/2020.

Her son was unaware she had dogs.

We believe they were adopted as pups within the same time frame in 2013.

The kennel got a hold of us and asked us to place them. (during covid initial shutdown)

BEST HOME -
A quiet home is best suited for him to gain trust with you.
No kids/preteens nor dogs is best.
It would be best for him to have a home in a remote area, with few visitors/guests.
We believe that an apt/duplex/condo with people coming and going would be less than ideal for him.

Duke would do best with a dog savvy owner as he is fearful of certain situations and of people in his space - such as someone met him and bent over to rub him in to spots and he growled and was nervous of what was happening.

DOGS -
We have not tested them with other dogs.
Owner said they should not be with other dogs.
Duke is said to be fine with the kennel owner's small dog.

CATS -
They were said to have lived with cats.
They have not been tested with cats.

KIDS -
No kids or preteens for Duke at all please - he was nervous near one when eating treats at our  initial meet and greet.

PEOPLE SKILLS -
Duke likes the people at the kennel.
He takes time to trust and warm up to new people.
He does not like people getting in his personal space, and he will let you know if you do by trying to back you off, by growling, giving body language to show the warning, and lunging if you continue not to listen.
Therefore he has not made a good impression on the applicant that met him and sadly he can't live in a multi family dwelling so did not suit the other applicant's home.

TRICKS -
Duke will shake paw, lay down and roll over with a treat.

VETTING -
Update - after covid restrictions began lifting a bit the boys went for their checkup May 27th/2020 and got vaccines/deworm/chip.
The kennel also groomed them.
+
He was also boostered June 26th/2020.

WHERE DID HIS FRIEND GO?
Ginger has been adopted and Duke is still living at the boarding kennel.

VEHICLES -
Duke rode very well in the vehicle.

WEIGHT -
His weight waivers from 37-40 kg.

Adoption fee is $400

HOW TO APPLY -
If you are interested in adopting please read the following -
*We only adopt within Ontario
*We do not do same day adoptions. 
* No viewings without an approved application
*We do not deliver pets.
*Inquiries will not be replied to when all info and link to application is provided below.

All info on adoption process/policies can be accessed at www.adoptapet,lucknow.on.ca 
**.Applications -http://www.adoptapet.lucknow.on.ca/applications.html
It can be completed, saved and emailed back to the rescue at 
petrescue@hurontel.on.ca

animal.description:
Meet Master Charlie Brown, Chaz, Chuck, Chucky-Boy anyway you cut it he is a clown!  Charlie  is  by far one of our most interesting dogs.  For  years Charlie was part of a bonded pair.  He  loved  his  girlfriend MERE  and they were always together.  Finding  both of them a home together was  an impossible task. This past Winter Mere  passed  away from cancer.  We  thought Charlie  would  crumple and die but instead he proved us entirely wrong.  He  was on the rebound before he even hit the rim. We  decided  to enhance his adoption chances  by sending him to training. What an amazing surprise that was!!!  There was  a whole  side of Charlie  Brown he kept  a secret from us  for 4 years.  He quickly learned his commands (which we think he knew  but didn't tell) then he became Mr.Popularity at the camp.  He  loved  every dog there and could play non-stop keeping up with the best of them. He was smittened by the trainer  and couldn't keep his eyes off her  which in training is a good thing, We  sometimes thought Charlie  wasn't  the sharpest tool in the shed  but  we  were  wrong again.... he  had the propensity to learn quickly.  Add it all up.... this  is  one  amazing and highly adoptable dog ! Hope  you are interested in meeting him. It  would be well worth it...just no cats please,  we haven't tested him with one.  Charlie  is up-to-date on shots, neutered, chipped and ready to go home. 
His adoption fee is $200  and that will save another dog in need!

Once she warms up to those around her, she is a happy go lucky girl with everyone she meets. She would like a home that will take her on adventures, continue her socialization, and give her lots of love. She wants a person/family who will provide her with a life of mental and physical stimulation while keeping her safe and happy. She may be small, but she would like it if there is a plan for longer workdays, so she is not spending too much time in a crate or alone. 

Dayana came to us from a fellow rescuer.

We hold an event every weekend at our facility on SATURDAY 11-5pm.   Please visit our social media platforms for the specifics for each weekend as it changes from week to week. Please find our application at lovejoyfoundation.org when you come to an event please bring that filled out in hand with you. You can find our application at Lovejoyfoundation.orgYou MUST submit an APPLICATION via email in hopes to get an appointment, our application is found on our website lovejoyfoundation.org. If you do not get a phone call by Friday then we did not have anything available for you or the pet of interest was adopted before we got you application. We are a Southern California based rescue and do nothing adopt further than an hour from our headquarters in Inglewood, Ca. we do not adopt out more than a 30 minute radius. We appreciate you being understanding and Patient as we attempt to go back to a new normal.

We'd like to introduce you to a very special girl, Miss Maizy. She came into the Maricopa County shelter on Christmas Eve of 2019. She's been waiting such a long time to find her forever home and we just know that perfect family is out there somewhere.

Maizy is sweet, calm and easy going. She's all about quick walks to the ice cream truck and lounging with her peeps. Love you some snacks and couch time? So does she! Enjoy the peace and quiet? She's on board. Do you find yourself telling those neighborhood kids to get off your lawn? Maizy is your girl.

She's been in foster with our good friends at Dog's Eye View Board and Train for almost 6 months and has learned so much but it's time for her to move on to her forever. 

Maizy is approximately 7 years old, spayed, vaccinated and microchipped. She does have arthritis so she will need to be on medication to ease her pain but she sure doesn't let that stop her! She also suffers from seasonal allergies, so her furever family will need to keep up with her allergy meds. She would do best in a home with older or calm children and prefers to be an only pet so she can get allll the attention to herself.

If you're interested in meeting her, please submit an adoption application: https://www.oneloveaz.org/adoption-process

All dogs in our VIP (Very Important Pits) Program receive post adoption support and access to our free weekly Mutt Manners training classes. Maizy will also receive free lessons from A Dog's Eye View.

Adoption Fees vary based on shelter promotions but are generally less than $50.

COMPASSIONATE RE-HOMING FOR SENIOR DOG

Magi (

pronounced

Maj-eye) is a sweet 14 1/2-year-old Lab/Chow mix is looking for a new home.

Magi is 89 lbs.

She has been an emotional

support dog for a disabled person for many years but her person is no longer able to care for her. Now it is her turn to be taken care of and spoiled.

This senior pup deserves peace in her golden years...this beautiful, shiny soul who is so sweet and loving. She would like a person(s) who will give her a lot of love and spend time with her.

As she has gotten older, her needs have changed.

Magi needs to be an "only" childno cats, no kids.

Another senior dog might be okay, but a younger one maybe too much for her

.

Unpredictable behaviors are

harder for her to deal with at her age. She would thrive in a quiet environment where her person is home a lot.

She has had a couple of moves in the last 18 months due to no fault of her own so she may take a month or so to settle in and feel safe.

A consistent routine would really help with this and she is looking for a patient and compassionate human to call her own.

At her age, she sleeps a lot but

loves to go outside for short walks and

enjoys learning new things!

She has a slight heart arrhythmia (on meds for that) and arthritis as well as some hearing loss but makes her way around just fine. Unfortunately, she cannot manage stairs as they would be too much for her at this point. Her back leg/hip are weaker and gives her some pain from arthritis.

I know a senior doggie is more work and expense so I would be more than willing to help with veterinary bills. We also don't mind pet sitting if ever needed as she knows us and it would be familiar surroundings for her.

If you love senior dogs and willing to take on a new animal friend, and would like more information, please contact:

animal.description:
****PETronus Rescue endeavors to include all pertinent information for each of the dogs within our organization with regard to approximate age, potty training status, kennel training status, temperament, activity level, dog/cat friendliness, etc in an effort to give those considering adopting as much information as we have.  Inquiries requesting additional information will not be returned, due to limited volunteers. Thank you for your understanding **** 

Meet Chip.

Chip was picked up off the streets in Houston as a stray in January 2020. He is a young dog (estimated to be between 1 and 2 years old) that had previously no obedience training, but is very smart and eager to please. He has learned sit, stay, walks into his kennel (whereas before he would not go in willingly). He loves to play and if his new home has dogs they need to be playful (or at least tolerant of a young and playful guy!) While he is playful, he can also relax once his energy needs have been met. He can be shy in new situations at first, but has warmed up to his foster and will thrive with routine and more socialization.

All PETronus Rescue dogs receive basic vaccinations (distemper/parvo, bordetella, & rabies), spay/ neuter, and microchip prior to adoption. We also treat any know medical issues, including heartworms.

Our dogs live in foster homes while they wait patiently for their forever families to find them. This is beneficial in that they learn house manners, crate training, housebreaking, etc while they wait and we are also able to get a very realistic picture of their energy level, temperament, etc so that we can place them in a home that is the best fit.

Our adoption fees are $200 for dogs over 1 year of age and $250 for dogs under 1 year of age. Puppies receive 3 rounds of puppy vaccinations.

If you are interested in adopting one of our amazing dogs, please fill out our adoption application here http://bit.do/PRAdoption and we will be in touch!

animal.description:
Location: Langley BC, CanadaKing Arthur
Breed: Pitbull terrier mix
Age: 5 yrs
Gender: M, neutered
Wgt/Hgt: 47 lbs / 26 inches tall
Energy level: Average. Medium-high (when playing)
Relations: Good with dogs after intro, teens, kids/ Not so good with cats
Highlights: sweet, smoochy, good walking on leash, rides well in car, loves to play ball and go for walks, house trained
Region: Mexico

Knights, assembled! Honoring my name, and as the truthful king of smoochies, I'm looking for honorable folks to spend the rest of my life with. If you're up for becoming a part of the Pittie round table, I'm your perfect match!

I am a sweet boy who is super handsome, calm and well-adjusted to being around people.

I was found on the streets of Mexico wandering around; it seemed as if I hadn't been abandoned for very long. I almost got ran over by a truck, but my rescuer managed to get me out of the avenue, safe and sound.

My rescuer and her family decided to take me in, so I could be safe. Apparently, my looks could have put me in danger. Sadly, my rescuer's country isn't the most pitbull-friendly place.

I must've had experience with travelling by car before, because things went perfectly all the way to the vet. The doctor said I had no health issues, and after a few days, I got neutered, vaccinated and dewormed (not my favorite moment, to be honest).

Since then, I've been taken care of by my rescuer and the vet's team, especially by a very sweet 14 year old guy with whom I spend the most time. I can get a little anxious when "my" person leaves and will softly whine. https://youtu.be/939J5WPyZe4.

I don't care much for crowds though and feel a bit stressed at that time.

My caretakers say that I'm the smoochiest dog ever, a good kiss is all it takes for me to be ever affectionate and just overall happy.

Listening is one of my strongest suits, so you can always count on me for that. I love sausages, so they'd do the trick if you want to train me. I can be a little stubborn at first (I'm a king) but I learn pretty fast, so I'll pick up the commands after a short time. https://youtu.be/2r8GFznskqo.

I always have a great time exercising, but I know how to walk calmly on a leash and pretty well ignore most everything. https://youtu.be/S5p7IPOBrvQ.

I'm smart, obedient, clean, and house trained. Yea. I like other dog's company, but I think I will do best as the only one in the house. I sometimes move forward and growl at other dogs when they get too close. With a couple meetings, I usually become friends. I don't like sharing my toys with other dogs when playing though. https://youtu.be/IxHbYTo5rj0.

I have been around a couple of young children and it went well. I just think I might be a little strong to hang out with them often, but I definitely get along with teenagers. They're my favorite!

Not usually many problems with cats, but since I don't like them too close, I can growl when I get stressed, and they can make me a little tense. But you can be sure that my years in this world made me a true gentleman, emphasis on the gentle part!

I don't know why, but recently I've started to bark at many things while in my crate. I'm typically not much of a barker. I just want to be part of a family, where I can hang out with you.

I enjoy any kinds of activity with my human knight, whether it be relaxing after a long day, or racing together in the morning. My energy level depends on what I'm doing, so I can be pretty relaxed while watching a movie or pretty energetic while playing ball (I love it!).

I'm a very adaptable guy. A back yard with a tall fence (since I know how to jump quite high when playing ball- yes, I am quite athletic) would be nice, but I also like going out for walks to enjoy the air and the view. I look forward to starting a new life in Canada and will be sure to bring lots of love and fun to my new home!

I have been neutered and vaccinated.

My adoption fee is $500.00 CAD, this includes my airfare to Canada.

Disclaimer: It is important for all applicants to visit our website, http://www.lovedatlastdogrescue.ca/adopting/ and read about Loved at Last Dog Rescue.

Information included in the profile is provided to us from the international rescuer or local fosters. LALDR does not have access to overseas dogs and cannot always verify the accuracy of their descriptions. Every dog is an individual and can act differently in different situations based on the person adopting them and the environment in which they live.

The age and breed of a dog is usually an educated guess, so we are not able to guarantee the accuracy of age or breed of our dogs.

Normally, we will not approve adoptions to homes with children under 12 years of age. More information can be found on our website.

animal.description:
Mun is about 2.5 years old, approx 50 lbs and we believe she is a dobie Shepherd and possibly Rottweiler mix.  She was dumped at a high kill shelter when her owner's moved and did not take her with them.  

Initially she is shy of new people but once she knows you she is a friendly pup and very social.   She warms up to and will trust a female faster than a male. However, she will accept men with patience. We do not know her history but believe she was abused by a man, so patience is ideal if there is a male in the home.

The best way to Mun's heart is with treats.  She is like a head-strong teenager who wants things done her way but she also knows when she does something wrong.  She is an Alpha female and is extremely intelligent and an experienced owner would be best and recommended for Mun. A fenced yard or avid runner would help burn her energy.  (Running would be okay once the heartworm treatment is completed).

 She loves toys and treats.  Mun loves to ride in the car, likes to be brushed, and be with her person.  She can sometimes be protective of her toys as she has a tendency to resource guard until trust is  built.  Her current foster mom can take toys from her without a problem.  

Mun has a lot of personality and once she warms up to you she will be your best buddy and sit on your lap and snuggle.  She will bond to her person.

The pictures do not do this beautiful girl justice at all.  She is gorgeous in person.  We are working on getting better photos too!

Cats would not be advisable in Mun's world.  She does not like cats.

The perfect home for Mun would be the only pet so she can have all the attention.  A female only home would be great, but, a home with a male will require some patience in the beginning but will work given time.

We now there is the perfect home out there  for Mun.  Could it be you?  

Mun is spayed, up-to-date on vaccinations.  She is heartworm positive and we are doing the slow kill method which is monthly heartgard which has been started.  Her remaining heartgard will go with her adopter to finish the treatment.

This little lady is named Moe. She is a Xoloitzcuintli/Chihuahua mix who is only two years old. Once she warms up to you, she will be the BEST cuddle bug around! Since she is fearful of strangers, she needs a VERY special and understanding adopter. Someone who is dog savvy and can work with her, patiently. This is NOT to be taken lightly, she is small but has shown aggression in the past (she HAS AND WILL BITE AGAIN if given the opportunity) when introduced to new people in an uncomfortable manner. Do not expect Moe to be a normal doggo, she likely will never be comfortable with strangers. She has even been known to bite humans shes comfortable with. An adopter who is dog savvy, patient, and persistent is a must. A calm and quiet home without children, cats, and frequent visitors would be best for her. A home without a man would be preferred as she has never been known to trust men. She prefers dogs her own size but is currently doing well in a foster home with large dogs. This little lady is house trained on a schedule and is also crate trained! When she was rescued, we noticed that she has major skin issues. Were working to resolve this issue but it may take months to years before fully recovered.

The adoption fee for this pretty girl is $225. She has been spayed, microchipped and is up to date on vaccines!

Want to meet Moe? Submit an adoption application and someone will be in touch to schedule a meet n greet to see if shes the right match for you!

animal.description:
Action Jackson (AJ) came to us as owner surrender from a family that neglected three other dogs we had to seize. He was kept in a pen until he arrived here to live in a kennel. He is around 2 years old. He is extremely affectionate! He sits next to his person, on their feet, or climbs on them constantly. He is very, very needy. He does not like other animals and he would need help with house training. He is very intelligent and seems to catch on fast (we have kept him behind the counter some and he does wonderful). He can jump very high as well as climb a fence so he cannot be left unsupervised in a yard. He is a really sweet and happy boy that will make someone really happy they have him, he just needs a little bit of help. He was born on Christmas Day 2018.

Update: AJ had a foster home for about a month. He improved dramatically on his behavior and really improved his housebreaking ability to about 90%. The foster worked very hard with him to help him understand not everything (including people) are a chew toy lol. He got a lot of walks/hikes to help with his energy. Unfortunately, the foster was not able to keep him due to their work schedule and having no one to help with AJ's schedule. The foster felt it was not fair to AJ and we understood.

Everything in the first paragraph still holds true. He needs to be an only and he is very sweet while also being very energetic. He needs a special adopter and will require a home visit to foster/adopt. He rides great in a car and walks great on a leash. He loves to be held.

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Garth. I'm sometimes called Garth-a-mus.

I was rescued after I was found abandoned in an apartment with another small dog. For whatever reason, though we got along great, she was happy go lucky and I actually have some anxiety left from the experience.

Because of that, I'm a happy go lucky guy when I am able to be independent. I'm more of a let's hang out as pals kind of dog, rather than a lap lover or cuddler. I'm perfectly happy to follow you around, watch what you are doing, and going on outings like buddies.

I am looking for a forever home with an experienced family. This is an absolute must. Because my past is unknown we don't really know why I have a few issues but I really don't like to be picked up. I really want to work to be okay with it but I just really struggle with it so I am an all 4 on the floor kinda dog, just like big dogs are. Speaking of dogs, I like to play with other dogs my size and would do well in a home with them but I can also be on my own as well. While I enjoy spending quality time with my people friends, I am also content to spend time on my own as I have an independent spirit.

Even though I do get along with others, due to my size, age, personality, and anxiety, I would do best in a home without children.

My foster parents have helped me to learn manners or what we call 'Petiquette' and how to be calm though I still sometimes have trouble controlling my excitement and impulses. When socializing I have a hard time with new people so I will need someone who is willing to let others know that I am your buddy, but not everyone's buddy if you know what I mean.

I know basic commands and I 'sit pretty' to get my meals. I love to go on walks but I am still working on how a harness feels. With the right one, I do great though! I am also crate trained and love to have my personal space. Oh, and I also love to jump and dance when I achieve something I'm a bit nervous about. My favorite words to hear are 'YOU DID IT!' :)

If you think we may be a good match, or you would like to get to know me better, please complete an application at https://www.smallbreedrescue.org/Home/AnimalAdoption/54

PS: I weigh about 7.5lbs, my vaccinations are up to date, I am microchipped & neutered, and my teeth have been cleaned :)

Due to home introductions that are part of the adoption process, we can only accept applications for interested parties who are in or near San Diego County, California at this time.

animal.description:
BEAU the Brave is a 57 pound approx. 2 1/2 yr old pitt mix.  This big, beautiful boy is very quiet and mild mannered.  He is happy-go-lucky & LOVES people and is fine with kids.   At his foster home he lives inside the home with the family and other dogs.  Beau isn’t a big fan of  unfamiliar dogs & May growl.  However, once properly introduced he’s fine.  Beau is house & kennel trained. (He sleeps in a kennel at night.)    Although Beau gets along with most other dogs, we recommend that he not be in a home with other large male dogs, especially around food. Food aggression is a trait that many rescue pups have and can be overcome with time and proper training. However, at this time, we wouldn't adopt him to a home with other large male dogs    Like many rescue pups, this furbaby is HW+,  but please don’t let that scare you.  He’s asymptomatic &  is currently undergoing the *slow-kill method of treatment (see more information below).  

All our adoption fees include spay/neuter, micro-chip, up-to-date vaccinations, including rabies thru date of adoption. This pup is heartworm positive and is currently being treated with the *slow kill method, approved by her veterinarian, on prevention & on flea/tick prevention. 

*The slow kill method of treatment, simply stated, is a 30 day regiment of  doxycycline followed by a monthly dose of Advantage Multi for 12 months, then retesting.   Most dogs test negative after one year of following this treatment; however, we always recommend that potential adopters consult & follow the advice of their family veterinarian upon adopting any of our hw+ pups.   Although the fast-kill method is still considered the "gold-standard" by the AVA, and may be preferred by some vets; the slow-kill method has proven to be effective in our rescue. The main reason we utilize this method is due to our limited financial constraints and the high number of our rescue pups that are infected.   In the cases of severe infection and if the pup is highly symptomatic, we sometimes use the fast-kill approach instead.   Again, we recommend for you to consult with your veterinarian after the adoption is complete and follow their recommendations.   

In order to be considered for one of our beautiful pups, please go to our website and complete and application: https://www.mustluvdogs.org/adoptable-pets.
Please note that we are a DUE DILIGENCE adoption organization. Part of our approval process requires, among other things:
* Experienced pet home with verifiable vet references/history preferred, but we realize that everyone has to start somewhere, so all applications will be considered.
*The majority, but not all, of our pets require a fenced yard or secure enclosure.  In the case of apartments, we require Landlord approval and designated dog area in complex.
*Verifiable good veterinary history INCLUDING regular vaccination/visits and good Heartworm Prevention history is a MUST!
*Adopter must be able to have time to spend with the pup and be able to provide the pup a safe environment to live.
*ALL our dogs are expected to be primarily INSIDE dogs.  They MUST sleep inside the home.  We truly understand that some folks have working dogs (i.e. farmers, ranchers,etc); however, the majority of our dogs have had a rough life prior to coming to us & we want to make sure that they are showered with LUV & maybe even a bit spoiled for the rest of their lives. 

Other facts are also considered, including whether children or other pets are a good fit with the dog. 

Must Luv Dogs reserves the right to deny any applications that we don't think are a good fit with the pup. Our first & foremost concern is the dog's best interest. It is our MISSION to place them in a home that is a great fit for their needs for a lifetime of luv & being part of a family.
*We will consider adoptions in any area; however, will do not ship or transport puppies under the age of 12 mos. We will ONLY transport an adult dog on a transport approved by MLD, at adopter's expense.
* In order to be affordable and afford every family an opportunity to have a pup of their own, we keep our Adoption Fees low; however, please keep in mind that the fees we charge do not cover all costs for the pup.  Any additional donations are greatly appreciated!

Please note that all of our pets are in private foster homes. In order to reduce any stress or confusion for our pups, we require a completed, approved application BEFORE setting up a meet & greet for any of our pups.  Alternatively, you are always welcome to come meet any of our pups at one of our regular Adoption Events.   Our events are always posted on PetFinder OR on our Facebook page: https://www.facebook.com/mustLUVdogs.org.

Finally, THANK YOU for considering Must Luv Dogs for your next pet. 

*Most dogs require a fenced area in yard. 
*Apartments okay IF nearby dog park or walking trails (with landlord appoval).
*ALL dogs must be INSIDE dogs and treated a part of family. 
*We are a DUE DILIGENCE Adoption Rescue.  
*Must have good Vet history & Heartworm prevention is a MUST!
*ALL dogs are fully vetted, spay/neutered and microchipped prior to adoption.

She loves to be outside, but will also curl up on the sofa to nap!   If you're lucky, she will give love and cuddles. She is an alpha female and would probably do best as the only dog, unless you have another dog who is submissive.   Queen Mikki loves her bed and blankies. animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Name - Kora

Age -Adult

Weight - approx 60 lbs.

Medical - Kora is on Fluoxetine. This is a daily medication to help with anxiety

Other dogs - Kora is dog selective and can be dog reactive on walks. She has previously lived with other dogs and would require a home with very easy going dogs who would co-exist with her. She needs slow intros or would be best as an only dog

Cats - No. She does have a high prey drive

Kids - Kora's previous family had children and they said she was good with them. She has not recently been around children

Background - Kora originally came to us in 2013 when she was rescued from by a Good Samaritan from an awful situation where she was kept on a heavy chain in someone's garage. We adopted her out to what we thought was a good family. Unfortunately they dumped her just a few short years later. We adopted her out again in 2016 to what we thought was her Forever Family. Unbeknownst to us, they gave her away to yet ANOTHER family. Supposedly that family loved her dearly but was forced to surrender her to our local shelter when they had to move and could not take her with. Thankfully her chip is still registered to ITP and the shelter called us to let us know she was there

Crate trained - Kora is used to sleeping and eating in the crate

Leash trained - She can be leash reactive to other dogs (pulls and barks). Her Foster Family has started walking her with a backpack and this has helped her have better leash manners, although she still needs some work in this department

Housebroken - Perfectly house trained and will use the doggy door

Eating Habits - Eats normally, not a picky eater

Commands known - Kora knows sit, down ,stay, bed, crate, leave it, wait, gives her paw and knows her name. She is a very smart girl

Car rides - She is used to being crated while in her Foster Family's minivan

Bath time - Loves to go in the shower with warm water. She loves being pampered!

Affectionate - Kora is pretty independent. She is not overly affectionate. She is happy to sit near you or rest in the same room as you

Activity level - Moderate activity for her age. Foster Family walks her about 30 minutes a day with the backpack on and this seems to be plenty of exercise for her

Play style - Occasionally she might chase the ball or tug rope but she is not really into toys

Bad habits - Her worst habit is the reactivity to other dogs while on leash. Foster Family has been working with our behaviorist to correct this behavior. Being on the Fluoxetine has also helped calm her and her being able to relax has helped

Redeeming qualities - She is so calm and quiet for the most part and she has the best manners! She does not jump on you, she takes treats softly, she knows her commands and we really appreciate her independent nature

Best feature - Her cute soft ears!

What Foster Mom/Dad wants you to know -
"It breaks our heart that Kora has been let down and abandoned by her people so many times. We can't blame her for having anxiety now - she has been bounced around from family to family for all of her life! We are working on providing a relaxing environment for her to help with her insecurities. She really is such a good girl - very smart and sweet. The medication, along with daily exercise, really seem to be helping her relax. We hope a patient family will fall in love with Kora and promise to never abandon her again! She deserves her Happily Ever After once and for all."

Please consider sponsoring Kora with either a one-time or monthly tax-deductible donation. Your donation will help It's The Pits with day-to-day care, including food, vaccinations, flea treatment, treats and toys. Click on the Sponsor This Pet link above to make your donation today. Thank you!Complete an Adoption Application! 1/30/21 3:35 PM

animal.description:
Luna is a very sweet and beautiful girl.  She is paralyzed but making progress.  .  She was lying on the floor of the shelter, dumped by owners as she grew more paralyzed.  I couldn't leave her there.  She has been diagnosed with SMA spinal muscular atrophy.  One vet wanted to euthanize her immediately and another gave her 6 months to live.  She has surprised them all and is almost a year and a half.  She had some swimming rehab and it helped tremendously.  She can now stand with her wheel brace and move.  She needs someone who can give her lots of time and love and water rehab.  She has defied all odds so far; who is to say she can't go much farther!

Please no children under 8.

She is vaccinated, spayed, hw negative and microchipped.

Tara is a 43 pound, approx 4 year old pitt mix.   She is a gentle giant with a beautiful, old soul.    She is laid back and calm.  This sweet girl spent the first 5 years of her life at the end of a short chain, living outside with little love.  Thanks to her foster family, she now lives with a family of humans who show love and affection to her regularly.    She loves nothing more than to stretch outside on the porch and nap in the sunshine. Tara also appreciates a good, long back-scratching session from her humans!    Please give this precious girl a family of her very own to love and adore.   She will make some lucky person or family the most loyal of all pets.   Like most rescue pups, Tara is heartworm positive, but is currently undergoing the *slow-kill method of treatment (see more information below).  

All our adoption fees include spay/neuter, micro-chip, up-to-date vaccinations, including rabies thru date of adoption. This pup is heartworm positive and is currently being treated with the *slow kill method, approved by her veterinarian, on prevention & on flea/tick prevention. 

*The slow kill method of treatment, simply stated, is a 30 day regiment of  doxycycline followed by a monthly dose of Advantage Multi for 12 months, then retesting.   Most dogs test negative after one year of following this treatment; however, we always recommend that potential adopters consult & follow the advice of their family veterinarian upon adopting any of our hw+ pups.   Although the fast-kill method is still considered the "gold-standard" by the AVA, and may be preferred by some vets; the slow-kill method has proven to be effective in our rescue. The main reason we utilize this method is due to our limited financial constraints and the high number of our rescue pups that are infected.   In the cases of severe infection and if the pup is highly symptomatic, we sometimes use the fast-kill approach instead.   Again, we recommend for you to consult with your veterinarian after the adoption is complete and follow their recommendations.   

In order to be considered for one of our beautiful pups, please go to our website and complete and application: https://www.mustluvdogs.org/adoptable-pets.
Please note that we are a DUE DILIGENCE adoption organization. Part of our approval process requires, among other things:
* Experienced pet home with verifiable vet references/history preferred, but we realize that everyone has to start somewhere, so all applications will be considered.
*The majority, but not all, of our pets require a fenced yard or secure enclosure.  In the case of apartments, we require Landlord approval and designated dog area in complex.
*Verifiable good veterinary history INCLUDING regular vaccination/visits and good Heartworm Prevention history is a MUST!
*Adopter must be able to have time to spend with the pup and be able to provide the pup a safe environment to live.
*ALL our dogs are expected to be primarily INSIDE dogs.  They MUST sleep inside the home.  We truly understand that some folks have working dogs (i.e. farmers, ranchers,etc); however, the majority of our dogs have had a rough life prior to coming to us & we want to make sure that they are showered with LUV & maybe even a bit spoiled for the rest of their lives. 

Other facts are also considered, including whether children or other pets are a good fit with the dog. 

Must Luv Dogs reserves the right to deny any applications that we don't think are a good fit with the pup. Our first & foremost concern is the dog's best interest. It is our MISSION to place them in a home that is a great fit for their needs for a lifetime of luv & being part of a family.
*We will consider adoptions in any area; however, will do not ship or transport puppies under the age of 12 mos. We will ONLY transport an adult dog on a transport approved by MLD, at adopter's expense.
* In order to be affordable and afford every family an opportunity to have a pup of their own, we keep our Adoption Fees low; however, please keep in mind that the fees we charge do not cover all costs for the pup.  Any additional donations are greatly appreciated!

Please note that all of our pets are in private foster homes. In order to reduce any stress or confusion for our pups, we require a completed, approved application BEFORE setting up a meet & greet for any of our pups.  Alternatively, you are always welcome to come meet any of our pups at one of our regular Adoption Events.   Our events are always posted on PetFinder OR on our Facebook page: https://www.facebook.com/mustLUVdogs.org.

Finally, THANK YOU for considering Must Luv Dogs for your next pet. 

*Most dogs require a fenced area in yard. 
*Apartments okay IF nearby dog park or walking trails (with landlord appoval).
*ALL dogs must be INSIDE dogs and treated a part of family. 
*We are a DUE DILIGENCE Adoption Rescue.  
*Must have good Vet history & Heartworm prevention is a MUST!
*ALL dogs are fully vetted, spay/neutered and microchipped prior to adoption.

animal.description:
Have you met Roxy?

15-year-old Roxy and her sister Pinky were surrendered by their former owners to the San Diego Humane Society because they were moving and their new home didn't allow dogs. We rescued them with a bunch of other SDHS seniors so we didn't know they were sisters at first. Then, we noticed they were never apart, always cuddled into small beds together, and were nervous if they other left for vetting or grooming. It was clear - these girls are best friends and we will only be looking for a home that can take them together. Roxy has a perfectly frosted face and man is she a fighter! She was surrendered with a huge hernia and a broken leg. She had surgery to repair her hernia and feels like a new girl. Roxy will eat anything and never says no to a snack. Roxy is crate trained and has never had an accident in her crate or overnight. Roxy is a mellow girl, but does get random spurts of energy; she may only have three good legs, but this chick is FAST when she wants to be.

Roxy and Pinky live in a foster home. Their Foster Mom shared, "Here comes Roxy! Roxy is absolutely loving her retirement retreat. She's so happy, energetic, and just full of life. She may have three working legs but boy she's fast when she gets excited! Best board game companion. Absolutely adores her younger sister, they are just so sweet together!"

Please submit an application to schedule an appointment to meet this lovable duo! Apply here: www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/apply

Visit us at Open House: Saturdays & Sundays, 10 am - 1 pm

Learn more about our programs at www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/family. No adoption fees and we help with medical costs!

Questions: adopt@frostedfacesfoundation.org

animal.description:
This is Pinky!

13-year-old Pinky and her sister Roxy were surrendered by their former owners to the San Diego Humane Society because they were moving and their new home didn't allow dogs. We actually didn't realize that they were a bonded pair when they first arrived at FFF but it soon became clear! These two go together like peas and carrots! Because of their bond, we will only be placing them in a home together. Pinky is the cheeky playful sister. She is solidly house broken and would never even dream of going potty in the house. Pinky likes to hide her treats for later, even though it means her sister with the super sniffer will find it and eat it later. Pinky enjoys long walks, chasing bunnies, and sunbathing naps in the afternoon. She cries in excitement when she sees a potential friend on walks and playfully greets them upon intros.

Pinky and Roxy live in a foster home. Their foster mom shares, "Pinky is most definitely the biggest cuddle monster ever created. She
is a big energy bundle, she loves to hike, run, and just be outdoors! Roxy loves to be carried outdoors and just look around - what a life!

Cuddling together remains their favorite activity though!"

animal.description:
Lily's mom was a purebred Boston Terrier.  She had three huge pups which required a C-section and soon died from complications of the surgery.  The three pups were hand raised by Grandparents who were taking care of their deceased son's young boys. .  

Eventually the grandparents realized the kids had no interest in the pups so we ended up re-homing each pup.  When we finally got Lily she was over 4 mo old and a bit spoiled.  

She was a house dog.  By the time she reached age 6-months she started to stray off our property and run bunnies.  So we had to lock her up becasue she went missing over 24 hours. Such a terrible life to be locked up.  She shares a pen with a 6 yr old male Mountain Cur, Wiseman, and a female Pit Rat Terrier mix, Pamela. 

This 30-35 pound beautiful girl needs a home with an active owner or kids who will enjoy playing with a dog.

We don't know how she is with cats.  Good with dogs, kids, strangers. 

Call Marilyn at 573-722-3035 to adopt Lily from 9:30am to 9:30pm Central Time.  We have adopted dogs all over the USA, however during the Corona Virus we do not have volunteer transport help nor can we fly dogs.

The address for our rescue center is 34 County Road 2266, Brundidge, AL 36010. We are one turn off Hwy 167. No appointment necessary for pets that are located at the rescue center. Appointments must be made to visit pets in foster homes. Location information will be listed beside the pets name if they are at a location other than our rescue center.

Questions can be emailed to troyanimalrescueproject@gmail.com or call 334-508-2367.

animal.description:
Boston Mix - Happy BoyMeet sweet boy, Mickey Jacuzzi, who is a 6 to 7-year-old American Staffordshire mix with a little Boston Terrier in him. He is a strong boy at 57 lb. He's fine with all people including kids (bigger are better because of his size) but needs an only-pet home.

Mikey would love to have a home and family of his own. He came from a shelter as a stray. We found out he likes to go fishing and will jump in the water to fish on his own if you aren't careful!

Mikey is a very sweet boy and tries his best to follow your direction (see the video). He likes to be near his human and will spend some short cuddle time, but his favorite is to play and roll around in the grass. Mikey is neutered, UTD on vaccines, microchipped and heart worm negative. He has even had a dental done!

To find out more about Mikey Jacuzzi, call his foster mom, Sharon, at 865-255-5567. Mikey's adoption fee is $175.00 He is located in Knoxville, TN. If you are interested in Mikey the 1st step is always an application found on our website: www.bostonterriertn.org

NOTE: Submission of an application and fee does not guarantee adoption of any specific Boston, since that particular dog may have applications pending or may not be the right match for you.
Please use the foster momma or dad's contact information above for questions.
The process always begins with an application which can be found at The Boston Terrier Rescue of East Tennessee website
Note that in most cases, we do not adopt to families with small children, e.g., 'under 6,' as a precaution to the child's safety and the dog's safety. In some cases with larger Boston mixes or other dogs, we do make exceptions. Please ask the foster momma.
We prefer to place dogs within driving distance of where they are being fostered. If someone from outside the local area is approved for adoption, they must be willing to personally drive/fly to get the dog. The East Coast division (NC/SC/VA/MD/DC) does have special transport capabilties for their kids. Ask them.
Also, submission of an application and fee does not guarantee adoption of any specific Boston since that particular dog may have applications pending or may not be the right match for you.

animal.description:
BRADLEY WOULD LOVE TO BE IN A FOSTER HOME WHILE HE IS WAITING TO BE ADOPTED. IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN FOSTERING BRADLEY, PLEASE GO TO THE MAKE A DIFFERENCE RESCUE PAGE AND SEND A PRIVATE MESSAGE THAT INCLUDES YOUR PHONE NUMBER AND EMAIL ADDRESS. 

Bradley is a 2 year old Terrier mix. He loves to be outside, hang out with humans or snuggle up on the couch. Children 16 years old or older. Bradley is good with dogs after a very slow proper introduction is done. Unfortunately, we do not know how he is with cats. He loves to go for walks, play and just do whatever you want to do. His forever home must have a fenced yard where he can safely run, play and hang out with his people. Bradley is neutered, up to date on his vaccinations, on heart worm preventative as well as house and crate trained. Bradley would make a great companion dog.

All dogs we rescue stay with us until they find their forever homes. We do not do same day adoptions. A home visit is required to ensure our dog is going to a safe environment and our dog gets along with your dog(s) and/or cat(s). We require all our dogs over the age of 1 year attend 1 obedience class (6 week session) outside the home. You must live within 1 hour of Birmingham, MI to adopt one of our dogs. No out of state or outside the U.S. adoptions or fosters. Bradley's adoption fee is $275.

animal.description:
Odin’s first week in foster care! 

He’s still adjusting to being in the new surroundings. Odin is the most mellow, sweet boy! ??? completely house trained, doesn’t jump on furniture or bark, loves his bed, treats, and stealing my ?? (socks), he likes being brushed and is the goodest boy during bath time. 

We have been walking almost every day...I haven’t noticed any limping. Odin is the easiest dog to take care of and would be a great addition to a quieter home. He did great with other dogs on a walk and meeting my mom, sister and 10 yr old nephew. So older children would be best. Odin weighs about 50 lbs and has an estimated birthdate of April 1, 2020.

Our adoption fees vary, Shelter Dogs are $150, Prison Dogs are $200, Puppies are $250, and Popular Pure-Breeds are $400. The price includes: a Home Again Microchip, set of shots, de-worming, heartworm testing (if old enough), spay or neuter, and a 1 year rabies shot (if old enough). All dogs adopted must leave with a county license at an additional cost of $17, this fee is cash only. The adoption fee can be paid using credit card or cash.  If you are interested in this dog, please call the shelter at 614-879-8368 or fill out an online application at www.hsmcohio.org

HSMC Adoption applications must be done at www.hsmcohio.org  Please do NOT click on the "Adopt Me" button on this bio. It is only a pet inquiry. If you have additional questions about this dog, please call the shelter at 614-879-8368 or contact us through our website!

animal.description: Well hello there! My name is Millie. I'm a bit of shy girl, but can be oh so silly when I have doggy playmate around. I haven't had the greatest life, but I'm now building confidence in people and myself. To help me continue to learn and grow, I think I need a doggy companion to help me out. I'm not especially fond of kitties. To tell the truth, they kind of scare me. I enjoy playing fetch and tug of war. I would prefer my forever home have older children as younger ones make me nervous. I'm sure, with the right family, I will shed my introvert self and flourish into an amazing companion for you. I am house and crate trained, and walk on a leash. I am spayed, vaccinated, microchipped, and tested heartworm negative. I would like an active family that can exercise me and is not gone long hours. I can get bored and destructive if I'm left home alone or in a crate for long hours. My adoption fee is $200 in greater Houston area or $550 (includes adoption fee, health certificate, and transport fee) out of state. Fill out an app at www.soca-fbc.org/adoptables.

animal.description:
German Shepherd Mix 3 years Female Medium 50lbs We found Hema on the side of the road bleeding profusely from his right nostril and took her to two different vets since the first one could not get the bleeding to stop. He stayed at the vet for 3 days while they tried to figure out why she would not stop bleeding. The bleeding was stopped. She was very skinny, and in poor nutritional health so felt this maybe the problem. She has been with us for several years and her nose bleeds if there is hot weather and if she is in direct sun light. She is a special needs dog because of this. She may have a genetic disorder. Von Willebrand's disease. She is best for a home with no kids and no other pets. Hema does have shedding issues due to some skin problems that require daily care. She is not good with strangers and barks excessively if she hears people coming around. Hema can be destructive with household items so its best not to leave her unattended. She also likes to dig and jump fences so you need to have a large high fence. Hema can have separation anxiety as well if left alone too long. She also may have accidents in the home so she has to be watched to be taken outside to go to the bathroom.We do not have a central location to see our dogs. Meeting any dog is by appointment ONLY currently. Appointments can be set up to meet any dog in San Diego. Currently we are unable to do any out-of-state adoptions.

If you are interested in a particular dog please FILL OUT an Adoption Application at our website @ http://bajadogrescue.org/ready-to-adopt/adopt and we can schedule you for an appointment to meet with a particular dog if it is available. We do require an application if you are interested in adoption. If you are interested in potentially adopting please fill out an application at http://bajadogrescue.org/ready-to-adopt/adopt. Your application will be reviewed and you will be placed on a waiting list for the dog(s). If your name comes up on the waiting list(s) we will contact you. You can see the dogs we have available for adoption on our website at http://bajadogrescue.org/shelter-dogs/

Please check out our FAQ's page at http://bajadogrescue.org/faqs/.

Questions? Check out our Ready to Adopt page at http://bajadogrescue.org/ready-to-adopt/.

animal.description:
Meet AJ
AJ is a happy hound. He was rescued from Animal Control, with his companion Mindy. They arrived at our shelter on April 1, 2020. 
AJ is a wonderful older dog. He’s a seven-year-old hound/shepherd mix. He’s a larger dog, but he moves gracefully and calmly so don’t let his size fool you.  He has beautiful manners. He’s calm, sweet and very friendly. He’s a lower energy sort of guy and prefers to relax with his people and his best friend Mindy. AJ walks well on a leash and he knows basic commands. AJ is happy to go along to get along. He’s just a big love bug who will make for someone’s best companion. He’s very low-key, but loves to see what Mindy is up to and happily follows her around.  AJ and Mindy are a bonded pair and must be adopted together. The way they depend on each other, it’s like a seamless ballet. Each dog brings out the best in the other and together they are probably less effort then having one dog, because they complement each other so well. They’re recent arrivals and we have yet to test them with other dogs or cats, but will do so for potential adopters. Our guess is they could be house-trained, because they are so polite and smart, but it may take some remedial training since they have been without a home for a little while now. 
AJ is exceptional. He seems to be the quintessential family dog. It’s crazy to think he and Mindy ended up homeless. We have no idea of their back story, but they are a delightful pair who would make for a great addition to any family willing to open their hearts and home to them. 
AJ is neutered, fully vetted and micro-chipped. 
Call 706-865-4135 for information on additional health services provided as part of the adoption fee.  If interested in one of our puppies or dogs, please submit an application online or at the shelter. Applications can be submitted online at: https://www.charlessmithgallhumanesociety.org/page/dog-adoption-application 
Once an application is submitted online, you will receive an email saying your application has been successfully submitted.  If you don’t receive this email within 24 hours, please check to make sure all application fields were completed or please call our shelter at 706-865-4135. All adopters must complete an approval process which involves a reference check with current/recent vet and a brief home visit if located in the immediate area. We do permit out of state adoptions. Adopters MUST come to the shelter to transport their new family member home. We do not ship nor do we transport them to their new homes. Adoption policies and application procedures are detailed at the shelter website: http://smithgallhumanesociety.org/ under tab All Adoptable Animals.
Charles Smithgall Humane Society (CSHS) is a No kill shelter. Animals in our care remain safe with us until adopted. Resident animals are primarily owner relinquished and also accepted from local Animal Control. The facility usually is operating at capacity with a list of animals waiting for space to open.
Adoptions and meet and greets are being scheduled by appointment only. Please call our office, email us or complete an application and someone will be in touch just as soon as they can. 
Location: 4823 Helen Hwy. 75N, Sautee, GA 30571, Phone: 706-865-4135
Email: smithgallhumanesociety@windstream.net

animal.description:
Meet Mindy
Mindy is a wonderful dog. She and her mate AJ were rescued from Animal Control and came to our shelter on April 1, 2020.
Mindy is an Australian Cattle dog mix. She’s about five years old and of medium size. Mindy celebrates her herding roots and has good energy. She loves sitting on your feet and makes a game of getting you to go where she wants to go. She definitely likes to work and keep busy, but her energy is not overwhelming. Given she’s five years old, she is more mature and seems pretty happy-go-lucky. She is very smart and knows some commands. She is leash shy, but does okay once the lead is slipped on. She loves ear scratches and she’ll vocally tell you how much she appreciates the attention and how good the scratches feel. She has a beautiful red and white coat and her eyes reflect her intelligence. Like, AJ, we haven’t tested her with other dogs or cats, but will do so for potential adopters. 
She and AJ are a bonded pair and must be adopted together. Mindy relies on AJ for comfort and security and AJ loves to be where Mindy is. Adopting this pair may be easier than having an only dog. They complement each other and their interactions are seamless. They love being with people and welcome attention, but they are also content to relax and explore the yard together. They are a delightful pair, who will be no more work than if adopting just one dog. 
We do not know Mindy’s and AJ’s backstory, but they are polite and may even be house-trained given how mature they are and how well they act. Not sure how they found themselves at Animal Control, but we’ll do everything we can to find them a perfect home and give them a second chance at a happy and secure life. Mindy is a little gem and AJ is a wonderful companion. 
Mindy is spayed, fully-vetted and micro-chipped.
