animal.description:
Adeline is a 2 year old beagle that has special needs. She was surrendered to us in early 2020 when she developed hind end paralysis. Addy, as we call her, has shown immensely improved ability to stand and walk since she came to us, though she will likely never have a truly normal gait; she no longer requires a wheelchair to get around. She is currently being fostered by All Breed Grooming, Boarding and Daycare; she loves other dogs! Addy will do best in a home without children. Addy bonds hard with her people and does those excited beagle bays when she sees a familiar face! Adeline’s ideal home would be with someone who is retired or works from home; once you get a routine established, her care is really not that time consuming. Adoption applications are at ITVrescue.org.

All of our animals are examined by a veterinarian, given age-appropriate vaccinations, dewormed, microchipped, spayed or neutered, heartworm tested and treated if necessary.

Please realize that many of our animals are kept in foster homes. Please complete an adoption application at http://itvrescue.org/adoption-application/ in order to meet with one of our animals. There is no obligation in completing the application, but it helps us find an animal that is most appropriate for your family.  The ITV Rescue Center is open Tuesdays 12-5; Wednesdays 12-7; Thursdays 12-5; Fridays 12-5 and Saturdays 10-5.  The Rescue Center is located at 1417 N. Stockwell Road.  You are welcome to come to our rescue center during open hours to see all of our great adoptable animals. Thank you for your interest in our animals!

NOTE: Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable, so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label.

Glory is ready to find a family to spend the rest of her life with...could that be you?

Glory can be a bit shy when you first meet her but give her a little time to warm up to you and you will see her sweet personality come shining through. Before coming to us, Glory's life was one of suffering and severe neglect. Now, thanks to the dedication of an amazing foster Mom, Glory is learning how to be part of a family. Glory's ideal forever family will be patience, loving and understanding when first getting to know her. They should understand that Glory is a creature habit and does best with a daily routine, also that she is a home body who enjoys snuggling in her favorite chair. Glory has learned to really enjoy spending time with her people and her foster mom says she's a great listener and most of all she's incredibly loyal. Glory is potty trained, crate trained, and walks great on a leash. We also believe Glory will do best in a home with no other pets....and honestly we think she deserves to be the only recipient of all your love!

Glory is a 2-3 year old, 35 pound Terrier mix. She is up to date on vaccinations, spayed, microchipped and she is on monthly heartworm prevention.

If you would like to adopt, please fill out our application!

animal.description:
PLEASE NOTE,DURING THIS PANDEMIC/SHUT DOWN- We have been swamped with applications, inquiries and phone calls.  It's been impossible to even keep up with responding to everyone as we would not get anything done considering the overwhelming numbers of people reaching out about all our rescues. 

We can no longer answer phone calls or inquiries because, by the time
you INQUIRE  if a pup is available, we have had at least 3-6 APPLICATIONS.  The dog is gone before you can even then fill out an application.  

As volunteers in rescue, it is all we can do to keep up with responding to multiple applications.  Interested parties should fill out an application.

The shelter listed our boy as "Pup" and guessed him to be around 5 years old. His last day plea and his sweet face caught our attention and it didn't take more than that for us to reach out and say.....Diamond Dogs Rescue will Take him!  Since our rescue, he was fully vetted, neutered, microchipped and made ready to find his family.  Pup is medium sized weighing around 50lbs

Currently being fostered in New England he lives with two adopted Diamond Dogs and does very well with them.  However, we have learned that proper introductions are important and that a dog that matches his energy level is best suited.  He is dog selective.

Pup has herding instincts so he would do best in a home familiar with those breeds.  Your experience in handling will make such a difference in how well this dog fits into your home.    Due to his visual impairment, we recommend a home with no kiddies, kitties or other small critters. He loves to play with some other dogs,  to be outside (fenced in yard best), being brushed and curling up at the foot of the bed at the end of the day. 

Note on herding dogs- they show remarkable intelligence, agility and energy. As working dogs, they thrive on activity and sense of purpose. Some of the breeds in this group make excellent family pets, but families need to be cautious of heel-nipping varieties who might try to herd the little ones.

If you are interested in adopting Pup, you can fill out the online application by going to:
https://www.123formbuilder.com/form-2521188/

Follow us on Facebook for updated photos and more information on our adoptable pets!

Meet Tempest

Tempest is now available for adoption. She is a very sweet 4 year old Pit mix. Tempest is definitely on the smaller side, and only weighs about 40 lbs. 

Tempest came to us locally. She was placed on a euthanasia list because she couldn't handle being crated constantly. She would get so excited when someone would meet her, and would jump and run around (we don't blame her). We placed her into a foster home and she does very well. She loves to play, and definitely has puppy energy. She is potty trained, and crate trained. She gets nervous in smaller (her size) crates, but is just fine in extra large ones. 
Tempest is a little shy when meeting new people, but warms up very quickly and her tail never stops wagging. She knows basic commands, but can definitely use continued training. She is VERY smart and just wants to make you happy. Tempest does well with children, but older children who can play with her and handle her constantly wagging tail are needed. Tempest cannot be in a home with other animals. 

Tempest needs just a few things in order to be successful in her forever home. 
She needs:
-Training and consistency 
- To be the ONLY pet
- A fenced in yard or to live in the country with  lots of room to run and play
- Someone to snuggle with

If you are interested in meeting this beautiful girl, please go to luckypawsmidwest.org and fill out the adoption application on our website.
Help us find Tempest her forever home!! ?

Tempest is vaccinated for rabies, distemper, and bordatella. Tempest is spayed and is microchipped. Tempest's adoption fee is $350 plus WI state tax!

If you are interested in meeting Tempest, please fill out an application at luckypawsmidwest.org. Once your application is approved, we can set up a time for you to meet Tempest!

Lucky Paws Midwest is licensed and inspected by the State of Wisconsin: 402655-DS

animal.description:
Shakira came to us as a stray and is around 3 years old. She received her name because we were so overflowing with dogs at the moment that we had to stick her in the dropbox and she proceeded to howl/sing in a cackle that made everyone laugh.

She LOVES people. She is also extremely energetic and loves toys. Sadly, she has been here so long that when you go to walk her, she will also pull on the leash trying to tug you with her to go faster. She sits patiently in her kennel and looks depressed at you to guilt trip you (she is extremely intelligent and manipulative lol).

She started off very dog aggressive. However, we have put her in one of our yards and another friendly one in another yard and she has done nothing, but wag her tail and run the fence line with them. I think previously, she was likely never exposed to other dogs. She is likely going to be dog selective just based on that from what we have seen from her.

We have put her behind the counter some at work. She does really well when you are with her, but if she is left alone, she will chew anything and everything. And I mean anything. I think that is because she was bored. We have also cratetrained her in the hallway near the counter. She will whine, cry, and bark to be with us when she knows we are around while she is crated. I think that would sort itself out pretty easy, but she needs someone who is patient.

I am not saying all this to dissuade anyone from adopting her. I am being upfront so the right person can be prepared, because she is truly a wonderful dog. A lot of these neurotic tendencies sort themselves out away from the shelter. The best adopter for her is going to be someone who wants a really energetic dog to take running or hiking, that has no other animals (another dog in the home could be possible also), no cats, and does not have small children. I do not think she would be aggressive to children in any way so do not be alarmed with that, but I would be cautious that she would knock them over when she gets rambunctious. Older children that are probably 7/8 years old or up should be no issue.

She is going to be extremely attentive, loving, smart/trainable, and perfect for the right person. Sadly, I think she was dumped out on purpose because of her energy level and no one wanting to train her. 

She requires a home visit to adopt.

animal.description:
Atia is a beautiful, young (2yo), energetic purebred Bull Terrier. She is ready to be your adventure buddy and explore the PNW with you! 

She weighs around 40-45 lbs, and though she is petite, she will need a strong leader both physically and mentally.  She is sweet and independent yet eager to please and has responded well to treat training.

REQUIREMENTS TO ADOPT:
- Bully experienced home
- Must be the only dog in the home
- Fenced yard
- Kids 10+ (she will knock down smaller children accidentally)
- No cats or other small critters

As is typical with most Bull Terriers, Atia is strong yet silly and exhibits traits such as stubbornness and bursts of spunky energy.  She is a goofy gal who loves to go and would make an excellent hiking or jogging buddy.  

While Atia must be the only dog in a home, she does fine on leash with other dogs in situations such as hiking or going for walks, but cannot be in nose to nose proximity.

Atia is spayed, UTD on shots and microchipped. Her adoption fee is $450.

*ADOPT ME!*
Birdie - 5 years old, located in Florida
Dog ID#: 200821-P-B-GA
Intake Date: 4/16/2020
Available Date: after heartworm treatment, around June 2020 

Meet Birdie! This precious little lemon was found running at large in Georgia in early March, scarred up, light heartworm positive and extremely underweight. She sat unclaimed for weeks, and now she is SAFE! Bird Bird is currently 39 lbs - her target weight would be closer to 45 lbs. She has not been treated very nicely and must have had some poor outdoor living conditions based on the old scars on her legs. Birdie has had her treatment for heartworms and she is doing great!

Birdie can be shy meeting new people, but once she has been introduced to new friends, she is puppylike in her behaviors, following people around and wanting to stick close. Birdie loves being indoor dog, and she loves to explore the yard with her foster family as well. Birdie startles at loud noises, so a fenced yard would be safest for her. Birdie is good in cars, and calmly watches the world go by during car rides.

Birdie is good with cats and most dogs. She has learned to play with other pointers in her foster home. Birdie would LOVE to have someone home a lot with her, or to be able to go to work with her family. We can't wait to see what her future looks like, this little lemonhead with an underbite is SO cute!

Want to learn more about one of the dogs we have up for adoption? Fill out our adoption application (http://www.pointerrescue.org/adopt.html)!!

He does have some separation anxiety and does not like to be left alone at home, he currently does well when left home with his dog brother. He does like to get into the trashcan so that needs to be put up when you leave the house. He finished his heart worm treatment without any issues. He does have some arthritis. He would do best in a home where someone is home with him often and willing to take him on a walk most days.

Tanner is a happy, affectionate, athletic boy. He is so smart and loves to learn. He enjoys playing fetch and going for walks/runs. He currently knows: sit, stay/wait, down, leave it. He is currently working on "relax" on his "spot". Tanner also has a sad side to him. He is nervous around new people, but everyone that has given him the time and patience is showered with affection. 
We are looking for a foster-to-adopt situation with no other animals or children where he can grow into his new home and both he and his new person can learn about each other over time. He will need to continue his professional training and visits with his specialist vet. A home with a backyard is a must. His new person should be female as he warms up to women much faster. Must have some experience with dogs, preferably large dogs. Experience with rescue or fearful dogs is a huge plus. 
So if you are a woman who lives alone with no other animals or children in a house with a backyard, has a big heart, experience with nervous dogs and is active, Tanner needs you!

Note:  Not all animals attend every adoption event. Please contact us for more information on this dog.
Note:  Adoption fee includes sales tax.

animal.description:
8/1/20

NOTE FROM PA FOSTER:

This is Rori, I wanted  to let you know that I am  fostering Millicent, the blind, senior Pomeranian, and to give you an update on her. The last time I updated you on her was before she had her first heart worm injection and she was not doing well at all just with the doxycycline she was given prior to treatment. With her fragile condition it was decided by the processors that it would be best for her to stay with me throughout her treatment. She made it through all her injections and treatment and she is finished with all medications as of 3 weeks ago. She is such an amazing little survivor and I am so incredibly proud of her!!! I have been giving her some time to adjust to being off all medications especially since she does not tolerate any medication well, and have been observing her in hopes of some improvements. Unfortunately, I do not think her incontinence is going to improve. She continues to have a very weak bladder and whenever she is up and walking around she has some leaking at least every 15 minutes or so as she is walking or moving. I have been trying to get her to adjust to being in diapers for the past 4 months and with her older age and being blind she does have balance issues and wearing the diaper seems to make her more off balance and she is very anxious. I have tried diapers of all different sizes. materials, and fit, but she does not really do too well with any of them. She does also have a collapsed trachea, but as long as she has quite a bit of room to move around and get into a comfortable position, she does well. She also needs to eat dry food only because she seems to gag and throw up on the consistency of canned food. She needs to eat two times a day or she gets very weak and lethargic, but mornings are very hard for her and she is a bit cranky and out of sorts, so morning feeding is hard since she needs to be coaxed and supervised as she eats which takes about 20 minutes or so to get all the food into her. She does much better with her evening meal and eats independently. She sleeps quite a bit throughout the day and does not really have any leaking or accidents, but once she is up for the first hour she has no bladder or bowel control and there is a lot of cleaning up after her required. Then the real bad accidents taper off some and the cleaning up is not as extensive. She likes attention after she has been awake for awhile and mostly likes to be held in someones arms as they are standing since she gets uncomfortable if not stretched out with her trachea. 

4/1/2020

Millicent is a very sweet, loving, and gentle senior Pomeranian who is 12 years old. She is a tiny little one weighing just 6 pounds. She is blind, has a heart murmur, and heart worm disease. Even though Millicent is blind she is amazing and navigates around her foster home very well. She does like to have some extra space to move around in so she prefers a pen where there is more room rather than a crate. She stays very nicely in her pen and loves to take naps and relax. She also loves to snuggle in her foster mom's arms. She is house trained and walks nicely on a harness and leash, but likes to take short, slow walks because she does get tired easily. She lives with other small dogs and cats in her foster home and gets along with everyone. Because Millicent is quite fragile and small it is recommended that she live in a home with older children or only adults. 




  To begin the adoption process please, fill out our online application. Go to wagsrescue.com and click on adoption form.
Please call Susan @ 267-312-3372 if you have questions.

animal.description:
BAILEY WILL SOMETIMES FEAR BITE - if you don't mind being bit, feel free to inquire about her, you MUST, in your inquiry, state that you don't mind being bit.  Otherwise, you will NOT receive a response.  We are sorry, but please understand, we KNOW she's cute.  But something VERY bad happened to her.  She's been adopted and returned several times because of the biting, she's GREAT, but she WILL sometimes bite!  The times she mainly bites are when she's startled or, when she's having a harness put on her or taken off her.  She needs an ACTIVE home WITH ANOTHER DOG (this is a requirement because she gets along great with other dogs), and no children!  Bailey is available to LOCAL applicants only, you must live within a reasonable driving distance of Farmers Branch, TX, 75234.  Once you're approved to adopt Bailey, you will need to do the following:
-Go to the dog park MULTIPLE times, where her current foster dad takes her daily, it’s located in Farmers Branch
-Interact with Bailey until Bailey is comfortable and allows you to touch her, which doesn’t come easily or quickly.  Her foster dad has been taking her to the dog park for weeks - if not months now, and everybody there has tried to touch her, they’ve been giving her treats etc and, while she will take the treats, she still will not let anyone touch her, and these are people that she sees daily!
-Demonstrate the ability to take a harness off Bailey and put a harness on Bailey (these are some of the main times she tends to bite)
Once Bailey is comfortable enough with allowing you to do the aforementioned, we can proceed to a trial adoption.  We hope you understand but Bailey is a special needs case and getting to know her and be able to touch her is going to be a very slow process of building trust.  We are doing this for Bailey's well being.  Thank you.

animal.description:
During the state mandated shelter-in-place order BACS has transitioned to virtual, socially-distanced adoptions.
If you have an interest in a particular BACS animal, please email KSwanson@cityofberkeley.info. The first step will be to set up a virtual meeting with their current foster family via phone, zoom, or facetime, to provide you with more detailed information about the animal. Following that, if you feel like it could be a good adoption fit, shelter staff will help coordinate a socially-distanced meeting in person so that you can meet your potential family member up-close and personal. Thank you for your patience during this time. We really appreciate your support!

Orla is a bundle of love. She loves everybody--people, dogs, even cats. She hasn't spent a ton of time around children while in our care, but the few instances where she did interact with them, she seemed mostly uninterested in them. She loves to snuggle and be the center of attention. At the dog park, she is delightfully social. Sometimes her play with other dogs can become rough, but when dogs correct her, she listens and backs off. She's a great off-leash hiking dog. Orla would love to live in a house with a yard. She loves to find a nice sunny spot and snooze. Her hobbies are snoozing, destroying stuffed animals, playing tug, playing with other doggies, snuggling, getting rubs, and eating bones. She doesn't need to be the only pet. We've worked with her on leash training, obedience, and separation anxiety. She has made plenty of progress in all areas, but she is charmingly stubborn and still has room to improve. Orla needs a family or person who can give her stable and predictable routines, Orla settles in quite comfortably.

animal.description:
PLEASE READ THIS PROFILE AND THE REQUESTED CRITERIA BEFORE CALLING OR SUBMITTING AND APPLICATION. THANKS FOR YOUR ATTENTION AND CONSIDERATION.
PLEASE ALSO FOLLOW HIS FOSTER MOM ON INSTAGRAM BEFORE YOU APPLY. https://instagram.com/quirky.canines?igshid=85dxg1w8x3vc
Please read all his posts and reach out to his foster to under his behavior and issues before applying. Parker receives numerous inquiries but will need someone who understand dog behavior and are ready for a challenge.
Meet Parker! Parker is a 5-6 year old, 18 lbs., shih tzu mix. He loves affection, being petted, and most of all he loves treats!

Parker was found at a park, hence the name Parker. He was extremely scared, matted and malnourished. After a few days of decompressing, he started to come out of his shell. He currently is scared of being picked up and we think that whomever must have owned him, never gave him affection. He is already crate trained, he loves it, He is slowly starting to jump on his fosters lap and enjoying the affection. He would be ideal in a home with older children and other friendly dogs. We believe he would be just fine with cats. He does enjoy car rides and walks.

Note from his Foster:

Parker does love cuddles and once he trusts you, he loves being petted. He uses doggy stairs to go into bed to snuggle. Parker loves and greets everyone but he does attach to one person in the household stronger. As he feels better and comes out of his shell, you'll find Parker playing with toys and running around with you. He walks extremely well on a leash and will follow you wherever you go. Food is the quickest way to his heart. He is all smiles and will even give a playful grumble to get his meals or treats quicker. Parker isn't looking for playmates, he'd prefer to be the apple of your eye. He's be fine with older animals, quick movements make him nervous, and he does get jealous. He has learned to sit and be petted before his meals and he goes to the door to be let out. We love Parker and he is a great dog but he has challenges that most people may not be prepared to handle. He has issues being picked up or petted too quickly, especially around his face lower back areas. He will show his teeth and sometimes bite. We emphasize this because it is an issue. We believe he was abused but on top of that he has pain issues. He has done better with pain meds and they will be a necessity. But he will need a patient adopter that can understand he can and most likely will be challenging.

Please follow Parker on his fosters IG at @quirky.canines and there you will see all his posts. You can find our adoption application at https://muttsandrunts.org/adoption/ Our adoption fee is $150-350 depending on the age of the dog and includes vetting, spay/neuter, updated vaccines, microchip & registration, and current flea/tick treatment. Our fee does not include cost of transportation.

animal.description:
Hi my name is Tommy.
I'm looking for a confident companion, who lives where the wild things grow. (I prefer no neighbors.) I want to be able to adventure through the woods and roll in fields. I'm a home body, who wouldn't enjoy socializing around town. Even visitors may make me nervous, so I'd like to go lay down when they come over at least until I know they are friendly.  
But! I promise to be the bestest friend as long as you will guide me with confidence, patience, & love. I may not be that cute little puppy, but sometimes I play like I'm still little and I am definitely cuuute! I love to cuddle, and love nibble on my humans fingers. And also smother them with all my weight in love.. The staff say I have eyes that can read humans like a book! And I'm sometimes too smart for my own good. I have a few tricks up my sleeve like sit and shake and sometimes lay down. I haven't spent much time with small kiddos, so I think I'd rather live with big ones right now. I havent met alot of dogs, but I have a girlfriend here & we make out through the kennel. (Shh I'm not supposed to kiss and tell.) If you think you have what it takes for this special boy, don't wait another moment! He needs you! 
www.marshmallowfoundation.org

Arrived: 6/24/20 Vaccinations are current, neutered and dewormed. 

Hi everyone! My name is Tommy and I’m looking for a family to call my own! I arrived at the shelter after my older person could no longer care for me. Before arriving at the shelter, I spent a lot of time outside so I am learning all kinds of new things about being an indoor pet. The nice people here call me a quick and eager learner that glows with praise and encouragement! I’ve even shown good potty training habits!  I’ve worked a little with basic commands like sit, stay, heel, come and down and did pretty well for a beginner! 

My ideal home would be an experienced dog person or persons with a yard for me to play in, preferably fenced, perhaps with another dog to help show me the ropes and grow my confidence.  Once I am comfortable, I love my people and routine and will seek out attention whenever possible.  Older kids would be ok as long as they were active participants in my training and growth. Once I learn about life as an indoor pet, I am sure I will LOVE them to pieces! 
Visitors to the shelter are by appointment only and after an application has been submitted online:

Volunteer Application:    http://www.marshmallowfoundation.org/info/display

animal.description:
Zoey is a beautiful young sable German Shepherd female estimated around 1 year of age. Zoey was a stray and we unfortunately do not know her history but Zoey is happily looking forward to having a family of her own.

Zoey is a playful and rambunctious young girl. Her favorite activities include playing in muddy ponds, getting all the love, and inappropriately barking at unknown dogs and people. Zoey is learning how to navigate the world and make new human friends. While Zoey can be a very friendly and social girl she is at a critical point in her life known as the 'fear period' and can struggle with reactivity when meeting new people. It is extremely important that Zoey have a confident, experienced, handler that can compassionately guide her through the safe socialization she needs in order to learn how to navigate the world kindly. Zoey is very much a puppy and while eager to please she is still figuring out what is expected of her and how to rise to those expectations. Zoey has been great meeting volunteers with the guidance of her foster home and with those she knows is a very loving, playful girl. She has enjoyed going on hikes around private property and exploring ponds and mud puddles. Zoey is an active and athletic girl who is going to require ongoing exercise and structure to ensure her growth into a well rounded adult Shepherd. Zoey would be a great running companion, hiking buddy, and would likely excel in a number of dog sports. Zoey is NOT suitable for a home with children at this time.

Zoey is still figuring out other dogs and how to interact in a polite manner. Zoey can be very vocal when she meets new dogs and was defensive with other dogs when she arrived at her foster home. She has since settled in and is able to enjoy playgroups with other young Shepherds as well as group hikes. Zoey is slowly figuring out that she can play appropriately and doing a great job. Zoey will require ongoing structured socialization and guidance to maintain her progress as she is at an age of development where her socialization both in and out of the house is vital. Zoey is NOT friendly with cats or small dogs as she has shown a very high prey drive with both.

Zoey is a young, eager to please, and outgoing Shepherd who is searching for an active, loving, and adventurous home to give her the guidance and love she needs to grow into an even more wonderful companion. If you're the home for Zoey please email Tierhavenrescue@gmail.com for an adoption application or visit tierhaven.rescuegroups.org for FAQs

Buddy O'Pal is a German Shepherd, with a birthdate of March 2013. Buddy does have some trust issues so will need to meet his adopter a couple times prior to adoption. Buddy loves country living and would love a large yard to play in. No cats tho. 

Buddy is very smart and very loyal once he gets to know you. Due to his trust issues, there should be no children in the home.

Buddy was recently attacked by another dog so is a bit fearful of other dogs. So Buddy will need to have a slow intro with any other dogs in the home.

The suggested adoption donation for Buddy O'Pal is $200. We are a 501c3 organization which means that your donation may be TAX DEDUCTIBLE. Your donation goes toward the high cost of veterinary care for our animals in rescue, as well as providing supportive services to animals in homes.

Information about the adoption process: All adoptions require a completed ADOPTION APPLICATION. Once your application is approved, we will put you in touch with the dogs foster to see if you and the pet are a good match. If so, we will arrange a meeting for you and the pet. The adoptions for all of our animals will take place in the Omaha, NE area and must be done by the adoptive family in person. We do not ship or deliver.

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dogs needs. If you and the dog are not a good match, we will help you select another dog, or we will keep your approved application on file for 6 months.

To learn about Muddy Paws Second Chance Rescue or donate to our animals, please visit our website at MuddyPawsSecondChanceRescue.com or our Facebook Page.

animal.description:
Oh Jeffrey, or Jeff as his friends call him. Goofy, sweet , silly , charming (when he wants to be) and of course handsome. Just Around 1 years old Jeff is basically an overgrown puppy with no manners. 

As sweet and handsome as this goofy boy is, Jeff sometimes struggles with meeting new people. More specifically he struggles meeting them on leash. He also has a harder time meeting some men vs. women. Though “leash reactive” as we call it, we have been working with Jeff to help him safely interact with new friends while on leash. We have also been working on some Muzzle training with Jeff. It’s safe for every dog to be comfortable in a muzzle to protect them, as well as others. Though he has shown improvement in many areas he still has much to work on. Any adopter should be prepared to work on training with Jeff. 

Because of his weird quirks we do not feel Jeff would do well in a home with kids under the age of 16.  We do feel Jeff would do best in a home that can provide him structure and routine that can help him succeed to be the best dog we know he can be. 

Thought he has quirks Jeff has many great things about him. Once Jeff is comfortable with you he has no problem giving you a few sloppy kisses. He likes to give hugs too, but we are teaching Jeff that he doesn’t get attention when jumping up on people. Right now we ask him to sit and then he gets his beloved head and butt scratches. He sometimes thinks he’s part cat when he tries to rub all over you for more. 

Jeff also does really well with other dogs who match his goofy play style. He really wouldn’t mind a confident brother or sister that could show him the ropes. But he would do well without one also as long as his new family understands he will need exercise and structure in his daily routine. 

Oh and car rides, Jeff loves them. Especially if they end in a hike where he can explore all the smells and sounds around him. Also, though he may protest sometimes, Jeff does very well in a crate here at the rescue, and goes right in for staff when asked. 

If you think Jeff would be a good addition to your family, please fill an application out at dogtownrescue.org Jeff is up to date on vaccinations, neutered and microchipped.

Charlie is an amazing dog who has unfortunately had her world turned upside down.  She was with her family for her entire life and then they dumped her at the shelter stating she was reactive coming out of her crate but they also indicated she was crated A LOT! Since she has been with us we know this: she handles all touching (even nails and cleaning her ears!), can be left not crated and sleeps all night, she is great on walks but gets vocal when she sees other dogs, she loves her people hard so you have to be ok with her laying on top of you and lots of kisses.

Charlie is an anxious dogs in new situations and therefore needs time and a routine.  If you are interested please complete our adoption application on our website.  We would do multiple meets as she literally does not act like herself at first! We are also a very different kind of rescue - our dogs and their adopters become family so with a dog like Charlie that needs a little extra support we would sponsor training and overall would slowly transition her.  Charlie is ok with dogs she knows but will need to be the only pet also!

Looking for a pretty gal that will brighten up your day? Then contact us at Paw It 4ward at adopt@pi4w.com

animal.description:
As animals are posted, we begin receiving adoption applications. With one volunteer available to review all applications, we ask for your patience waiting for an email response. While we are closed to the public, we will only be responding to pet inquiries that accompany an application. Adoption appointments are scheduled first come with approved application, first served. (See our adoption procedures below.)

Not only does Joyce own the dress, she can model it! This smart young lady knows so much. Joyce is petite with a big personality. Unfortunately she got into trouble by jumping over her owner's short, metal fence while he was away. So with a privacy fence, Joyce could be the best diva you could ever adopt! She's about at precious as they come! Joyce's estimated DOB is 8/2018, she weighs approx 29 lbs. and should grow in size.

Joyce was generously sponsored by Regan Ellis during our virtual Reigning Cats and Dogs event. Thank you Regan for sponsoring Joyce!

HSPC's adoption fee is seventy-five-dollars through December 31, 2020, unless stated otherwise within the pet's description. At times, our adoption fees are lowered during special events that are posted to our website or Facebook page. Every pet that is available for adoption has been spayed/neutered, microchipped, and is up-to-date on vaccinations including heartworm preventative (canines). Adopters are required to schedule a wellness exam with their veterinarian at their cost within 7 days of adoption.

Please only submit one application. Once you are contacted by email, you will have an opportunity to provide us with any additional animal(s) under consideration.

animal.description:
Damian is around 6 years old and weighs approximately 14 pounds. He is estimated to be a pomeranian/sheltie/chihuahua mix. He requires a patient and experienced adopter and not a first-time pet owner. He has a medium energy level and loves to play. He really enjoys playing fetch! See a post on our Instagram, @poochmatch, for a small clip of him laying fetch with a volunteer. He is very sweet and loves attention. To receive attention, he will jump on your lap for you to pet him: IT MUST BE ON HIS TERMS. He likes to hop up on your lap instead of being picked up and put there. He belongs in a home where he is not expected to interact with visitors or strangers. Damian is NOT suitable for children. If you have kids, grandkids, kids that visit, grandkids that visit, or interested in having kids in the future, he would not be a good match. He requires a quiet home that will let him adjust at his own pace over a couple of weeks, not a couple of hours. Once he adjusts and builds TRUST with his adopter(s), he is happy and sweet (as seen in his photos and video). His trust with you must be built slowly. If you are looking for a dog to be immediately friendly and settled in your home within a couple of days, Damian would not be a good match. He gets along well with other dogs after a proper introduction, but does not require canine companionship. He is not well suited for the dog park/beach. Damian is doing well with leash and crate training. His adoption fee is $365 which covers the cost of his neuter, all core vaccines (Rabies and Distemper/Parvo), blood test to ensure he is in good health, microchip and microchip registration. If you’re interested in adopting, the first step is completing an application which is available on our website, Poochmatch.com, under the adoption tab. Please read the following paragraphs for additional information about our process.

If this listing is still posted, we are still accepting applications for him/her. We do not do out-of-state adoptions on highly adoptable dogs; we would only consider out-of-state adoptions for dogs that prove hard-to-place locally. We cannot hold dogs, please submit your application when you are ready to adopt.

UPDATE: ADOPTION EVENTS CANCELLED DUE TO PANDEMIC AND SOCIAL DISTANCING. If you are interested in meeting any Poochmatch dog at our weekly adoption event on Saturdays at the Petsmart in Yorba Linda, CA (5521 Mirage St.) between 1-5 PM, please fill out an application from our website, poochmatch.com, and submit it no later than 11 AM on Fridays. Upon receipt AND approval, the dog you are interested in meeting will be made available to meet on a Saturday. Due to the high volume of dogs and puppies in our foster homes, it is impossible to bring them all every Saturday. The only way to ensure that the dog that you are interested in will be at the adoption event is to FILL OUT AN APPLICATION AND BE APPROVED. Otherwise, we cannot guarantee that the dog you are interested in will be at our adoption event. If you cannot make the time frame of our events, appointments can be made at another time and location solely at the discretion of the foster parent. Please understand that private appointments will be coordinated to meet the convenience of the foster parent/transporter.

All adoption fees cover the mandatory and non-negotiable spay/neuter, rabies, microchip, microchip registration, full sets of core vaccinations (rabies and 1 set of distemper/parvo for adults, 4 for puppies) and deworming. Adoption fees vary based on age, breed, size and the costs incurred on the dog's behalf by us i.e. medical, behavioral training, etc. and they range from $225-$495.


COVID-19 PROCEDURE:
In an effort to create a safe environment for our potential adopters and our staff, we have changed our protocols and procedures during these difficult times. Starting immediately, our procedures will change from what’s written on our website and other social media platforms. Our weekly adoption event at the Petsmart in Yorba Linda is temporarily cancelled due to COVID-19 and social distancing. The only way to meet one of the dogs/puppies we have available for adoption is through completion of our adoption application through our website, poochmatch.com, before 11 AM on Fridays. On Fridays when we review the applications, we will pick the best fit for each dog or puppy applied for and coordinate mutually agreeable appointment times for the applicants who are approved that week. Private appointments are currently only scheduled on Wednesday, Thursday or Saturday of each week. Masks or bandanas are mandatory; faces must be properly covered.

With the overwhelming desire of the public to adopt at this time, we have received as many as 30 applications for one dog in just one week. Working with a staff of volunteers, we are only able to reach out on Fridays to the people we have approved to adopt. If you have not heard from us by Friday, we have selected a different applicant. If you have multiple dogs/puppies that you are interested in, please indicate each dog/puppy of interest on the application at that time so we don’t rule you out for another dog/puppy available for adoption.

Please understand, we have an influx of texts, phone calls and emails that makes it impossible to get to each and every one of you. Not just for adoption interest, but also from veterinarians, people who must relinquish dogs, people who have found a stray dog in need of pick up, etc. We are currently not in need of fosters. Due to the fact that there is such a high demand, we are sticking with strict protocol to not adopt out of Southern California. We apologize for this inconvenience and difficulty to be able to get in touch with us while there is an overwhelming desire and demand to adopt at this time. We appreciate your understanding and patience as we navigate through these difficult times with every intention to keep the public and our staff safe.

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Lottie Lee! I love to play and I'm a natural at chasing squirrels! Because of my instinct, my foster mom says cats are probably a no go, they're just so cute and fluffy...I can't resist chasing them! I would also benefit from having an amazing backyard to play in! 

My foster mom has been teaching me lots of tricks! I'm very treat motivated and easily trainable. So far I am great at sick, know stay, and I'm also crate trained! I'm still young (only two years old!) and have a very spunky and energetic personality! I love all people, especially those with treats! 

I'm "pittie" strong, which means muscular strong but also stubborn-headed, so will need a great handler to make sure I don't get away with things (such as pulling on a leash). 

I'm a very loving gal and I hope I'm the right fit for your family! If interested in meeting or adopting me, you can fill out an application at lpah.org/adoption.

Meet Bugaboo!

This handsome low rider is app. 3/4 years old, neutered, current on vaccines, heartworm negative and microchipped! He is a true bro dog, looking for a cool dude to spend his days with. He loves to run! Bugaboo has a lot of energy for one so small, and his zoomies we equate to a bull in a China shop lol so watch your knees lol! Bugaboo needs a home without other animals, as he can be a bit dominant. He also needs strong person/handler, to teach and continue to lead as he will follow. ? He has TONS of love to give and just wants to be right by your side at all times, so a home that can allow him to do his own thing is a must, and or a stay at home family would definitely be a plus!

Jaded Paws Rescue is a 501c3 foster run organization, and we do not have a kennel facility for the general public to come and visit. We do this because we find our animals will be much more accustomed to the home environment when the time comes that they get adopted! If you'd like to meet a Jaded Paws Pet, simply email us and we can schedule a meet and greet that is compatible with your schedule. Our adoption process includes an adoption application, a meet and greet and a 7-day adoption trial at the prospective family's home before the adoption is official. animal.description:
MEET DAVY and HAZEL

***POTENTIAL ADOPTER LOCATION REQUIREMENT- Our general adoption area is with a 50 mile radius of our Friendsville Home base - zip code  37737*** You can check to see if you fit within the radius at https://www.zipcodesoft.com/zip-codes-in-a-radius

Our adoption applications can be found online at www.tapsusa.org

Who are we?  We are Hazel (left) and Davy (right) and are a bonded duo who have been together for most of our lives and we want to keep it that way :).   
Where did you meet TAPS?  At a local Tennessee Shelter.
How old are you?  We are around 10ish years old.

Hazel is a lap puppy for sure!  Davy is a lap puppy fetch puppy - he's so silly!  Both dogs are super affectionate and loving.  Their owner died and they were taken to a shelter where no one reclaimed them.  Hazel and Davy need a fenced yard with access from the house.  They were never fully housetrained, but we have been working on that and with a schedule, good quality food and some vitamins, these seniors are getting an A+.  We feel they need to have quick access for potty breaks.  Hazel and Davy need a fenced yard with access from the house. This is a requirement for their next home.  

To adopt one of our animals, the first step is filling out an adoption application at www.tapsusa.org Please make sure you get a confirmation that your application has been submitted. 

BY APPOINTMENT ONLY

OPERATION ADOPT
706 Kiser Station Road
Friendsville, TN  37737

BY APPOINTMENT ONLY

All animals are spayed/neutered, current on age appropriate vaccinations and microchipped before they go to new homes because that's the responsible way to keep them all safe.

We only adopt to local homes  in the immediate vicinity because we utilize our volunteer force to process home visits.  Photos of your home, letters of reference are not acceptable which is why we only adopt locally. Only in very rare circumstances do we adopt out of area.  Examples of this would be finding the perfect home for a senior animal or one that has other special needs that we have not been able to place locally for an extended period of time.

animal.description: Hogan is a 4 year young American Staffordshire Terrier mix who came into our Rescue as a rescue from the Riverside shelter, 2 months ago. Hogan was adopted and 18 months later returned to the Riverside shelter as he did not get along with the other small dog in the family.  Hogan is a curious, playful boy who is so excited to play tug of war with you and his rope toy. He enjoys chasing balls, and playing with his toys are his favorite pastimes besides snuggling up to his humans.  Hogan does not do well with kids in the home! Hogan can get protective over his family when new people come around, so be sure to introduce him to new guests slowly and dont just have them barge in.  He is highly intelligent, loves the sun and the outdoors.  He takes treats very gently from your hand and loves bones. Although crate trained, Hogan is a big baby and hates to be confined in a kennel or a crate. He is however, highly trainable. Hogan loves his car rides, walking with his human and is great on a leash.  No small dogs and not sure about cats for Hogan!  Please consider this playful, outdoorsy boy to be your best friend.

Please do not ask us to reduce adoption fees since all fees help us to cover medical expenses for all of our animals, some of which can be very expensive.  Saving lives is not cheap so thank you for your understanding and helping us save as many as possible.

animal.description:
Meet Peanut. He’s a pup from back when Covid started and A rural county rescue in Alabama reached out for our help because transports up north had been cancelled.  So we partnered up to help find some pups homes. Peanut was adopted back in May but sadly it didn’t work out. He’s since been placed back in foster care where he truly has been thriving and doing well with socializing and training. He is now 6-7 months old. He is a  Terrier. He’s not very big at only like 20 lbs and we don’t see him growing a whole lot more. He has these long legs but skinny body. When he first came back into care he seemed to spook when people would open a door and come in. His foster family has worked on this and he is doing so much better. He adores his foster dad but he adores he’s 3 year old human foster sister even more. He’s happy and playful. Loves to run outside and play with other dogs. This boy is utd, neutered and ready for a forever home!

All dogs have a $175 adoption fee which includes vet check, age appropriate shots (atleast 2 sets for puppies), dewormer, heartworm test (if over 6 months), rabies (if atleast 16 weeks) and spay/neuter! Puppies will be altered before adoption. All rescues and shelters practice pediatric spay and neuter. This is essential in our rescue efforts and it is a policy that we will stick by. All dogs over 8 weeks and 2 pounds will be altered before adoption. There are no exceptions to this rule on all healthy and adoptable dogs. 

Puppies/Dogs that are not available for adoption due to vetting not being complete can be reserved with an approved application and a non refundable $50 deposit. This deposit is applied to your adoption fee and the remaining $125 is due at pick up.

Wags and Whiskers is an all-volunteer rescue. We also have full-time jobs and Families. We will try to answer all questions and applications in a timely manner. Please be patient and bear with us . Do not contact Parkway Animal Hospital as they are a vet clinic and can not answer questions on behalf of Wags and Whiskers. All questions and comments must go directly through the rescue. Thank you for your understanding.

ADOPTION APPLICATION

animal.description:
Rocky is such a sweet boy and is like a kid with his toys; he especially loves squeaky toys. This big-hearted guy is great with adults and older children (teenagers), soaking up attention and cuddles. He’s energetic, smart, and funny. He loves (and needs) lots of exercise, so would be a great companion for those who are up for exploring with Rocky on long walks, and who have the physical ability to control a larger pup.
 
Rocky is friendly with larger dogs like himself, and gets very excited when he sees dogs on his walks. He is not a fan of small dogs or cats, so should definitely not be in a home with small animals.

Rocky gets a little anxious when his family member leaves, but a long walk and a tv on for company helps him to settle in for a good nap.
The ideal candidate for Rocky is someone who works from home or works part time. His owner moved and couldn't take him along, so he was surrendered. Rocky deserves a loving, caring home where he can feel safe and welcomed as a member of the family.  He has been neutered, vaccinated, and chipped. Rocky is 5 yrs old.

animal.description:
Patton (also known as Petunia!) is one smarty pants! And boy, oh boy does he love his cookies! He was rescued by Dog Tales Rescue in Canada, and was later transferred to Dogs Playing for Life's Canine Center in Florida for further training. He's been waiting in Florida ever since. 

Patton is a purebred, papered American Bulldog. He is super smart and has nailed advanced obedience. He would love to continue to learn more as long as his person is packing treats! He is recommended as the only animal, in an adult home. Patton is a strong, big dog with goofy eyes, who loves to chase squirrels or raccoons, and play tug. 

He needs an experienced owner who wants to continue his training and perhaps even enter him into the world of competition (Senior edition). 

Here are a few more things to know about Patton:

*Patton is a staff-favorite at Dogs Playing For Life!

*He is not reactive in public on leash to other dogs, but he does often 'worry' a bit, so quieter more open spaces seem to be more enjoyable for him.

*He is a big, strong boy who initially struggled with resource guarding - he has come a long way and through his advanced training he has learned to "leave it" on command.

*Like a fine wine, he has greatly mellowed with age - he is trustworthy in the house during the day and housetrained. 

*He LOVES car rides and rides loose in the car.

*He likes training games, like catching treats, tug, etc. 

*He is muzzle trained, and does best muzzled for any vetting or more invasive handling, but once he has a relationship with someone he is very affectionate. 

*Patton has been with us for three years, far too long! He's more than ready for a chance, he's worked so hard and he'll be a good boy for someone.

*We are open to a foster home with another rescue group or an adopter, and we will support the new foster/adopter with training.

*Patton has a sponsor that will cover his veterinary care for life!

Interested in learning more about this big goober? Submit your adoption inquiry at https://www.shelterluv.com/matchme/adopt/DPFL/Dog or email melissa@dpfl.org

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Violet! I am a super loving girl who would love nothing more than a family to call my own! I am very affectionate and love to be petted. I also can get overly excited when seeing my person after a long day apart, so I might jump on accident just to give you a hug! I LOVE to swim!! It is so much fun! I do make a mess because my feet are so big which makes me clumsy! My foster mom says I resemble a hippo when I swim because I love to splash and make noise! I love making new dog and people friends! Dont be intimidated by my size though! I am a complete love bug and just want a nice head rub. I do have a funny bark though! I love a good treat and food! I could eat alllll day. My big appetite makes way for big muscles, so I am very strong! I need a family who understands I need someone to keep me and my big energy under control. I am very smart and a quick learner, so I wont have a problem picking up on manners! I already know how to sit! My energy does run out quick, so I am always ready to crash on the nearest couch after a good run. If you think I could be your girl, please come meet me!

All dogs adopted through Troy Animal Rescue Project are up to date on vaccinations, spayed/neutered (age appropriate), and heartworm negative. All dogs are given monthly flea/tick preventative, monthly heartworm preventative, and are dewormed regularly. Dogs adopted through Troy Animal Rescue Project are microchipped. Adoption fee is $50. Home visit and vet reference required. Applications can be put in online at http://www.troyanimalrescueproject.org/adopt.php or in person at our rescue center.

The address for our rescue center is 34 County Road 2266, Brundidge, AL 36010. We are one turn off Hwy 167. If you use Google maps, type in Troy Animal Rescue Project and it will take you right to us. Hours of operation are from 10-3 daily. We are open Saturdays and Sundays. No appointment necessary for pets that are located at the rescue center. Appointments must be made to visit pets in foster homes. Location information will be listed beside the pets name if they are at a location other than our rescue center.

Questions can be emailed to troyanimalrescueproject@gmail.com or call 334-508-2367.

animal.description:
Buzz (A37367835) is 3 years old, 54 pounds, neutered, and fully vaccinated. 


I am a great dog for that single guy or gal. I really do not do well around little kiddos as quick movements and loud noises make me nervous. I love to play fetch and I get along with all other dogs big and small. My foster mom has a boxer and an English Mastiff. A friend also comes to visit with a Chihuahua and I like to play with her too. Currently my foster mom has me have run of the house and I like to follow her around all day until we go outside where I like to play fetch, play water sports and rough house with my boxer foster sister. I love to cuddle and I love to sleep in the bed next to you. I can hear everything so I am also a great watch dog. If you are willing to take the time with me I can be a great dog and a great companion.


Buzz is currently in a foster home and available for adoption!  Please email FWACCcompliance@fortworthtexas.gov if you are interested in adopting.

We just had him vetted and poor guy had to have 18 teeth pulled.  He is on soft food for now.  Update he can eat dry food too.He is a happy dog but clings to people.  We know nothing of his past.  Only that he may have some separation anxiety.  We are hoping for a family that is home a lot or someone that works from home.  He was not skinny when found and definitely an indoor dog.  Loves beds and couches.  He needs to learn how to ride in a car and walk better on a leash.  He tries to jump out of car so he needs a seat belt harness or needs to be in a crate while in the car.  Sometimes he cries and sounds like a cow.  He is lonely and needs a family to love him. He does like other dogs and has tolerated 2 of our puppies pouncing on him to play?

animal.description:
Hi, I'm Darko! I was rescued as a newborn pup in Mexico after a home-check revealed that I was not in a safe living situation.  I didn't have my dog Mom at that time and sadly, I'm the only survivor of my brothers and sisters, but I'm safe and sound in Chicago now looking for a fur-ever home. I'm young, healthy, neutered, and up-to-date on my vaccinations! My current foster guardians would describe me as a very intelligent and high energy pup! I would LOVE a home where I can be a part of an active person's lifestyle :) I am however very fearful of strangers and I don't enjoy other dogs - I'd rather just hang with my person!  Due to my struggles in the past, I have some behavioral issues. I want to learn, I want to understand love but I need someone who will patiently show me the way, and how to be a companion. I hear that is the most beautiful thing and I want to try that out. If you live a calm, easy going lifestyle and have patience and dog handling experience, please consider me as your pal.  Serious inquiries only because though I am adorable, I need a bit of hands on work, time, patience and most of all ~ consistent love, around the clock.

Chicago, IL
FamousFidoChicago@gmail.com
SERIOUS INQUIRIES ONLY.

animal.description:
If you are interested in any of the dogs available at New Leash Rescue, you can reach out to the foster listed below for more information and then complete an adoption application which can be found at https://www.newleashrescue.org/adopt/policy.  Please email the completed application to newleashrescue2018@gmail.com

Brutus came to us from a local impound where he was an unclaimed stray.  Brutus weighs about 80 pounds and is estimated to be around 6 years old.  Brutus needs an experienced home where every person in the home will be his pack leader, or else he can be snappy with those that he thinks he can be the boss of.  

He is good with other dogs.  He is in a foster home with mostly medium to large sized dogs but he has been exposed to a small dog too and has done well.  He can be playful and like to run around in his fenced yard.  

Brutus is crated while his foster is gone and at night he sleeps on the floor beside the bed.  Brutus doesn't love the crate but he will go in willingly if a treat is thrown in.  He has a little bit of anxiety and will lick at the kennel door a bit.  He is crated in a heavier duty plastic crate currently.   He would prefer a home where he didn't have to be cratef, if you asked him.   He sleeps on the floor on a dog bed beside the bed at night.  

 Brutus does well with his house training after he has been able to acclimate to the house and learn the routine.  Brutus will be best in a home with Rottweiler experience.     He is also a big leaner and has a little weight behind him if he wants attention.   He has not been cat tested.   

He does have some resource protection around other dogs.  In his foster home he is fed in his crate and does well.  With people eating he will beg for a little bit and then will lay down under or beside the table.  He gets excited when seeing other dogs while out on a leash and will jump and pull.  We recommend any adopter attend training with Brutus.  He is extremely smart and feel he will excel at this.  He is a bit stubborn but is food motivated.  Aren't we all? ?

Brutus has a bite history so please consider before inquiring.   

Adoption fee is $350.00 + tax  (no checks) 

Foster to contact: Katie @ kit_n_caboodle22@hotmail.com 

Please inquire whether Brutus will be attending an upcoming event. 

 Our fosters do the best they can to provide all information about the animal's background and temperament while in foster care in their home. An adopters routine and home environment is likely going to be different than that in their foster home. 

Sometimes there is more that comes out about a dog's personality once they have been able to settle in a home and truly become comfortable. There are great articles out there written about the different stages a pet goes through after adoption, discussing transitions that happen at 3 days, 3 weeks, and 3 months. We highly recommend reading about this - it will help you understand the transition your new pet goes through.

Zoey is around 2 years old and a Jagd Terrier.  She has a wire coat and does shed.   Zoey is visually impaired and is almost blind, she can possibly see some shadows, but is special needs and is looking for the right fit home.   

Zoey will do best in a quieter home, with children age 10 and up.  She is good with other dogs and likes to play some, but she needs a family that understands her special needs.  Zoey will have accidents at first and will take time to acclimate to any new place because she can't see.  She will be shy and take some time to feel comfortable to venture out.   She should not be off leash, and would do best in a fenced in yard where she can move around safely. 

A Jagd terrier requires a terrier savvy owner.  These are not a good first time dog and need someone experience to be able to understand and appreciate their antics. 

Zoey had a dental to remove a few retained baby teeth when she came into rescue.  

Please contact Zoey's foster to learn more.  

Adoption fee is $350.00 + tax (no checks)

Foster to contact:  Sara - 651-260-3774 or sara.fostermom@gmail.com

animal.description:
Ava is a sweet, happy and loving girl who can be a little shy with new people. she loves to go for walks and play in the yard with people. Ave has EPI and needs special enzymes power so she can eat.

Dogs with Exocrine Pancreatic Insufficiency (EPI) have a malabsorption and maldigestion condition where the pancreas is no longer producing enough pancreatic enzymes to digest fats, carbohydrates, and proteins. Because of this, dogs (and also cats) will often present with unexplained weight loss, diarrhea/cow-patty like yellow/pale stools. Although EPI was once thought to be just a German Shepherd condition, it is now found in all breeds.

Without a special enzyme powder on her food she is not able to put on or maintain weight. She can't be without it. it runs about $50 to $60 a month.

animal.description: Ava came to us a 9 week old puppy suffering from Megaesophagus secondary to PRAA. This is a condition in which the esophagus will not move the food down her throat as it should. Ava has surgery to correct her PRAA and it did lessen the severity of her Mega Esophagus but didnt totally correct it. Ava must eat her food after its been soaked and blended in a blender and she needs to eat out of an elevated feeder. She drinks water normally and is no longer on daily meds. Ava loves other dogs and cats and children. She is almost potty trained but still has occasional accidents. She needs a family that will be diligent on ensuring that no small objects are left where she can get them because they can pose choking hazards for her with her mega E. Please take a few minutes to read up on Megaesophagus to see what it is and what care is required for a dog with the condiotion if you feel you are interested in Ava.

animal.description:
Max is a 6 year old German Shepherd looking for his forever home. Max is a laid back, chill boy who just wants to hang with his person. This boy is so easy to have around, and loves a lazy walk and just to relax and watch a good movie. Max does fine with the two female dogs in the house, but does not like to share attention with his foster mom, therefore, Max should be the only dog in the house. Although Max is easy to have around, he still requires an experienced dog owner. As with most German Shepherds, they are intelligent, obedient, and very protective of their home, environment, and people. The new owner must continue to provide obedience and structure to ensure a happy dog. Max loves belly rubs, and is a very affectionate sweet dog. Max does not like cats. If you are looking for a laid back, loving affectionate dog, this is your boy. Max said he would prefer an adult home with one or two people to adore.

Come see this pup on Saturdays during adoption event hours. Please email Linda at lbredfire@sbcglobal.net or call WT&F's Dog Team voicemail 707-812-9030 to get a jump on the process, ask questions, and/or to confirm they will be there. Dog adoptions are held outside Napa Petco every Saturday - 12:30pm to 4:00pm.
This dog comes spayed/neutered, microchipped, vaccinated, dewormed, heartworm tested negative, and more with an adoption fee/donation to Whiskers, Tails and Ferals in Napa, CA. See more information at http://whiskerstailsandferals.org/.
Visit our Facebook page: https://www.facebook.com/whiskerstailsandferals/

animal.description: Mack is a handsome senior Puggle (a Pug /Beagle cross). This sweet gentleman has gone through some tough times losing his owner and ending up in a humane society and then being adopted by a family who could not keep him. He is now in our care and receiving lots of TLC in his awesome foster home. He is lovely in the house and has lots of charm, however he can be vocal and is not suitable for living in a condo/apartment. Currently he is in good health and this former chunky monkey has lost weight. Mack is now an active fella who loves long walks and to swim laps in the pool. He loves a good game of fetch. He is the size of a small Beagle with a big personality and an even bigger heart! We will not accept applications with children under 14 as to the best of our knowledge he has not lived with children under 14. Mack needs to be the only pet in the home as he much prefers the company of being with his people. Mack will make a lovely companion but he is not suitable for a first time dog owner.

animal.description:
Please contact Susan (ozarksummer@yahoo.com) for more information about this pet.DC is a wonderful, loving, fun kid who wants nothing more from life but a friend to hang with, go on a few walks a week and just live a life of love and care in an adult setting. He MUST have a fenced attached yard or he will roam off in search of an adventure that will end badly!

*************
DC is thriving in foster care! He has taught his foster parents that he LOVES to chase a ball! Might bring it back, might prefer to play keep away but either way BALL IS A MUST! He is very passionate about playing ball and will need a new guardian that would love to play ball too!!
*****************************
DC is a beautiful young adult bull who came from circumstances that define his emotional needs. He is a smart, sensitive and affectionate boy who is a people pleaser but due to his past life he is very unsure and will quickly be submissive. He needs a guardian that is firm, gentle and will lend him some confidence and assurance that he IS a good boy and its ok, he does not need to worry about doing wrong and facing horrible punishment and pain. He just wants to make his human happy! This dog has illustrated that he is not clear on what is his bad and what is not his bad and at some point was punished harshly for things that he did not have a hand in, maybe an angry human or just drunks or who knows what. Many times the ego plays a role in some human types to select this breed and they imprint their lack of self confidence in domination over the powerful beast, some how that makes certain humans feel better about themselves. We don't play into that mentality and will be watching for signs as to avoid placing him where he will face it again.
DC will sit and speak on request, which is fun! He is good on a leash and will spend all afternoon just playing, romping and snorting around the yard. He enjoys toys and will chase squirrels and birds, which usually qualifies him as not a cat person! He loves to throw and chase so might be a good ball chaser with the right human!
He very much likes other dogs but needs possible housemates (if any) that would hold up to some seriously not gentle but fast play. He would not be a good housemate to small, fragile or easily annoyed furkids. He does well with the furkids in his foster home but they are all big and busy kids like himself. We are so heart warmed to see him engage is care free play and running around just to run and feel the freedom it offers.
DC will need a fenced yard because he will suffer discrimination from neighbors and local governments wherever he lands. He will so need the freedom of going into his yard where he knows its safe and he can enjoy the carefree time that has been so instrumental in his progress this far.
DC has an adoption donation of $175 of which $150 + any addition donation amount will be tax deductible for you
Poor guy does have a sensitivity to topical flea treatments so his new family would have to be committed to Nexguard Chewables as part of his regimen. DC is 22 inches at the shoulder, broad and strong weighing in at 70 lbs of solid muscle! He will need a gentle, firm pack leader with a super tight fence. Since he got in trouble over a domestic disturbance and quiet no kids home would be ideal. He loves Leash Walks!!! Please submit your interst at this linik
https://ozarkhavenrescue.weebly.com

Glad to answer any questions at all! 4/27/20 11:31 AM

animal.description:
Duster is a very sweet, playful and incredibly good-natured Black Lab/Terrier mix.  He is approximately 10 years old and weighs 65 pounds.  He is such an affectionate boy with a very happy and fun personality! Delightful Duster loves people of all ages including small children.  He gives kisses and is fantastic with all other dogs. He is okay in a household with dog-friendly cats that enjoy his enthusiasm. Some less dog-experienced cats may consider him a pest. He rides well in the car, walks well on leash, knows the commands sit and down, and takes treats very gently from your fingers. He is a smart boy and a quick learner who will do anything for a treat. Duster is perfectly housebroken and crate-trained. His tail is always happily wagging, and he is full of loving kisses. He enjoys leaning against you, looking adoringly into your eyes and rolling over for belly rubs.
Duster is extremely healthy, neutered, heartworm-tested, micro-chipped, and up-to-date on rabies and distemper vaccines. Duster is in a foster home in Chicagoland and would love to have a loving forever home to call his own.  To meet and possibly adopt him, please contact Melia at melia88@comcast.net to get an adoption application emailed to you. His adoption donation of $200 benefits the rescued dogs of Lucky Dog Rescue.

Porter has been consistently one of our most human-fearful dog, is protective of his space and becomes defensive when he feels threatened. He takes time to form a bond with someone and trust them enough to feel comfortable. He walks very well on a leash and is very treat motivated with the right person he could be trained easily. Porter will do best as the only pet in a home so that his adopter can give him all the time and attention he needs to adjust. He will not be a dog that can be taken out in public with large crowds. Introducing him to new people will have to be taken very slowly. With the right person he has the potential to be wonderful and loving dog. Overall Porter needs an experienced dog handler who is willing to meet with him multiple times and work with him through his fearful behaviors.

animal.description:
Skippy is a sweet, all-around good dog.  He came to us after being found by a good samaritan, having a  bad wound that turned out to have been caused by a gunshot from a black powder gun.  He came to us in mid-January of this year.

He narrowly escaped serious injury or death. We were amazed at the trajectory of the bullet and that it didn't cause more damage than it did.  The bullet was the size of a marble and penetrated the left side of his neck, glanced off his shoulder blade, went through one lung lobe, broke a rib and lodged under the skin on the right side of his ribcage.  

Skippy is a trouper and a survivor!  We're grateful and amazed that he has quickly and completely healed from his trauma.  He is very energetic and happy.  He will need lots of exercise and would appreciate a family that is really active and includes him.  He loves people and is good with other dogs.  We don’t know if he’s good with children.  Judging by his personality I bet he would be, but he’s so energetic that they should probably be older children.  Skippy is a charmer!  We think he will make a good family dog...maybe best with older children because he is energetic and enthusiastic about life!

He's a great size...about 50 pounds...and, he's just about 2 years old.

animal.description:
Please note that while we are closed to the public we will not be responding to pet inquiries. Once animals are posted, we immediately begin receiving adoption applications. With one volunteer available to review all applications, we appreciate your patience as you wait for an email response. Adoption appointments are scheduled first come with an approved application, first served. (See our adoption procedures below.)

Eddie came to us from an owner who felt he needed a fenced yard for exercise. And he does, because he's an active boy who loves to play fetch. Eddie is a lot of fun and would do best with an active family or owner that is a bit rough 'n tumble like him. Eddie is guaranteed to provide many laughs with his goofy personality. He lived indoors with his family, was house trained, and knows several commands. Eddie's been at the shelter WAY too long, and we cannot believe this ham keeps getting overlooked. Eddie's estimated DOB is 8/1/2018; he weighs about 56 lbs.

Eddie was generously sponsored by Peter Farrell during our virtual Reigning Cats and Dogs event. Thank you Peter for sponsoring Eddie!

HSPC's adoption fee is seventy-five-dollars through December 31, 2020, unless stated otherwise within the pet's description. At times, our adoption fees are lowered during special events that are posted to our website or Facebook page. Every pet that is available for adoption has been spayed/neutered, microchipped, and is up-to-date on vaccinations including heartworm preventative (canines). Adopters are required to schedule a wellness exam with their veterinarian at their cost within 7 days of adoption.

Please only submit one application. Once you are contacted by email, you will have an opportunity to provide us with any additional animal(s) under consideration.

Online Adoption Application 
Hi I'm Roseland! or Rosie, as my foster family calls me! I can't wait to meet you! I am a sweet girl - I will stare at you with my gorgeous, amber eyes & you'll do anything I want...oh, wait...foster says that is probably not best...I should have some rules so I can be my best self. I am an energetic young adult who enjoys playing as much as I do snuggles with my humans - I am a bit of a bed hog. I love treats & food too and definitely need some appropriate things to chew on. I was born in the rescue & adopted as a young puppy but didn't get the care I needed and was returned. I am a bit of a wild child at the moment on a leash - I'm just so excited! I will need training to reign that in but I am so smart and have so much potential - I am essentially a puppy brain in an adult dog body! Did I mention snuggles - they are oh so important - couch or bed, doesn't matter to me! I am also house-trained - of course any transition could lead to a slip-up - you'd have to understand that in getting any dog. I like other dogs and want to play but I play hard so a friend would have to be a tolerant one. I also don't want to share bones, thank you very much! My foster mom says I'm gorgeous - I have a chocolatey coat with white features, including a white "knee sock" on one of my front legs! And my fur is SO soft - velvety! My adopter must have the time and patience to help me be my best self. Could you be my pawfect match?

Roseland needs to be in a home as an only-dog-- she doesn't want to share the love!

animal.description:
Have you met volunteer favorite Janie?

One day, early in 2020, Janie's owners called LA County Animal Control and asked them to pick up their dog because they were done with her. And that's how Janie came to be in Baldwin Shelter. Only thing is, Janie's not really a senior... she'es only 6 years old! She's still not sure how she ended up at this old folks home! The reality is, Janie REALLY needed us so, we Frosted her on March 24, 2020. Janie had severe dry eye that was untreated for so long she was creating no tears on her own causing a lot of discomfort. We got Miss Janie in to an ophthalmologist who did a parotid duct transposition to lubricate her eyes with saliva. It's a fancy procedure, but if it gives her eyes a chance to heal and be comfortable? Well, only the best for our girl!

Janie has been on a couple Flings. She's the best girl in a home! She's fun, active, and loves to play. One of her Fling Moms shared, "If you ever lack motivation to get out and exercise, Janie will help! Walking, running, hiking... Janie's your girl! Not confident with your cooking skills? Janie will always be there to taste test, and it's all five stars to her! Live alone? Janie's deep bark warns off would-be intruders, and her snores will relax you to sleep."

Another volunteer who always makes sure to spend a little extra time with Janie told us, "Janie has SO much love to give! After she's been on a walk to get her wiggles out, the only thing missing for her to have the perfect day is to be in someone's company. She's learned how to dribble her ball back and forth by herself, but I swear it's like she's saying "I won't make you do much work, just please sit here with me." I love how she makes me feel like I'm the best thing on the planet when I spend time with her. This girl would be so happy to finally get a home of her own."

Janie lives onsite at Frosted Faces Foundation. Stop by to meet this special girl during our next Open House!

Visit us at Open House: Saturdays & Sundays, 10 am - 1 pm

Learn more about our programs at www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/family. No adoption fees and we help with medical costs!

Apply to become a family: www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/apply

Questions: adopt@frostedfacesfoundation.org

Updated: 1/31/21 KG
