Unless otherwise stated, the adoption fees for dogs over 5 months range from $50-$175. Puppies under 5 months are $175.00. Cats over 1 year are $35.00, kittens under 1 year old are $60.00. Dog adoption fees include a microchip. Cats can be microchipped by request for an additional $5.00.
The adoption fee includes the animal's surgery, vaccinations, flea preventative, deworming medication, sample bag of food/treat samples and a free first exam with participating veterinarians. Shelter policy and 2018 Indiana state law decrees all animals must be spayed or neutered prior to leaving the shelter.
WE ARE CURRENTLY OPERATING BY APPOINTMENT ONLY DUE TO COVID-19
Our shelter is open to the public on Monday- Saturday from 8:00 am -5:00 pm EST with the exception of Wednesdays on which we typically open by 1:00 pm. If you would like to make an appointment to meet one of our many adoptable animals, please send an email to us at pvchs@joink.com. To apply to adopt, you may download an adoption application from the Applications and Fees tab on our website. The web address is www.pvchs.cfsites.org. Please email the completed application to pvchs@joink.com.

animal.description:
Rocco desperately needs a calm foster so he can start heartworm treatment. He must be calm for two months. The vet is located in New Orleans LA. Email animalhelperneworleans@gmail.com for an application to foster or adopt. 

Rocco was an owner surrender. They said he was hostile, barked nonstop and wouldn't eat. I'd bet money that dog was never hostile a day in his life. He barked and didn't eat due to his bad case of heartworms. That wasn't his fault but his owners. We treated him for a urinary infection. He completed a month of doxycycline. He got a proheart injection which is 6 months of heartworm prevention. He was treated for intestinal parasites. He's had several great exams. After heartworm treatment he will get a dental with a dental xray. He had an echo by the cardiologist. He coughs randomly. The cardiologist found nothing wrong with his heart. The guess is his trachea. He is not the best with house training. I've had this issue with other dogs that ate heavy heartworm positive. They improve after treatment. He will be on prednisone during treatment so hell have to potty lots. He'd be perfect with a doggy door.  
 I think he looks like a hyena. He likes to climb things also. He just wants to snuggle. He loves car rides. He does know his name. He's great on the leash. He loves to play with dogs. He's always happy. Has a smile and a wagging tail. Our vet guesses he's 12. He's around 16 lbs but has super long legs. We have no idea on a breed guess. He's just adorable.
Hes located in New Orleans LA. Email animalhelperneworleans@gmail.com for an application.

Urgent Tosha's foster is selling the house. She needs a forever home asap. She's been patiently waiting for her forever home for 16 months.  

Tosha was pulled from Animals of IPAC  (Iberia Parish Animal Control) on November 22, 2019. She had been picked up on July 16, 2019. She was seized for a cruelty case. She had been tied to a tree. 

Tosha is approximately 4 years old and 40lbs. She’s a very loving dog. She loves kids. She is house and crate trained. She gets along well with other dogs. She is not good with cats or pigs. She is active. She would do best with daily exercise. 

Tosha was treated for heart worms. She’s spayed and microchipped. She had a 6 month proheart injection for heartworm prevention. She is up to date on shots. She’s had a great exam and negative fecal. She does have some slight trachea damage from being tied to a tree. She should wear a harness always instead of a collar. 

Tosha can be adopted anywhere and is currently located in New Orleans. If she is adopted locally the adoption will include 3 hour training sessions with Canis Integrated Behavior Solutions LLC. They are completely positive.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website. All of our dogs and cats are in foster homes and we have no paid staff. If you have questions concerning a specific animal, PLEASE fill out an application and the foster parent will be in touch. We will not arrange any home visits with any of our dogs and cats until your application is processed. Please understand our foster parents are precious to our 2nd Chance family; without them we cannot function, so we do our best to not burden them with multiple appointments. Our foster parents will choose their top 3 applications and arrange home visits with these applicants. The adopter will be chosen at that time. The process can take anywhere from a week to a month. We want to make sure our little furry ones are placed in their 'forever home' and never have to go through a rehoming again!Hello my name is Yoda or that is what the shelter named me. I don't really know my name :) I just sort of do whatever I want to do. I like to be with my person at all times and I absolutely HATE a crate. I would love a home where they would cuddle with me 24/7. I was wayyyyy overweight so my foster mommy is working with my diet and I feel better already. Yes I am a dog so I will eat anything offered to me but it doesn't mean it is good for me. I couldn't even walk I waddled so I don't want an owner that is going to think that to love me is to feed me!!!Please fill out an adoption application:
Adoption application (Dog)
Adoption Application (Cat)

Please understand we do not adopt out dogs to
families with children under the age of 5. We do not adopt dogs to renters. Some dogs will have fence requirements while others may not.

A pet is a lifetime commitment. The dogs and cats in our system find themselves there, for the most part, because their humans did not have the same loyalty to them as they did to their owners. We do not take the adoption process lightly, and will do everything in our power to make sure the animal is placed correctly the first time around for your sake and theirs. Thank you for choosing to adopt not shop!

animal.description:
To first see Eden, you might think, she is bold, confident, and very sure of herself. With Eden, looks can be deceiving. She is a beautiful boxer/pittie mix that is approximately 4 yrs. old, and solid 70 or so lbs. Eden is a very special girl, who we want to go to a home, where she will be happy, feel safe, relaxed and most of all, a home that she will succeed and thrive in. She was an owner surrender almost a year ago now, (in February 2020) with some information given but not much detail to go on or work with. Sweet Eden is 100% crate-trained and house-trained. In fact, she loves her crate and finds it to be her safe place when a new person comes to the home (or if she just wants a long nap) We do not recommend cats or dogs for this girl, or anything furry that she can chase. She is very interested in squirrels, or anything that gets in her way on her walks that she loves but does well with treats to distract her attention from them. We did test her with some other shelter dogs through a fence barrier, but although she did okay, we do feel it is best she is the only pet in the home.

With Eden, it has taken her some time to just simply learn how to be in our home and relax. At first, she was terrified of the stairs, the kitchen, the ceiling fan, the garage, to name a few, but now, (she has been with us now a lil over 2 mos.) She now knows that all these things are not going to hurt her, and she happily runs up and down stairs and in the kitchen for treats and is slowly getting better at the garage. The "getting in a car is still a no-go for her lol (unless you put her in a crate, or in a gated back part of an SUV) She is not a fan, but with practice, she will feel better with this too! The only thing she is not quite comfortable yet is the young man in the home, who is not scary at all, but she just has not had much interaction with him, so it causes her to be "stressed" if he is around. We have seen improvement already, by just having him treat her when he passes by, letting her sit in crate in living room with him, or having her leashed when he is in the same room.

Eden is the type of dog, that is just honestly going to be worth every bit of the wait and patience you give her. She is quite low maintenance, and the MOST loveable, sweet Velcro dog you could ever meet! The key with her, is patience, and not rushing her to get comfortable with things, but giving her the time, she needs, and lots of positive reinforcement. She is very SMART!! She knows several commands and has already learned "twirl!" and is working on "drop it" (trading toy for a treat) and almost knows "sit pretty"!

Once outside, in the back yard, she seems more comfortable and will even do some major zoomies over and over, do a lil digging if she is in the mood, and come to you with her toys for some fetch time or tug of war! As far as children, we strongly recommend based on her timid personality, that older kids will be best. She does wonderfully with the dog savvy young teen in our home right now and often cuddles with her while she does her virtual school classes.

Lastly, we will add; Some of Eden's favorite things are: Food, treats, belly rubs (rolls over for them) stuffed animals and toys (she will keep herself entertained most the time) and even paws you for attention! If she is sleeping in a bedroom, she prefers her own personal space in the room, over a spot on the bed. Eden is such a wonderful girl that no doubt, will be a heart-dog to someone lucky enough to adopt her.

animal.description: If you are applying for McKynlee, please indicate on your application that you have read and understand her specific needs. Born on 01/06/20 and raised in foster care, McKynlee is a deliciously loving, 36 lb. Lab mix. With her gorgeous big eyes, this girl looks at you and melts your heart instantly. McKynlee, affectionately called "Kyn Kyn" by her foster family, is so full of love for her people and never fails to let them know. Her snuggles are just the sweetest, and she will mold herself into her people to cuddle or lay against a leg or on a foot. This girl's love for her new family will be very, very special and her connection to others will develop more gradually. Funny and feisty, McKynlee loves her toys and enjoys, not just her siblings, but the other dogs in her foster home as well. She can often be found romping with them in the yard and would enjoy a home with another playful canine buddy. Full of joy in the morning, she makes the cutest happy noises - her foster mom calls it her "warble". McKynlee has also been learning to swim in her foster family's pool, which she usually follows with a sun session in her chaise! McKynlee is very connected to her people and her canine friends, but since she is hesitant with new people and new things, she would probably prefer to be more of a homebody than to be the dog going on lots of outings. As a result of this, she would do better in a home with children over age 12. This angel is crate trained, housetrained, knows basic commands, and is working on her leash training. McKynlee has Megaesophogus, (where her esophagus does not properly carry food to the stomach) that has been well managed since she was about 8 weeks old on daily medication; she will likely need this for life and with it does eat and drink normally. Likewise, this does not slow her down one bit, and she is plenty rambunctious and happy. Goofy and playful, McKella has a blast playing with her toys, her siblings, and with the other dogs in her foster home. She would love to find a home with a canine buddy to play with. animal.description:
This is ‘Girl Friday’. We really have no idea what Friday's mix is. Most times it's fairly easy, but this one's a real stumper, and Friday's not talking. 

In early March 2020 Friday was found as a stray right here in West Orange. We posted her on Facebook looking for her family, but haven’t had any luck finding them. So, after the state’s required 7-day hold, off to the vet she went. We thought she was under a year, but the vet thinks she might be as old as 2.  (We're guessing now she's about 3.)  She weighed in at 60 lbs. She was brought up to date on her shots (rabies and distemper vaccinations), was checked for parasites and tested for heartworm and lyme disease (all negative), and was spayed. This was all part of getting her ready for adoption. Unfortunately, this was exactly when the Corona shut down started and we had to temporarily suspend the WOAWL’s shelter adoption program while we, as a community, dealt with the crisis. 
 
Since Friday is at the shelter and not in a home situation we can't tell if she is housebroken, but the ACO's tell us she tries to keep her run clean; and since the shutdown happened on the day she was returned to the shelter, she hasn't been around children. The only other dog at the shelter available for adoption was not good with other dogs, so we don't know how Friday would be in a home with another dog.   

When West Orange municipal buildings closed due to the Corona virus restrictions, it included the township's animal shelter. The animals weren't ignored, however, and the Animal Control Officers were in the shelter every day feeding and cleaning and socializing.  Now they are doing adoptions by appointment.  

If you are interested in seeing Friday please give us a call at 973-736-8689.  It’s voice mail 24/7, but we try to return calls the same day.   

The shelter is located at 311 Watchung Avenue, West Orange.  Once the Corona crisis is over and "things are back to normal" we should be back to the regular adoption hours,  Monday through Friday 4:30 – 5:30 (except holidays) and the 1st & 3rd Saturday’s 11AM – 3PM.   Hopefully it won't be too long before the shelter is once again open, and appointments won’t be necessary.

animal.description:
Sophie is a very sweet, friendly, affectionate girl who we rescued in February, 2019 from a house where she was left behind when her owners moved after being evicted. One of her rescuers, Kara, is also fostering her, along with her other dogs, including some other fosters and three large horses. Understandably and to be expected after what she's been through, Sophie has anxiety issues and is currently on prescribed Prozac from a veterinarian, which has really helped her calm down and helped her to become less reactive. She's playful, and loves attention and to be loved on, but has some trust issues that need to be worked through. She has come a long way and although she tends to be dog selective, she is friendly with some dogs. Her playmate is Harley, rescued on the same day and also being fostered at Kara's, and they play together in the large, fenced in area outside all day and then stay inside at night.

I'm Michelle and one of her rescuers, and she's really found her way into my heart. I take her on outings to a local park where we take walks together and she loves it. She doe have a tendency to pull on the leash.

From what we gather from the neighbors where she was abandoned, Sophie had at least one litter of puppies that died and her owners neglected her before abandoning her, so this sweet soul has been through so much and has come a long way in a short time. She needs structure and stability and the ideal home would be a place with no other pets and no small children. She is very reactive and fearful of Kara's three large horses and her cats that stay upstairs. She can be triggered by new things so that's why it's important for her to have a daily routine with no chaos. She needs someone with a lot of patience, understanding, and experience with dogs that have behavior issues stemming from being abandoned. She does well in a very structured, routine environment, doesn't do well with a lot of changes.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Name:

Punkin

Breed:

American Staffordshire Terrier Mix

Adoption Fee:

$150

Date of Birth (estimated):

9/17/2015

Weight:

50 lbs

Good with Dogs:

no

Good with Cats:

no

Good with Children:

yes-respectful

Other Needs:

fenced in yard (6 foot) // supervision with toys (high obstruction risk) // to be muzzled in the community // kept away from other animals

Punkin is a super sweet gal who is searching for a mellow home where she can work on overcoming her fears and learn what its like to be a normal dog. She is quite fearful in new situations and gets startled easily. She will pancake to the floor when nervous and will need someone who is patient and understanding to help her feel more comfortable and confident. Despite that she is incredibly happy and sweet! Especially with the people she lives.
Because of her general fearfulness, we are looking for a home without small children. Punkin LOVES running around outside in the yard and is always so happy to strut around. Punkin has a history of ingesting toys and had an obstruction surgery when she came to rescue. Because of this, potential fosters/adopters will need to be very careful with the kinds of toys she gets and she cannot be unsupervised with toys that she may be able to rip apart. Punkin does not get along with other animals and she will need to be the only pet in the home. She will also need a home with a 6ft fence. Punk is a special girl who needs a very special home who understands her needs and can make sure she is always being set up for success. She really is a loving girl who likes to snuggle and watch tv and give kisses she just didn't have the best start in life. She was mistreated and never learned love. We just know there is someone out there that can understand her and give her the life she deserves.

Her needs can be discussed in further detail upon request.

If you are interested in meeting or adopting this animal, please read the following before submitting an adoption application on our website - fureverhomerescue.com.

Adoption fee includes spay/neuter, microchip, age appropriate vaccinations, 4Dx test (covers tick-borne diseases (
A

naplasmosis

,
Lymes, E

hrlichiosis) as well as heart worm)

& de-worming. We ask that our dogs live indoors unless otherwise stated & agreed upon. We ask that applicants live in our area.

animal.description:
Wiley is a handsome adult male Pit Bull Terrier mix who was brought to the HSOV on March 6, 2020 by Good Samaritans who found him on Briggs Hill Road in the Belpre Ohio area.

Wiley has a brown/brindle-and-white short smooth coat, a long tail, and a beautiful white face with a small patch of brindle around his right eye and a large patch of brindle at the base of his right ear. He has a rather slender muzzle, a black button nose, and short semi-erect ears.

Wiley was a very frightened boy being confined in a kennel when he first entered our shelter and was not a happy camper for the first few weeks with us :(  We had hoped that his owner would see the preliminary photos we took on March 8th or that someone will recognize him but, sadly, that did not happen. Wiley was most likely a very different dog in his home with a family who loved him.

Wiley weighs approximately 55-60 lbs and has already been neutered.

In compliance with the Ohio Revised Code, Wiley was held for three days so that his owner would have an opportunity to come and reclaim him with proof of ownership but that happy reunion did not take place.

Wiley is beginning to warm up to our kennel techs and, though he is still nervous in our shelter, Wiley is showing us more of his personality.  He will obey the 'sit' command, so someone in his past has spent time training him to recognize that word.  Wiley also loves treats and appears to be an intelligent boy.

These updated photos were taken on March 22, 2020 when Wiley accompanied two of our core volunteers whom he has learned to trust.  He was still a bit cautious of the 'paparazzi' following him and snapping photos but nice to that lady just the same.  Wiley loved the 'good boy' treats which were offered to him in reward for good behavior.

Wiley will require an experienced handler and an 'alpha' leader to give him guidance/training.  Our kennel techs would be happy to introduce you to Wiley and to share their experiences/knowledge about him.
animal.name: Wiley (Neutered) - Photos 3/22/2020

animal.description: Paisley is a distinguished lady that is approximately 8-9 years old, but do not let her age fool you. She is in great health, weighs approximately 45.8 lbs and can run like a dog half her age. Paisley is an extremely smart, quiet and sweet dog that would make a wonderful companion for an older or retired person. She loves to be outside, go on walks, but is also content lying on the couch having cuddle time. Paisley shows no hesitation when you open a car door and always seems up for a ride- she just lies down and relaxes or looks out the window. Paisley shows some interest in other dogs and will try to mingle; she has not shown any aggression, but seems better with male dogs vice female dogs. Paisley has done really well when meeting new people and is good with older children. Her foster says Paisley is always looking for food, treats or toys. When vetted, Paisley was found to be heartworm positive, but has already started treatment. Whoever adopts this wonderful gal will receive everything Paisley needs to complete her treatment. She comes fully vetted, spayed, and microchipped. If you would like to meet Paisley, please call Hands to Paws Rescue or her foster at (706) 664-8305. Adoption fee is $125.00.

animal.description: Soulful eyes......meet Mardi!  She’s a 14 mos. old potty mix. Someone left her and 4 others crammed in a crate in the freezing rain outside of a business. Just when they were about to give up hope of ever being warm again, the employees found them the next morning and brought them in and warmed them up. They were suffering from malnourishment and intestinal worms. As you can see today she’s a happy, healthy girl. She’s passed up over and over again because of her breed and her color, and people don’t know what they’re missing out on. If you would like to meet this sweet girl and give her the love and family she so deserves, let us know.

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.This is Tilly! Tilly is a female American Bulldog mix rescued in New York. Our veterinary partners estimate that Tilly is 8 years old at the time of intake in March 2020. Poor Tilly was stabbed in the face several times and left to die. Fortunately, she was picked up and brought to a shelter, and as soon as Rescue Dogs Rock NYC became aware of her, we immediately brought her to our veterinary partner for the medical care she required to recover from her injuries. Unfortunately, Tilly lost an eye to this cruelty, but it doesn't stop her from enjoying her new life. Tilly is super sweet with people. We haven't yet tested her with dogs, so stay tuned. Tilly is understandably fearful of men, and she is not a city dog. She requires a home in the suburbs where she will be loved, cherished and kept safe and she will lead a life that is far happier than the life being led by the individual who did this to her. If you can give Tilly that life, please apply online to adopt Tilly at www.rescuedogsrocknyc.org.

animal.description: Hi! My name's Lilly and I'm a 3-year-old spayed PitBull Mix.  I've had a couple of homes in my short life, and I'm thinking it's time that I finally settled dow! As a matter of fact, I was recently adopted and returned. I can't wait until I have a family of my very own, because I really like people! My human friends here at Lucy Mackenzie know how much I like cuddling and going for walks. I particularly enjoy the more leisurely-style of walk, one where I can stop and smell the roses, and everything else in between! I'm proud to say that I'm a pretty smart girl, and am well-behaved, too. I'm open to meeting other dogs, and could maybe even live with one, if we got along. I can't live with cats, though - sorry. If you've been thinking it's time you adopted an adorable and adoring dog, stop in and meet me today!

All dogs adopted through Troy Animal Rescue Project are up to date on vaccinations, spayed/neutered (age appropriate), and heartworm negative. All dogs are given monthly flea/tick preventative, monthly heartworm preventative, and are dewormed regularly. Dogs adopted through Troy Animal Rescue Project are microchipped. Adoption fee is $50. Home visit and vet reference required. Applications can be put in online at http://www.troyanimalrescueproject.org/adopt.php or in person at our rescue center.

The address for our rescue center is 34 County Road 2266, Brundidge, AL 36010. We are one turn off Hwy 167. If you use Google maps, type in Troy Animal Rescue Project and it will take you right to us. Hours of operation are from 10-3 daily. We are open Saturdays and Sundays. No appointment necessary for pets that are located at the rescue center. Appointments must be made to visit pets in foster homes. Location information will be listed beside the pets name if they are at a location other than our rescue center.

Questions can be emailed to troyanimalrescueproject@gmail.com or call 334-508-2367.

animal.description:
WILLY!!!
*GOOD with LARGE FEMALE dogs only, GOOD with kids 5+, NO cats

* ADOPTION FEE $400   www.unbreakabull.com/adopt

There was a movie years ago called "Free Willy” that was about a whale named Willy that people were wanting to free from captivity and get him back to the ocean where his real home was. Well, I’m not a whale and I don’t live in the ocean, but I do look like Willy in the movie, so that’s close enough :) I was sitting in a shelter after being found as a stray. The shelter was not my home, and I didn’t belong there, but there was not a huge drive to get me out. Well, then came a virus and they were wanting to close shelters and get dogs out and into other homes. Here was my chance!!! A plea went out, and Unbreakabull snatched me up! I am 2.4 years old, and I love life!! I get along great with other dogs, but I am not good with cats. I chase them, and I’ve been told that’s not okay for me to do, but I still do it anyway, so I was told no cats in my life. I am a very high energy boy!! I need someone that has a very active lifestyle and wants to be out walking and hiking and doing lots of things other than sitting at home. While I am good at sitting around when I want to, I prefer to be outside doing things. I am getting used to being in a kennel, but I am not a fan of it and will cry, so apartment living might not be a good plan for me if you are going to be gone all day. I love being with people, hanging out on the couch with pillows that are comfy, and playing with my toys. I just returned from an 8 week board and train program, and I did great! I absolutely love the female persuasion of my kind, but they have to be bigger because otherwise I see them as a cat, so no small girls for me. I also like to be the only male dog, so I can’t be with males at all, but I am okay going on walks and meeting them. I just like to be the sole king of my castle. For the person who adopts me, they will receive FREE additional training if they would like from the board and train facility that I went to. It’s in Sturgeon Lake, MN, but they are excellent people there, and I learned so much while I was there. My soul is finally free, and I’m just waiting for the perfect home. So, while I am waiting for my forever home to be found, I will just enjoy the fact that today I am not sleeping on a shelter bed, but a nice comfy one. If you are looking for a handsome, active boy to be your forever friend, please head over and fill out my application. Until I see you, Love Willy (UPDATED 01/01/2021)



Fore more info and pictures visit
https://www.unbreakabull.com/adoptabull

animal.description:
My name is Keats, I'm about 2 years old and a boxer mix about 45-55 pounds. 
I've been let down by so many people, but I'm learning that not all people are bad. See I was found as a stray and although I had a micro-chip, my old family told my rescuer that they no longer wanted me. I'm not sure what I did wrong. I'm a very sweet boy, I LOVE cuddling and I really don't ask for much. 

I'm housebroken and working on kennel training with my foster family. I get along very well with children and other dogs (when properly introduced, and only been tested with a female). 

I’m up to date on vaccinations, neutered and microchipped. I am heartworm positive, but currently undergoing treatment. I'm waiting for a family of my own where I can feel safe and love for the rest of my life. 

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our dogs are healthy, spayed/neutered, vaccinated and on heartworm preventative. They live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. Many have basic obedience skills and all have been temperament tested. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, please visit our website to complete an application: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt
(please note: app cannot be done on a mobile device)

If you have any questions, please email us at adopt@takepawsrescue.org

He does not destroy anything while left alone, completely potty trained, and respects furniture and will lay on his bed beside the couch! He loves everyone- never met a stranger!!! He LOVES kids!! This dog is truly the best addition to anyone's home!

animal.description:
Clint's rescuer, Vida, found him roaming the streets near Wrens, Georgia last September, wearing a Serasta flea collar and already neutered, but no chip and no tags. Nothing is known about his background and who knows what he's endured or how long he was out there all alone, fending for himself.

Clint is currently staying at Graced Kennels in Augusta, Georgia in a huge outside kennel made especially for him and paid for by Vida, who loves him very much but with eight dogs of her own, couldn't keep him. He is such an affectionate, loving, friendly, playful dog and craves a lot of human affection. Clint loves people, is good with kids over age twelve, loves to cuddle but is very reactive towards other dogs and so needs to be in a home with no other pets. He has anxiety most likely from living on the streets and is taking anxiety medication. He gets as much love and attention as possible at the kennel, but it just doesn't compare to a forever home.

He gets lonely and wants nothing more than human interaction and affection. Hands to Paws is concerned about his quality of life and feels that he would be happy and really thrive in a forever home with his special someone, where he can get all of the attention that he so deserves.Clint is microchipped, heartworm negative and on heartworm, flea, and tick prevention.

Imagine how rewarding it would be to give this lonely, beautiful soul a home of his own and the opportunity to become the dog that he's meant to be!

animal.description:
Every once in a while, a special pet comes along that gives more love than you can ever imagine.  That is Dexter!  This 9-11 year- old Lab/Shi Inu mix loves people, is dog-friendly and is a snuggle bug.  Because he is blind (he can see some shadows), he loves being near his human—so if you are looking for a companion pet, he may be the perfect dog for you.  Along with being house-trained, Dexter is crate trained at night.  He loves to chew—but don’t worry!  He only chews on deer/elk antlers and his toys…not yours! With his blindness, Dexter is looking for a family with older children, so he doesn’t accidentally knock them over.  His best environment is a ranch-style home or one with baby gates on stairs.  A fenced yard is best because once he knows his yard, he will love sniffing and exploring to his heart’s content. No swimming pools, please. He does require daily medicine, but he takes it like the champ that he is. 

We hope you will open your heart and home to this wonderful and special dog.  If you are interested, please complete the application at hsuc.org.  His tail is wagging just thinking about his new family!

animal.description:
Moana is a lovey bi-eyed lady who is sweet and a bit mischievous. She is still working on house training (but doing very well with it) and although she can be a little possessive of food/treats/toys, she is not as bad as when she arrived. She’s vocal, gentle when taking treats, and walks well on a leash. She would do better with older kids as she gets excited to play and tends to nip the humans on accident; we're still working on that! She’s absolutely gorgeous and has come a long way since she came into foster care.

If you are interested in pursuing an adoption and you live in Texas , please complete the application (links provided below). The process includes a vet check, calling references and doing a home visit. 

http://www.texassleddogrescue.org/web_documents/tsdr_application.pdf
or
https://www.formstack.com/forms/?1632205-WX2Zb144ZP

Please note the following:
We usually do not facilitate out of state adoptions.  (Exceptions can be discussed but will be based on previous big dog experience and will require same adoption process.)
Children in the home or that visit often must be at least 6 years of age. (Exceptions can be discussed but will be based on previous big dog experience.)
Adoption donation is due at the time of adoption.  Puppies under 1 year are $300. Dogs 1 year to 7 years are $200 and dogs over 7 years are $150.  As this is a donation, it will be non-returnable if dog is returned to rescue.
Dogs are not placed on a "first come, first serve" basis but rather the best home for the dog. 
All dogs placed by TSDR will be:
spayed/neutered
vaccinated for distemper/parvo, rabies, and bordetella
heartworm tested and treated if needed
microchipped
other vetting as deemed needed
New owners will receive copies of all available vet information and must agree to keep them current on all of the above.

animal.description:
Please understand, I came from a very large hoarding situation. I am not socialized well with people. I am afraid of a lot of things. I need a home with somebody who is experienced with socializing scared dogs. If done properly, I will trust you. But please do not expect that I will come into your home and respond to love and attention. I do better if crated, left alone and allowed to come out of my shell over time.  I need a home with a privacy fenced yard.  I can be pushy and bossy with some other dogs. 

I am a male Dachshund/Shih Tzu mix. I am about 7 years old and weigh 25 pounds. I am neutered, heartworm negative, current on shots, microchipped and on flea/heartworm prevention. I have also had a dental done a d a negative fecal. My adoption is $250. 

I have never been around children and if frightened or grabbed at, I might bite.

Please email for an adoption application.
We do not adopt out of state.
Due to many bounced checks, we now require that adoption donations be cash only.  However, if you make a general donation to the organization (not associated with the adoption of a pet) we do accept checks and paypal.  If you are unable to adopt right now, won't you please make a donation to help care for the pets?  THANK YOU!!

animal.description:
Courtesy Post – If your looking for an easy guy….don’t overlook Chauncey!

This Southern gem is at the ripe age of 8ish, so all his wild child energy is gone. He is actually mellow and gentle and can be trusted in the house when you leave. And will more than likely be in the exact same spot when you return! …the dog bed or couch all curled up.
He does enjoy the return of his family and will show it by doing a little dance, prancing and whine some, as to say, I’m so happy your home.
He will let you know when he has to go outside to do his business by going to the door.
If your looking to take Chauncey out and about, you will be glad to know, he’s fantastic in the car!
He will harness up by helping.. good on the leash.. and will jump right in your vehicle. At first he’s curious enough to look around, but after a few minutes, he settles right down. So don’t forget he’s in the back seat when you return home!
He can not be trusted off leash. He will chase deer, rabbits and squirrels. And he’s fast!!
He’s fantastic with adults,  strangers and well mannered kids. As you may already know, pitty’s like to be warm, so a spot in the bed would be great, if not a nice warm blanket at night would be appreciated. Will sit and give paw on command.
Chauncey does have one rule, he WANTS  to be the only child. He actually needs to be (including cats) He does have fear aggression.. he is not comfortable around other dogs. Something in his past unfortunately happened and now he is always on edge and does not trust other dogs, sadly. We do not want him wondering if he will have to protect himself when at HOME, where he should feel safe and loved.
So if you are looking for a quiet companion
who knows the house rules already, and will give you sweet kisses.. then this is your guy!

animal.description:
Please contact Sheilah (muttmatchla@aol.com) for more information about this pet.GIGI (female, light brown) & FELIX (male)
It's not often we post two dogs together but we feel strongly about keeping these two together as they are very bonded. Gigi & Felix were owner surrenders to the Lancaster shelter. Why? Because a new baby was on the way! We're not sure how these two are related (mother/son or litter mates) but their previous 'owner' said they had them both since puppies and they have lived together their whole lives. Upon impounding they were separated and would have been euthanized alone but we couldn't let that happen! We reunited them and what a happy day that was. They were so excited to see each other they hugged and kissed each other for hours. At some point we may have to consider separating them in order to find them homes but we are holding out hope that someone sees how bonded they are and be willing to adopt them together.
These two are a unique mix of Shepherd (possibly Malamute) Boxer or possibly Bulldog. We believe Gigi and Felix are approx. 6ish years old. They are a very affection pair, love humans including children although they are fairly energetic, depending upon the children, a home with small children may not be ideal.

ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS & PROCEDURES
Mutt Match L.A. does not adopt out of state nor do we adopt on a first come first serve basis but rather to the home that is best suited for each particular dog and breed. An application, home check, contract and adoption fee are required for all adoptions. All dogs will be, or required to be, spayed/neutered, current on vaccinations and microchipped before adoption. Most of our dogs are from local LA area shelters, we generally have no prior history for them.
Adoption fees vary between $350 - $450 for puppies 8 weeks - 4 years, $300 5 - 8 years and $250 for dogs over 8 years. Adoption fee covers spay/neuter, vaccinations, microchip a wellness check, any additional medical expenses necessary and of course the all the love and daily care we take with each dog before they are adopted.
We believe a well behaved dog is a happy dog and companion. Therefore, we require at least one session with one of our recommended behaviorists for a reduced fee which is not included in the adoption fee.
For additional information or questions, please email us at info@muttmatchla.org. To submit an application, please visit us at www.muttmatchla.org. Mutt Match L.A. is an all volunteer rescue, please allow at least 48 hours for a returned response of all inquires.
Thank you! We look forward to hearing from you soon.

animal.description:
Lexi is almost 2-years-old. She is guessed to be a Black Mouth Cur/Rhodesian Ridgeback mix. She was rescued from a boarding facility with her sister, but they were originally rescued from a rural KY shelter as feral puppies.

Due to lack of socialization, Lexi has many feral-like tendencies. After four months, she will approach her foster mom on occasion, but still does not tolerate being pet. She LOVES the company of other dogs and playing with them is the only time she feels confident. So, she will REQUIRE a playmate.

Lexi does not walk on a leash. In fact, she wriggles and flails in fear. It would not be safe to even attempt to walk her right now. So a fenced yard is REQUIRED.

Lexi is a dog for someone who wants the challenge of making a difference in a dog’s life. The challenge is just giving her time to trust, however long that may be :)

Due to Lexi’s extremely timid behavior, she is only a foster-to-adopt. This means you have to foster her to see and decide if you are able to commit to her forever :) Must be local (NKY/Cincinnati)

animal.description:
Miracle's foster mom says: Recently I’ve been letting her be "loose" in the house. All the other dogs are away and I make her stay near me. Not that I need to tell her, she’s like glue!

She helps me make breakfast. And perches on the back of the couch to help me work. She’s not the best editor...

Today she helped me convert a closet into an office. Making sure to eat any dog food that fell out, pulling things out of the trash I didn’t realize she wanted to eat.

She’s going to be a great only pet dog.

Ps. She’s terrible at laundry since one of her favorite games is to get “lost” under the sheets.
-------------
Miracle is about 8 years old now. She spent most of her life as a backyard dog, and a neighbor said the only attention she got from her people was being yelled at. Miracle needs to be an only pet, and she is ready to be your cuddlebug and comic relief when the world is just too serious and sad.

Adopt Miracle.

animal.description:
Saber is a diamond-in-the-rough. With a little polishing, he will shine! Saber is loving, smart, and eager-to-please. He's also recovering from past abuse. Saber was rescued from the side of a very busy highway. We can only guess how he came to be there, but his fearful behavior indicates he had been abused. With patient, compassionate treatment, he has formed bonds with a few people and is learning to trust new people more quickly. 

This gorgeous boy does well with other gentle dogs, and he's learning to live with cats. He can get possessive about really yummy food, so we're looking for a foster or adopter who will follow a training plan to help him get over that. Saber needs an adults-only home for now, with people who will continue his training and give him all the love and attention he needs.

Please fill out our Adoption application: https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/24333/generic

Someone will reach out to you ASAP to get the approval process started.

animal.description:
Ramon, a.k.a. Ro, is an energetic, approximately 3 year old boy. According to Wisdom Panel, Ro is 50% American Staffordshire Terrier and 50% Border Collie. Ro is approximately 80 pounds, neutered, and up to date on shots. Ro is house trained, crate trained, and knows sit, shake/paw, down, stay and come. 

Ro was saved from an overcrowded shelter just days before being euthanized. Although we don't know much about Ro's past, we know that he is still learning to trust humans and understand that they can be kind and loving. Ro's new family will need to be patient and give him time to adjust to his new surroundings and build trust with them. 

Ro would do best in a calm, dog-savvy home without any small human siblings. That said, he would LOVE to have one or more canine siblings to show him the ropes in his new home. Ro gets along great with other dogs. He has not been cat tested. 

Ro is a smart, silly, sweet boy who will be a loving member of a family that is willing to give him the second chance he deserves. 

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our dogs are healthy, spayed/neutered, vaccinated and on heartworm preventative. They live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. Many have basic obedience skills and all have been temperament tested. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, please visit our website to complete an application: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt
(please note: app cannot be done on a mobile device)

If you have any questions, please email us at adopt@takepawsrescue.org

animal.description:
I’m Clay, I’m 13 and me and my brother were surrendered when our dad became to sick to take care of us…it was the middle of March 2020 in something called a pandemic…I don’t really know what that means, but I hear the humans saying it all the time…
Anyway, more about me: I am about 30-35 pounds and let’s face it, I’m not as young as I used to be…I have these things called cataracts, but I still have a lot of pep in my step, I’m pretty smart, and I know my housetraining, I keep a really clean kennel here, and only do my business when I’m out on a walk.  I know how to sit and give paw and love to cuddle on the couch with my human.  I love my brother Puddles, and thankfully they let us play and live and sleep together here, and when we are on opposite sides of a fence we talk to each other… our worlds have been turned upside down, and I know our dad couldn’t help getting sick, but I miss the comforts of my home and snuggling with dad and Puddles….
Here I’m friendly with all the humans, I love attention and don’t want to share you with those things they call cats…I can share you with my brother of course and maybe even other dogs… I am a little nervous here there is lots of noise and commotion and remember I’m 13, this really wasn’t part of my game plan for my golden years.  I know I’m not as cute as I used to be, I am wondering if you can see past that and see me for the good boy that I am….I’ll be so ever grateful if you take me home with you…and of course if you could by some miracle take both me and PUDDLES together, we promise to be the best pups we know how to be and show you every day how grateful we are that you are giving us a second chance on love and home.  Please remember it’s the season for miracles, and don’t wait too long, remember I’m 13!!!  Love and kisses, Clay

animal.description:
Hello I’m Puddles! 
I am about 9 years old, 45 pounds, people say my pics make me look smaller than I am, so I guess that makes me what they call photogenic, right???
 I was turned into the shelter with my brother Clay at the beginning of this thing the humans are calling a pandemic!  Our human dad got sick and he could not take us out, or feed us, and barely could get out of bed…so one of his friends thought we would be better cared for here. The people here are really nice, but let’s face it, it’s not the home we are used to, we miss our dad, snuggling on the couch that’s the life we knew for our entire lives…
We are house trained, and only go potty when we are being walked…we both keep outstandingly clean kennels, anything else is just not acceptable!!    We try to put on a happy face here, we are very friendly and love all the humans that we meet…however, those little frisky felines are animals that we don’t understand, and we would prefer to go to a new home that didn’t have any of those.  For a while we went to this thing called a college…there were lots of younger grown-ups there and they gave us loads of attention, love, walks it was fun…they had so much energy and kindness to give to us, and I got to be with my little although older bro Clay.  The semester ended and the fun humans had to go home so we are back at the shelter.  Today when we met the woman who is helping us write this, I went straight up on the agility obstacle without being bribed with a treat, and she even took my picture while I was up there!  I know how to sit, give paw and lay down, and lets face it, I like treats…so I’m happy to learn new things for them….hey they are yummy!!  Don’t you like cookies?
I know it’s a real long shot…but if you could find it in your hearts to adopt both of us, it really would be the season of miracles.  Thanks for reading all of this…hope to meet you soon!  Love and but wiggles PUDDLES

animal.description:
Update April 27: Fritz had the test today to see if his eyes were strong enough for the cataract surgery. The test showed that his retinas are not strong enough so he will not be able to have the cataracts removed. Fritz will need to be on 2 eye meds for the rest of his life. (1 morning and 1 evening). He will also have to have his eye pressures checked every other month. Fritz likes to be around his humans. He has some anxiety when he can't hear or smell someone and he thinks he is alone ( like when his foster mom runs to the basement). He also barks when his foster family leaves the house. 
 

Update April 20: Fritz went to the eye vet last week for his cataracts. We started him on daily eye drops and scheduled the test to see if his eyes are strong enough for the surgery to remove his cataracts.

Fritz is a 6 year old miniature poodle that was recently released from a commercial breeding facility. He is a sweetheart that is leaning how much fun it is snuggle and live in a house. He is learning that he likes dog beds but toys and treats will take more time. 

Fritz has 2 mature cataracts. He is blind in one eye and can only see light and dark in the other one. Fritz also has some dental issues and may lose some teeth during his dental. 
 

Fritz and Felipe are not a bonded pair but Felipe helps Fritz get around. Fritz will require a calm fur sibling to help him get around. He will also require a flat home with minimal steps so he won't fall. Fritz will also need a home without small children because sudden movements scare him because he can't see.

Fritz's adoption fee is 300.00 and he will be ready for adoption after his neuter and dental. 


	We are an all-volunteer rescue located in Omaha, Nebraska. All dogs are cared for in volunteer foster homes until they are adopted. We do not have a facility.
	LWDR does not ship or transport dogs.
	Approved out of area adoptions are considered. Adopters must be willing to travel to the Omaha area to complete adoption and take their new family member home as soon as their dog is medically and behaviorally cleared for adoption.

animal.description:
This is Preeya, she is a 4-6-year-old girl that was released from a mill where she spent her whole life breeding puppies. She has been learning the ropes of what fun it is to be a family dog and not a commodity. 
Preeya is now up to date on vaccinations and had her first dental. Unfortunately, during her dental she lost a number of teeth, falling out or needing to be extracted. Preeya will need a soft diet as she finds it difficult to chew a whole meal, but she loves food!
She has also had some issues with spotting, so we had a number of procedures done including a Cat Scan. Preeya also underwent a surgery to repair a bladder bubble and hernia to make sure things were all good inside. She is recovering like a champ!
Currently we are working on potty training and she will go outside on command, but it’s a work in progress! She is potty pad trained and will need those for the times she cannot hold it. A home with little carpet would be best for her to avoid confusion between carpet and pads. 
She is good around other dogs of the same size as her, she does prefer women over men, but she warms up with some quality time spent together. She does need a fenced in yard as well as someone who is home most of the time and also, she will need another dog already in the home to help her adjust and to make sure she's not afraid. Being from a mill, she still has some skittish and shy behavior that will take her awhile to adjust.  If you think she might be the little girl for your home, let us know and we'll arrange a meet and see how things go.

1. A home with someone home most of the day to help her learn. 
2. A home with little to no carpet. 
3. A home with another small dog to help her feel safe.  
4. A home with a fenced in yard. 

All of our dogs are current on vaccinations which include Rabies and Distemper/Parvo, they are spayed and or neutered, have been fecal tested and heartworm tested, and had a dental cleaning if necessary. They are all on heartworm and flea/tick preventative as needed in rescue.

The adoption process is an application, a vet reference, a home inspection, and a lifetime contract. The requested adoption donation for all of our dogs is $300.

We do not REQUIRE a fenced in yard (some dogs do not require a fence, as long as they can walk well on harness and leash. This is decided by what is best for each dog individually.) 

We are willing to adopt out-of-state applicants but you must travel to the Omaha area to meet and travel home with your dog. We do not transport or ship dogs. 

If you are interested in adding this beautiful baby to your loving family, please visit our website and fill out an adoption application at http://www.nebraskadachshundrescue.org/adoptapp.htm 
The Adoption fee is $300.

Audrey is a dominant female, and does well with other dogs who have submissive or tolerant personalities. Audrey did much better around male volunteers this weekend than the last time we met her. Audrey was curious about the cats nearby, but backed away from them once she investigated. Audrey is so deserving of a loving home and TLC.

Audrey is currently in the care of the Vermilion Parish shelter and will be fully vetted updon adoption or placement in a foster home. To adopt or foster, please complete the adoption application at AAVArescue.com

animal.description:
IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING THE FIRST STEP IS TO FILL OUT AN ADOPTION APPLICATION ON OUR WEBSITE AT:  
https://www.caninecastaways.org/adoption-application

IF A PET IS LISTED THEN THEY ARE AVAILABLE - WE KEEP OUR LISTINGS UP TO DATE AND REMOVE AS SOON AS ADOPTED.

NAME:  Apache
BREED:  Chihuahua mix
SEX:  male
COLOR:  white/tan
AGE:  2 yrs as of Feb 2020
WEIGHT:  12 lbs

PERSONALITY PROFILE
FAVORITE ACTIVITY:  playing keep away with toys 
COULDN'T LIVE WITHOUT:  a fenced yard
PET PEEVES:  leashes or anything else going around my neck or over my head
I NEED:   a structured home with rules & boundaries
MY GOAL:  to do things my way
MY MOTTO:  Double dog dare you!

Apache came to us as very scared of the world. It was obvious that he wanted to be friends but just didn't trust people.   He has improved dramatically but it is possible when he moves to a new home he may regress.  There is no doubt that it will take time to readjust to a new place which is not uncommon. Apache is used to us and his surroundings now and is doing great so he just needs someone that understands that it will take time for him to come around and get used to a new environment.   He would do best with a person who has had experience with scared dogs in the past.

Apache requires a home with a fenced yard and probably also a dog about his size. He loves to play but can play a little rough sometimes so a dog a lot smaller than him probably wouldn’t be a good idea. He also needs a home with no children since he can get scared and kids move quickly!

He does have a fear issue with a leash being put over his head so that is why he needs a fenced yard. This is something that could eventually be resolved but it would probably take a while for him to get comfortable with it enough so the best option for him is a fully fenced in yard at this time.

Apache will make a great addition to the right home.



If you are interested in adopting please complete our Adoption Application by copying and pasting the following link into your web browser: http://www.caninecastaways.org/adoption-application

For a full list of dogs we currently have for adoption use this link:  https://www.caninecastaways.org/adoptable-dogs


MEDICAL INFO:


The following has been or will be done for this dog...
- Basic Exam by Veterinarian
- Spayed or Neutered
- Heartworm Tested
- Placed on heartworm preventive
- Basic Bloodwork
- Urinalysis
- Microchipped
- Intestinal Parasite Exam and medication
- Vaccinations
- Placed on Flea preventive


ADOPTION DONATION: $250


This adoption donation helps to cover the vet expenses for this dog including heartworm preventive which is dispensed at the initial vet visit and then goes with the dog at adoption. All vet records will be provided to adopter. 

Visit us at www.caninecastaways.org

Foster Homes Needed!

Do you have time and room in your life for a foster dog?

http://www.muttloverescue.org/foster.html

*****************

Boomer came to Mutts from a rural shelter in NC. The shelter guessed he is about 4 yrs old but he could be older.. He's not telling! Boomer is about 45 lbs. He's a friendly guy and gets along with everyone. Boomer has finished his heartworm treatment and is ready to go on some adventures with a new family!

**BECAUSE OF OUR REQUIREMENT FOR A HOME VISIT, WE ARE ONLY ABLE TO ADOPT TO HOMES IN THE NORTHERN VA / MARYLAND / DC METRO AREA**

We have adoption events EVERY SATURDAY from 12-3 p.m. Please note that not all dogs can attend every event, so if you are interested in meeting a particular dog, please complete a no-obligation application on our website at http://www.muttloverescue.org/application.html OR write to adopt@muttloverescue.org.

Upcoming adoption events:

Mutt Love Rescue is doing everything we can to ensure the health and safety of our volunteers and adopters while continuing our mission to find homes for as many dogs as possible.

Effective immediately, we will not be holding our weekly adoption events. Dogs available for adoption can be met by appointment only. Potential adopters should submit an online application at http://muttloverescue.org/application.html. Once we receive your application, we will contact you to let you know the next steps.

We are always desperate for foster homes, now more than ever. If you are interested in fostering during this difficult time, please complete an application... unless you are a previous adopter/foster, then you can just contact us via phone (703-988-2608) or email (adopt@muttloverescue.org) to tell us which dog you want to foster!

For information on sponsoring this dog, please write to adopt@muttloverescue.org.

WE NEED FOSTER HOMES! FOR MORE INFORMATION, PLEASE EMAIL ADOPT@MUTTLOVERESCUE.ORG.

Visit us on Facebook: https://www.facebook.com/muttloverescue
Follow us on Twitter: @Muttlove_Rescue

animal.description:
** Please read the bio in its entirety before emailing with questions or submitting an application**

DUE TO TIME CONSTRAINTS, MESSAGES ASKING QUESTIONS THAT ARE ANSWERED IN THE BIO WILL NOT RECEIVE A RESPONSE. ALL DOGS LISTED ARE AVAILABLE.

Are you looking for the sweetest pup who loves everyone and will keep you entertained? Meet Bo

He's currently 6 months and over 50 lbs! He's going to be around 70 lbs when he finally stops growing.

He was in a car accident when he was about 9 weeks old, and ended up with a broken leg from it. Bo was in a splint for weeks and was the best patient imaginable. He's all healed up now and it's like nothing ever happened to it! He's the happiest dog and he loves everyone he meets. He really likes to play with other dogs, so a nice, active, younger adult dog friend would be his dream. Cats? He loves them a bit too much and thinks they're chew toys, so he needs a home without them.

Bo loves other dogs but is too rough with the little ones, so is looking for a dog companion closer to his size.

*Bo is UTD on vaccines, is neutered and on monthly flea/tick prevention.

* Must have a medium to large adult dog in the home who is a match with his energy and loves to play

*His adoption fee is $250 ($265 with tax)

* Adopters must live within 2 hours of Florence, KY.

If you have specific needs that aren't addressed in the bio (children in the home, small animals, apartment/condo living, etc) please email to ask if the dog is suitable for the environment before submitting an application. Once the application is submitted, please expect someone to email you with questions and/or provide more information about the dog is we are unsure that the dog may be a good fit.

Most importantly, please be honest! We have many people tell us what they think we want to read, not what's truthful. If there are discrepancies, your application will be denied. It's important for us to place dogs in a home that's suitable. You may be a stellar owner but possibly not a good fit for the dog you were first interested in adopting. We're not trying to offend anyone, we're trying to set everyone up for success. We're a best fit rescue and will verify your vet and personal references.

Adoption Process:

Step 1: Complete a "no obligation" application on our website, www.pawprintsnky.com

Step 2: PawPrints will review the application, verifying Vet and personal references as well as landlord requirements/restrictions (if applicable)

Step 3: IF your application is approved, we will call you to schedule a meet and greet for you to meet the pet.

Step 4: If the meet and greet goes well, we will schedule the home visit.

animal.description:
**SPECIAL NEEDS - EXTREMELY SHY **

Male Border Collie Mix: 50 lbs

Born around May 2016 and arrived at TVR April 23, 2019

Kids: 16 and over Dogs:  Yes, REQUIRED   Cats: Unknown

Linus is a very special boy who will need a patient, quiet, and loving home to help him come out of his shell and gain confidence. In his first couple of years this bashful boy was not often exposed to every day life situations, if at all and perhaps he was even a stray at some point. 

Since arriving at TVR, he has become more confident and secure in his surroundings. He genuinely loves to play with the other dogs and feels much safer in their presence and with a pack. He is becoming more comfortable when interacting with people but it still takes a long time for him warm up to new people. In spite of his fears, he does know how to walk on leash and seems to be reasonably house-trained although accidents can occur during any new and/or stressful situation.

Linus belongs in a home with at least one other dog who is super friendly and confident to take the lead and show him the way. He will benefit from an outgoing counterpart that will help him find his courage. His human can help soothe Linus by brushing him (he loves it) and filling his dog bed with cozy blankets before tucking him into bed. 

We are not 100% sure what incident occurred to make the world an intimidating place for Linus, but we know in our hearts that with the right person by his side and the security of a home he will learn to feel safe and at ease. He will finally be able to take a breath and live a happy peaceful life which he deserves. 

Are you ready to give this sweet, gentle and shy boy the home he has been waiting so patiently for?

*HEARTWORM UPDATE: Linus has completed his heart worm treatment and is ready to go to his new home! It is very important for Linus to be kept on a monthly Heartworm preventative (such as Heartgard Plus) and not miss a dose. Linus will need to be taken to the adopters primary vet in 9 months (approximately June 10th, 2021) to be retested for Heartworm Disease.

Linus is available for adoption through Their Voice Rescue (www.theirvoicerescue.org). If you are interested in Linus, please contact them by email (adopt@theirvoicerescue.org) or by phone (540) 497-3562.
